<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Thursday, March 30, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Volcano Erupts in Northern Japan
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DATE, Japan (AP) -- The Mount Usu volcano erupted Friday, spewing hot rock,
gas and a plume of ash and smoke over the snowy countryside of Japan's
northernmost main island. There were no immediate reports of injury. Experts
monitoring seismic activity had predicted the eruption, and had already
evacuated more than 11,000 residents from homes at its base. Roughly 51,000
people live in this town and two others near the 2,416-foot mountain, 475 miles
north of Tokyo.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian Dad's Visa Attempt Hits Snag
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Elian Gonzalez's father asked for a visa Thursday to come to
the United States and take the boy back to Cuba. The attempt hit a procedural
snag, however, when the State Department told the father's lawyer that
applications must be submitted to the U.S. diplomatic mission in Havana.
Discussions between immigration officials and the boy's Miami relatives,
meanwhile, ended without a resolution. The talks were set to resume Monday. The
Immigration and Naturalization Service had warned that it would revoke Elian's
right to stay in the United States unless the relatives promised to turn him
over if their legal appeals were rejected. But after Thursday's meeting, the INS
pushed back the deadline for a second time to at least Tuesday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
FTC Investigates Yahoo! Practices
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) -- The Federal Trade Commission is investigating
Internet powerhouse Yahoo! Inc. to see whether its consumer information
practices violate federal regulations. The Santa Clara-based company has been
asked to turn over documents to determine if it complied with the FTC's consumer
protection regulation against the use and disclosure of user data, Yahoo!
revealed in its annual report filed with the U.S. Securities and Exchange
Commission on Thursday. The investigation also includes Yahoo!'s acquisition
last year of GeoCities, which helps people set up their own Web sites, the
company said.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
U.N. Targeting Money Laundering
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   GEORGE TOWN, Cayman Islands (AP) -- The United Nations launched a drive
Thursday to enlist secretive offshore havens in the struggle against money
laundering -- appropriately, at a conference set on a tiny island that is the
world's fifth-largest banking center. ''The amounts involved in these financial
scandals have gone beyond what the world community is prepared to tolerate,''
said Pino Arlacchi, a U.N. undersecretary general and executive director of the
Vienna-based U.N. Office for Drug Control and Crime Prevention. The two-day
conference was aimed at getting offshore havens to adhere to a set of banking
regulations laid out by the Paris-based Organization of Economic Cooperation and
Development.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
House Approves $13 Billion Measure
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The House approved a $13 billion measure Thursday for the
Pentagon, Colombia and recovery from Hurricane Floyd after refusing to threaten
European allies with a pullout of U.S. peacekeepers from Kosovo. The Senate
Appropriations Committee plans to write a roughly $6 billion version of the bill
next week, despite long-running opposition by Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott,
R-Miss. But Lott is under growing pressure to reverse himself. The legislation
provides money for popular causes like American soldiers and drug-fighting
overseas and road-building, natural disaster recovery and farmers at home.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Congo Limits Tribunal's Power
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KINSHASA, Congo (AP) -- A military tribunal that has passed hundreds of death
sentences will no longer have blanket authority to try civilians, Congo's
president said following condemnations of the court by the United Nations and
human rights groups. The government is also setting up a committee to review the
court's convictions, according to a statement from President Laurent Kabila. The
tribunal, known as the Military Court of Order, was set up by Kabila to handle
discipline problems within the army after he seized power in 1997. But it has
slowly extended its jurisdiction to non-army matters.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo's main share index fell Friday after an overnight decline
on Wall Street. The Nikkei Stock Average dropped 182.15 points to 20,259.35. In
New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 38.47 to 10,980.25 at Thursday's
finish. The Nasdaq composite index closed at 4,457.89, down 186.78, or 4.0
percent.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Nets Defeat Raptors 107-103
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- A foolish technical foul and an unfortunate
encounter with a rookie ruined Vince Carter's 39-point night, and the Toronto
Raptors lost for the fifth time in six games, 107-103 to the New Jersey Nets on
Thursday night. Carter picked up a technical for halfheartedly throwing the ball
at Scott Burrell after a hard foul with 3:31 left, then had his shot blocked by
rookie Evan Eschmeyer with 35 seconds left. The Nets kept their slim playoff
hopes alive as they pulled within 4{ games of idle Orlando for the final playoff
spot in the East.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by ELIZABETH A. KENNEDY
</SUBHEAD>
