<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 00:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> It's official: Legislature cries 'uncle' on timely budget  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State legislators have approved an emergency
state government spending bill, officially signaling another year
without an on-time budget in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The $2.4 billion emergency appropriations measure approved
Thursday keeps state government afloat between Saturday, when the
2000-01 fiscal year begins, and April 16.
</P>
<P>
   This is the 16th straight year that lawmakers and the governor
have failed to approve a new budget prior to the start of a new
fiscal year.
</P>
<P>
   Though some legislators -- chiefly Assembly Republicans who are
in the minority -- grumbled about another budget failure, both
chambers overwhelmingly approved the emergency spending legislation
before adjourning for the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, lawmakers approved nine emergency spending bills before
finally approving a permanent budget on Aug. 4. That missed by a
matter of hours breaking the record for all-time-longest budget
impasse, set on Aug. 4 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not the way that leads to timely budgets,'' Broome
County Republican Assemblyman Jay Dinga said, urging his colleagues
to vote against the stopgap spending measure.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is just unacceptable,'' Dinga said. ''We have a
responsibility to end this way of doing business. We enable a
process. We enable delay.''
</P>
<P>
   Included in the emergency appropriations bill is $457 million to
pay state employees and fringe benefits, $335 million for Medicaid,
and $226 million for welfare.
</P>
<P>
   Not included is money to pay state lawmakers on April 12, their
next scheduled pay day. Under legislation approved at the end of
1998, lawmakers' pay is suspended when the budget is late. Despite
that penalty, last year's budget delay dragged on for four months.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George Pataki and the chief legislative leaders, Assembly
Speaker Sheldon Silver and Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno, did
meet behind closed doors Thursday trying to move the process along.
It was the first time such a closed-door negotiating session --
previously condemned by Bruno -- has been held on the budget this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''No, we're not there,'' a grim-faced Bruno said on emerging
from Pataki's office late Thursday afternoon. Republican Bruno said
there was still no three-way agreement on how much money was
available to spend.
</P>
<P>
   Possibly adding strain to the negotiations was a fund-raising
letter Pataki has written on behalf of the Conservative Party
urging the defeat of Democratic candidates seeking state
legislative seats this November -- chiefly members of Silver's
Democratic majority in the Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Complaining about ''self-righteous 'limousine liberals,''' the
Republican governor called them ''dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This year, the establishment liberals are pouring millions of
dollars into an anything-goes effort to elect more left-wingers to
the Assembly,'' the governor added.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki broadside comes at a time when he has been trying to
form an alliance with Silver to win approval of a new state budget.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
