<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Commission says lobbying expenses in 1999 broke all records  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The creation of the state's new $9 billion
health care financing system brought out more lobbying money than
any one issue in the history of the state, a new report says.
</P>
<P>
   A hospital workers' union and a hospital association spent more
than $10 million lobbying on the Health Care Reform Act (HCRA),
about five times more than has ever been spent lobbying a single
issue in New York state.
</P>
<P>
   The HCRA spending sent total reported lobbying expenditures to a
record $71.9 million last year, a 30 percent increase over the
previous year, according to the state Lobbying Commission.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the 19th straight year a new spending record had been
set. Such records have only been maintained in New York since 1978.
Commission officials say only California topped New York in such
expenditures, although they didn't have exact figures available for
that state.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lobbying is continuing to be a growth industry in New York,''
said David Grandeau, executive director of the Lobbying Commission.
</P>
<P>
   The new records come only a year after single-issue spending in
Albany broke the $1 million mark for the first time. In 1998, the
New York Life Insurance Company spent $1.82 million on an
unsuccessful attempt to get legislators to overhaul laws governing
how mutual insurance companies can change their corporate status.
</P>
<P>
   And the HCRA spending has started a new arms race in Albany for
lobbyists, where everyone will look at what was spent on that
campaign and try to outdo it for their own issues, good government
groups lamented.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a 'C' word that rules Albany, and it's not 'citizen'
... It's cash,'' said Rachel Leon of Common Cause. Blair Horner of
the New York Public Interest Research Group grumbled: ''Clearly,
the fat cats believe that money talks.''
</P>
<P>
   Grandeau said more of the lobbying money was put into
advertising than ever before.
</P>
<P>
   ''The price tag for communication-driven advocacy campaigns
climbed to $12.2 million in 1999, almost six times more than the
$2.3 million spent in 1998,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Expenses for legislative receptions and ''lobby days'' also
posted a 25 percent increase over last year, growing to $1.5
million from $1.2 million, Grandeau said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the new spending on HCRA, New York's one-of-a-kind
subsidy system to fund cash-shy aspects of the health care
industry, came from the National Health and Human Service Employees
Union Local 1199, the Service Employees International Union and the
Greater New York Hospital Association (GNYHA) group called the
Healthcare Education Project. The $10.1 million the coalition spent
went mostly to advertising and other outreach efforts.
</P>
<P>
   However, that wasn't the only HCRA spending. Another Local 1199
organization also spent another $1.5 million, GNYHA spent $1.2
million on its own, the Healthcare Association of New York state
spent $775,000 and the Emergency Coalition to Save New York's
Healthcare spent $605,120.
</P>
<P>
   Their HCRA spending alone took up five of the top 10 spending
slots on the commission's list for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   With the lobbying commission's figures available, a coalition
including NYPIRG, the state League of Women Voters and the state's
chapter of Common Cause released its annual ''Fat Cats Factor''
list. That combines spending by special interests on lobbying and
on campaign contributions to come up with a unified list of
so-called fat cats.
</P>
<P>
   The joint HCRA effort between 1199/SEIU and the Greater New York
Hospital Association also led that list. Coming in second was the
New York State United Teachers, which led the list in 1997 and
1998.
</P>
<P>
   When it came to the Capitol's most successful lobbying firms,
Wilson, Elser, Moskowitz, Edelman &AMP; Dicker led the way in 1999,
receiving $3.7 million from 58 clients. The firm also was No. 1 in
1998 and 1997, raking in $3 million and $2.8 million respectively
for its Albany lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, Elser's clients include the American Insurance
Association, the state Blue Cross-Blue Shield Association, the
Hotel Association of New York City, Long Island University and the
Niagara Mohawk Power Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
