<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki helping Conservatives raise possible anti-Giuliani money  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- While he has endorsed Rudolph Giuliani's
Senate bid against Hillary Rodham Clinton, Gov. George Pataki is
helping the Conservative Party raise money that could help finance
a vote-splitting alternative candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In a fund-raising letter, obtained Thursday by The Associated
Press, the Republican governor asks for donations to the
Conservatives ''so they can fight Hillary Clinton's $25 million
campaign machine.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We must redouble our efforts to put more conservatives in
Albany and keep Hillary Rodham Clinton OUT of the Senate,'' Pataki
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Party Chairman Michael Long is actively courting
potential Giuliani alternatives and most political experts believe
a separate Conservative Party candidate could drain votes away from
New York City's Republican mayor and help elect Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican running for statewide office has won in New York
since 1974 without the support of the small, but politically
influential Conservative Party. It provided Pataki with the margin
of victory in his defeat of then-Gov. Mario Cuomo in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   There was no comment on the letter from the Giuliani campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's letter surfaced as Giuliani reported raising a whopping
$7 million and Clinton reported taking in more than $4 million
during the first quarter of this year. That brought the mayor's
total to $19 million since he began raising funds a year ago for
the Senate race. Clinton, who began raising funds in July, saw her
total top $12 million in what is expected to become the most
expensive Senate race in the nation's history.
</P>
<P>
   Relations have been chilly, at best, between the governor and
the mayor since 1994 when Giuliani crossed party lines to back
Cuomo against Pataki. Pataki endorsed Giuliani's Senate bid last
year only after national and state party leaders appealed to the
governor to do so in the name of party unity.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon said Thursday that the governor
has been sending such fund-raising letters to help the Conservative
Party ever since he became governor.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a letter that is designed to help the Conservative
Party which has helped the governor,'' McKeon said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the possibility that helping the Conservative Party
run a strong, separate Senate candidate could help elect Clinton,
McKeon said, ''We remain hopeful that the mayor will be able to
work out his issues with the Conservative Party and that he'll be
able to run on the Conservative line.''
</P>
<P>
   Long said Thursday, as he has in the past, that while the door
remains open for an appeal by Giuliani for Conservative Party
support, it appears less and less likely the mayor wants it or
would get it.
</P>
<P>
   Long said the stumbling block remains Giuliani's refusal to
support a ban on what critics call ''partial-birth'' abortions. The
mayor, like Clinton, is an abortion rights supporter.
</P>
<P>
   Long has also demanded the mayor not accept backing from the
state's Liberal Party, which has routinely supported Giuliani's
mayoral campaigns. Liberal Party boss Raymond Harding is one of
Giuliani's closest political advisers.
</P>
<P>
   Long said earlier this week that he has been in discussions with
leaders of the anti-abortion Right to Life Party and the Ross
Perot-inspired Independence Party about fielding a fusion
third-party candidate to oppose Clinton and Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   While the Conservative Party chief said he knew a third-party
contender could help elect Clinton, he maintained that ''if we do
run a separate candidate, we will be running a candidate with the
express purpose of trying to get that candidate elected. We have
the capability of making this a competitive three-way race.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Pataki's letter, Long said: ''We are united in being
against Hillary. I guess there is a difference of opinion
developing between us over Rudy Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   Third-party support can be crucial in close New York elections.
Unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates to also
collect votes on third-party ballot lines.
</P>
<P>
   Several anti-abortion Republicans, including Operation Rescue
founder Randall Terry and former U.S. Rep. Joseph DioGuardi of
Westchester County, are considering entering the Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   Long said he expected at least one viable Giuliani alternative
to announce for the Senate by the end of April. The Conservative
Party chairman refused to identify the potential candidate, but
said he believed it was a person who could win the backing of both
the Conservative and Right to Life parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
