<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush to headline Conservative Party dinner  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, AP Political Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Expected Republican presidential nominee
George W. Bush has agreed to speak at the annual dinner of the New
York Conservative Party, the head of the influential third party
says.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Party Chairman Michael Long said Bush's decision to
speak at the New York City event on May 17 was ''a clear signal''
that the Texas governor's presidential campaign isn't writing off
the heavily Democratic state for November, at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Many political analysts have said they do not expect the GOP to
contest New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's clear to me the governor and his campaign have not made
up their minds to walk away from New York,'' Long said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican presidential candidate has carried New York, where
Democrats outnumber Republicans by a 5-3 margin, since Ronald
Reagan pulled it off in 1980 and 1984. Reagan courted New York's
Conservative Party early on, speaking at its annual dinner in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's possible to do it again,'' Long said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our people aren't going to sit on their hands in this race,''
Long added. ''They don't want (Democrat) Al Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has not been officially endorsed by the Conservative
Party, Long said he expected the Texas governor would easily win
the party's backing.
</P>
<P>
   Long said Bush's appearance at the $500-a-person dinner would
not only help him in New York, but because of media coverage
spilling into neighboring Connecticut and New Jersey, those states
as well.
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki is expected to attend the
Conservative Party dinner, as he usually does.
</P>
<P>
   Not on the invitation list is New York City Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, the Republican running for the U.S. Senate against
Hillary Rodham Clinton. Giuliani, who has had Liberal Party backing
in his mayoral campaigns, has never been invited to the annual
Conservative Party dinner. Long has been looking for a
Giuliani-Clinton alternative to run for the Senate on the
Conservative Party line.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, third party support can be important in close races
because unlike other states, New York allows major party candidates
to add the votes from minor party ballot lines to their totals.
Pataki won the 1994 governor's race over Democratic incumbent Mario
Cuomo on the strength of the vote on the Conservative Party line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
