<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Icahn Seeks 31 Pct. Nabisco Stake  </HEADLINE>
By SKIP WOLLENBERG, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Will it be different this time for Carl Icahn
and Nabisco?
</P>
<P>
   One of the 1980's most daring corporate raiders is prepared to
make a $1.3 billion cash tender offer for roughly 31 percent of
Nabisco Group Holdings Corp., saying it would increase his chances
for electing his nominees to the board which in turn would make
selling the company its first priority.
</P>
<P>
   The plans Icahn outlined in a letter Thursday represent his most
ambitious effort yet to gain control of the company that was
created when RJR Nabisco Holdings spun off its cigarette holdings
in the face of mounting legal challenges to tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   He already owns 8.9 percent of Nabisco Group stock. He had
previously backed three failed proxy fights for control of the RJR
Nabisco board.
</P>
<P>
   Nabisco Group Holdings' sole asset is an 80.5 percent stake in
Nabisco Holdings Corp., the food company that makes Ritz crackers,
Oreo cookies and Planters nuts.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement from its headquarters in Parsippany, N.J.,
Nabisco Group said its board would review Icahn's proposal and
urged shareholders to take no action in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn said Thursday he was prepared to start a tender offer on
Tuesday of $13 a share for a total of 100 million shares of Nabisco
Group provided that the company drops its poison pill provision
adopted earlier this month to discourage unwelcome suitors.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Nabisco Group climbed 26 percent, rising $2.43} to
$11.75 in late trading on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Nabisco board adopted the poison pill, which allows
shareholders to buy more stock at a discount if an unwanted suitor
gets 10 percent of its shares, after Icahn announced he intended to
run a slate of candidates for election to the board.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn described the move Thursday as ''yet another expression of
contempt for stockholders'' by the Nabisco Group board.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Icahn had opposed spinning off the tobacco holdings
and advocated spinning off RJR's food operations instead. Nabisco
Group shares have fallen 54 percent since the tobacco spinoff,
through Wednesday's close, and it is now clear his plan would have
''achieved a far superior result for shareholders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the price of Nabisco Group shares have been
depressed by investor's concerns that smokers or others who may win
big damage claims against tobacco companies may eventually seek
payment from Nabisco Group because its predecessor RJR Nabisco
owned R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Holdings.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn said in the letter that the clock is ticking on tobacco
litigation, particularly with a jury in Miami considering awarding
damages that ''could result in an appeal bond that is prohibitively
expensive'' for Reynolds and other tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   He said the litigation and other liability issues ''could have a
very adverse effect on tobacco-related companies, their securities
and their appeal to potential buyers in the future'' and added
''now, not later'' is the time to sell Nabisco Group.
</P>
<P>
   He did not identify any potential buyers.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Burry, who follows tobaco stocks for Brown Brothers
Harriman, said Icahn probably feels ''the risk associated with the
litigation factors is not as great as the market fears them to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   ''If he can find way to unlock that value, he is going to do
very well,'' Burry said.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn already owns about 31 million shares of Nabisco Group;
another 100 million shares would give him about 40 percent of its
stock. Nabisco Group had about 325 million shares outstanding at
the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   He said that stake would facilitate election of his nominees for
the board, and said the new board's ''first order of business''
would be to consider the sale of Nabisco Group at a favorable
price.
</P>
<P>
   He set two other conditions for starting the tender offer -- that
Nabisco Group approve his purchase of shares despite a Delaware law
that would otherwise limit him to owning no more than 15 percent of
its shares and setting a new date for the annual meeting so that he
could vote the shares he purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The annual meeting is currently scheduled for May 9.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
