<HEADLINE> Minimum-wage increase reduced for some food servers  </HEADLINE>
By L. ANNE NEWELL, 
o0169nyc--
r n PM-NY--Restaurants-Minim Bjt   03-31 0541
PM-NY--Restaurants-Minimum Wage, Bjt,0575   
Minimum-wage increase reduced for some food servers   
EDS: Moving on news and financial wires   
By L. ANNE NEWELL
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- Labor activists are ''shocked and
surprised'' that some restaurant and tavern workers could see their
minimum wage go up by just 40 cents, and not the 62 additional
cents an hour they expected starting Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   A bill passed by the state Legislature Thursday would set the
state minimum wage for those workers at $3.30 an hour, up from the
$2.90 an hour they have been entitled to, but not the $3.52 an hour
they could have received starting April 1.
</P>
<P>
   The higher raise for tipped workers was originally approved by
the Legislature in December as part of a bill increasing wages for
farm workers.
</P>
<P>
   But the hospitality industry objected to a $3.52 an hour wage.
Restaurant and tavern owners complained that since those workers
are pocketing tips from patrons, their actual wages are well past
the state or federal minimums.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are outraged that the Legislature would choose to take this
amount of money -- 22 cents -- away from the lowest wage earners in
the state,'' said Mario Cilento, a spokesman for the state AFL-CIO.
''They've turned their backs on these hardworking men and women.
It's shocking that they wouldn't take into concern the real needs
of the lowest wage earners in the state.''
</P>
<P>
   Cilento said the workers are now depending on Gov. George Pataki
to take their needs into concern.
</P>
<P>
   A Pataki spokesman said the governor is supportive of the
general goal of the bill, but troubled by some of its minor points,
such as the establishment of a wage board to monitor the workers'
pay.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor's going to look at the specifics of the bill, but
clearly there are unrelated items that are troublesome,'' Charles
Deister said.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly held a sometimes heated debate on the bill, which
the chairwoman of the Assembly's labor committee, Queens Democrat
Catherine Nolan, defended.
</P>
<P>
   Nolan told her colleagues if they did not pass the legislation,
the workers would be unlikely to see any increase. She said since
both chambers have passed the $3.30 legislation, it is likely to
become law.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think $3.30 is a big step forward,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But others strongly disagreed, saying it was unfair of
legislators to take away what had been ''promised'' to workers,
especially two days before the raise would have taken effect.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is probably the most ludicrous thing I've ever seen,''
said David Townsend Jr., a Republican from Oneida County. ''It's
unheard of. When did we ever take money away from anybody? If
someone told you you'd get a raise, you'd expect it to be there.
This is crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Grannis, a Democrat from Manhattan, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this is, if not improper, then immoral,'' he said. ''I
think this is the wrong thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The December farm worker bill increased the state's minimum wage
from $4.25 an hour to the federal minimum wage of $5.15 an hour. It
also mandated any change to the federal minimum wage automatically
apply to the farm worker's state minimum wage -- effectively
abolishing the state's lower minimum wage for those workers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-31-00 0016 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
