<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Parking officials say disabled tags widely abused  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- At least one of every five disabled parking
tags used by Buffalo drivers hangs from the rearview mirror of an
able-bodied driver, City Hall officials estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Not only are those abusing the system -- government employees and
law enforcement officers among them -- squeezing into scarce parking
spaces, they are cheating the city out of meter fees, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The parking tags entitle disabled drivers to park for free so
Buffalo may be losing as much as $300,000 year in parking meter
revenue, according to a report Thursday in The Buffalo News.
</P>
<P>
   Starting Sunday, the state's fine for abusing permits jumps from
$55 to $85.
</P>
<P>
   During a crackdown earlier this month, Buffalo enforcement
officers confiscated more than a dozen permits that were used
illegally. Abusers have been known to forge or steal permits, or
use those issued to an elderly friend or relative or someone who
has died. Still others lie to a doctor who certifies them as
disabled.
</P>
<P>
   John Vertimo, superintendent of parking enforcement, stopped a
woman last week as she stepped from a vehicle displaying a
handicapped parking tag.
</P>
<P>
   ''She said it's her mother's card, and her mother's in a nursing
home,'' he said. ''I told her, 'Ma'am, you're using the card
illegally.'''
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, checks of government records showed the permit
belonged to a West Seneca man who died almost two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's problem is unique in New York, since other large
cities do not offer free parking to holders of disabled passes.
They may reserve spots for handicapped drivers, but the spots
require meters be fed, like the others.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Russell, regional administrator of the Eastern Paralyzed
Veterans Association, favors eliminating or changing Buffalo's
policy because of growing abuse of the passes.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm a quadriplegic -- it's going to hurt me more than others,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Anthony Masiello called the city's free parking policy for
the disabled ''a classic example of government help that goes
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ''To abuse disabled parking is unconscionable,'' he said. ''If
this practice doesn't work ... if people are taking advantage of
it, then obviously we need a thorough review and overhaul.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Schaffner, executive director of the Albany Parking
Authority, said his city uses shorter poles for its meters and
makes a special effort to keep them free of snow in winter so
disabled drivers have no trouble reaching them.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to Buffalo's problem is a lack of coordination among
local governments, officials say.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo has more than 10,450 outstanding passes and towns and
villages have handed out thousands more. But there is no central
registry of permits and no formal procedure for governments to
check on permits issued outside their borders.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard Sciolino, city director of parking enforcement, claims
there are enough abusers in Buffalo alone to completely fill
downtown's 1,500 metered spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are some blocks that don't take in any money ... We can
estimate the city is losing anywhere between $50,000 to $300,000 a
year,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-31-00 0016 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000331.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State regulator says PSC will review Con Ed outage  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The state's utility-regulating board will
begin a formal review of whether Consolidated Edison should be
allowed to pass through costs of its Indian Point 2 nuclear plant
outage to ratepayers.
</P>
<P>
   The chairwoman of the Public Service Commission, Maureen Helmer,
said information about the outage gathered by the Nuclear
Regulatory Commission and her agency shows a ''prudence
investigation'' is warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ''The commission would disallow any costs, including replacement
power costs, that it finds are imprudent,'' Helmer said in a letter
to state Senate Majority Leader Joseph Bruno explaining the
prudence investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Helmer also asked the Senate to back off a bill barring Con Ed
from charging ratepayers for the outage-related costs, saying her
agency has the authority to do the same thing with fewer
complications.
</P>
<P>
   Several legislators requested that the commission review Con
Ed's plans to begin charging its ratepayers for the replacement
costs the company has incurred since Indian Point 2 was knocked off
line Feb. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Gov. George Pataki's office released a report on
the Indian Point outage prepared by several state agencies and the
governor called on Con Ed to be ''held accountable for all
appropriate costs for this incident.''
</P>
<P>
   A leak in a tube at the plant carrying radioactive water
resulted in the release of a minute amount of radioactive steam
into the atmosphere. There was no measurable effect on the
environment and no one was injured, but it resulted in the first
alert in the plant's 26-year history.
</P>
<P>
   There is wide sentiment among state lawmakers in Con Ed's
service territory for a bill prohibiting the utility from passing
along costs of the Indian Point outage to customers. Utility
executives had said they planned to start adding the charges,
estimated at about $3 a month, to customers' bills.
</P>
<P>
   It is costing the utility up to $600,000 a day to buy
electricity to replace that generated at Indian Point 2.
</P>
<P>
   Con Ed critics argue that the company should absorb the costs of
the outage because its executives allegedly knew of impending
problems, but did not move in time to replace the equipment which
failed on Feb. 15.
</P>
<P>
   No date had been set for the start of the prudence hearing, but
Helmer said it should begin as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The state Assembly has already approved the ''no-pass-through''
bill related to the Indian Point 2 outage, but Helmer asked Bruno
not to have his chamber consider it for now.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bill would provide no additional benefits for electric
customers because the law clearly provides for refunds of
unreasonable outage costs'' as determined by the PSC, she said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Helmer said she doubts the legality of the Con Ed
bill, or at least is fairly certain it would be challenged in the
courts if approved by the Legislature and governor. Utilities have
successfully fought similar bills in New York in the past which
single out individual companies on grounds that they were being
denied equal protection rights under the constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Consolidated Edison spokesmen did not return calls seeking
comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In a report called a ''lessons-learned evaluation,'' Ashok
Thadani, director of the NRC's Office of Nuclear Regulatory
Research, said that if Con Ed had done a more thorough job, it
would have been able to predict ''an increased probability of tube
leakage or rupture'' by June 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki administration inquiry into the Indian Point 2 outage
said there were reporting problems from off-site radiation
monitoring sites following the plant leak and ''lapses'' in the way
Con Ed provided information to agencies outside the utility about
the equipment failure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-31-00 0016 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000331.0014 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NYPIRG: More ATMs now levying surcharges  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The number of automated teller machines in
New York that charge non-account holders has nearly tripled in
three years, a consumer advocacy group says.
</P>
<P>
   This year 93 percent of ATMs surveyed by the New York Public
Interest Group have surcharges, up from 33 percent in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   NYPIRG's Russ Haven said Thursday consumers are ''getting
whacked twice'' each time they use an ATM -- once by their banks and
again by ATM operators.
</P>
<P>
   Banks don't usually charge customers who have an account with
them to use their ATMs. But account holders are charged between $1
and $1.50 for using competitors' ATMs, Haven said. On top of that,
ATM operators on average levy a surcharge of $1.33 for each
transaction.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's like putting tolls on both ends of a bridge,'' Haven
said. ''We accept and understand that banks need to make money by
charging an access fee, but two times is too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Haven said 45 percent of the 366 ATMs surveyed were located in
bank premises, going against banks' claims that surcharges are
necessary to cover costs of providing ATMs at remote locations, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Surcharges are also anti-competitive, Haven added, because
larger banks have more outlets. That could drive consumers away
from smaller community banks in favor of larger banks to avoid
paying ATM surcharges.
</P>
<P>
   The NYPIRG report also found that non-bank owners, called
independent service operators, impose some of the highest fees, up
to $2.00 for each transaction.
</P>
<P>
   Assemblywoman Aurelia Greene, a Democrat from the Bronx, is
sponsoring a bill to prohibit ATM owners from surcharging
non-customers, but the measure is opposed by the banking lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Nessa Feddis of the American Bankers Association said that since
a federal ban on ATM fees was lifted in 1996, the number of ATMs
have more than doubled, making it more convenient for consumers.
She said independent service operators account for most of the
growth, installing machines in places like supermarkets, train
stations and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   ''Without surcharges, you wouldn't have a lot of ATMs,'' Feddis
said. ''Most ATMs weren't profitable before the surcharges.''
</P>
<P>
   Haven said legislative action is ''unlikely'' on a state level
and it is up to local municipalities to implement any bans.
</P>
<P>
   He cited New York City -- with the heftiest surcharge average of
about $1.41 -- as an example. In January, City Council Speaker Peter
Vallone introduced legislation that would bar banks from imposing
ATM surcharges on customers from other financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear, however, whether a local government has the
authority to require the elimination of the fees and Vallone had
acknowledged that if the bill is passed, the banking industry will
likely file a lawsuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-31-00 0017 </TRAILER>
