<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bennett founders claim trustee plotted their downfall for his owngain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   UTICA, N.Y. (AP) -- The founders of the bankrupt Bennett Funding
Group blame the former federal Securities and Exchange Commission
chief for their company's demise, and are seeking $5.8 billion in
damages.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Breeden, who directed the U.S. commission during the
Bush administration, ''quarterbacked'' a federal investigation into
their companies as part of a scheme to take over the businesses,
Edmund T. and Kathleen Bennett contend in court papers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to damages, the Bennetts are asking U.S. Bankruptcy
Judge Stephen D. Gerling to remove Breeden from his court-appointed
role as manager of the bankrupt companies. Breeden is responsible
for repaying as much money as possible to investors and creditors
and stands to make millions of dollars as trustee.
</P>
<P>
   The Bennett's accusations come even as their son, Patrick R.
Bennett, appears today in a Manhattan federal courtroom. He faces
up to 30 years in prison after being convicted last year on 49
charges that he used the family companies to cheat investors. He
also must repay $109 million.
</P>
<P>
   Federal authorities accused Bennett and his brother, Michael, of
running one of the largest pyramid schemes ever uncovered through
their Syracuse-based office equipment lease financing businesses.
Prosecutors said the Bennetts cheated as many as 12,000 investors
out of nearly $700 million.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bennett pleaded guilty in 1998 to charges of conspiracy,
obstruction of justice and perjury. He faces a maximum of 15 years
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors did not charge the elder Bennetts in the case.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Bennetts filed their lawsuit Wednesday without the aid
of a lawyer. They said they did not have money to hire an attorney.
</P>
<P>
   The Bennett's complaint came in response to four lawsuits
Breeden filed against them seeking the return of money to the
companies.
</P>
<P>
   The Bennetts were supposed to respond to requests by Breeden for
information not make accusations of their own, said William
Russell, whose law firm works for the trustee. He said the
Bennett's allegations were ''ill-founded'' and ''lacking in any
basis in reality.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The response speaks for itself. This happens to be what the
facts are,'' Edmund Bennett told The Post-Standard of Syracuse from
his home in Ellenton, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   The Bennett's court papers contend Breeden manipulated and
falsified the Bennett companies' books to make the company seem
insolvent. They pointed out that Breeden served as chairman of the
U.S. Securities Exchange Commission until 1993, when the agency
initiated the investigation of fraud at the Bennett companies.
</P>
<P>
   Breeden orchestrated the federal investigation and used his
influence to gain control of their companies, the Bennetts claimed.
</P>
<P>
   The $5.8 billion in damages that the Bennetts asked for is the
same amount Breeden seeks in the lawsuits he has filed against
them, the couple said.
</P>
<P>
   Breeden has not yet seen the Bennett's lawsuit and had no
immediate comment, said attorney Gary Mucci, who is helping handle
the case. The Bennetts have leveled the same accusations previously
and Breeden has denied them.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett Funding was the cornerstone in a small empire that
included hotels, racetrack investments, resort financing and
investments in gambling enterprises. The Securities Exchange
Commission filed a civil complaint against the company in 1996
alleging that the companies cheated investors by selling bogus
leases.
</P>
<P>
   The companies entered bankruptcy the next day. Breeden has said
the Bennett companies owe more than $1 billion to 21,000 creditors.
</P>
<P>
   The trustee has said he expects to collect about $720 million
for creditors by the end of the case. He may ask for up to 3
percent of what he collects, which means he could earn $21.6
million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
