<BODY>
<HEADLINE> SEC May Delay Trading in Decimals  </HEADLINE>
By MARCY GORDON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal regulators' July 3 deadline for U.S.
stock exchanges to begin trading stocks in decimals may be extended
by a few months, the head of the Securities and Exchange Commission
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, SEC Chairman Arthur Levitt told a House
Appropriations subcommittee that he was ''frankly dismayed and
disappointed'' by a request for a delay in starting decimal stock
trading by the brokers' group that operates the Nasdaq Stock
Market. But he told the lawmakers the SEC likely will extend the
deadline for a few months.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to be absolutely certain that our markets are
systemically ready to handle the transition'' to decimals, Levitt
said. As for the length of the expected delay, he said, ''We're
talking about months, not more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   After the hearing, Levitt said the delay could be one or two
months.
</P>
<P>
   The brokers' group, the National Association of Securities
Dealers, recently told the SEC that its computer systems, strained
by record trading volumes, are not ready to handle a switch to
decimals by July 3. The NASD has asked for a delay until next year.
</P>
<P>
   The rival New York Stock Exchange has said its systems are
prepared to meet the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the SEC ordered all the nation's stock exchanges to
begin quoting at least some share prices in dollars and cents by
July 3, requiring them to fully abandon the 200-year-old use of
fractions by year's end. Under the SEC's plan, some stocks are to
begin trading in 5-cent increments, with many possibly trading in
penny increments by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, SEC officials resisted extending the
deadline in response to the NASD's request.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Peterson, a spokesman for the Nasdaq market, had no
immediate comment on Levitt's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the all-electronic market scheduled a news
conference on technology issues today.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say adopting the decimal system would help ordinary
investors by narrowing the difference between a stock's best bid
and asking prices, known as the spread. Spreads typically vary from
12{ cents to 50 cents, an amount that adds up to a sizable profit
for brokers, who take in a percentage based on the size of the
spread.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents argue that a narrower spread will make the markets
more competitive and efficient, increase trading volume and improve
liquidity.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, critics say the narrower spreads in decimal trading
would erode profits, something that could reduce the number of
market makers, the firms which form a market's backbone by
facilitating trading.
</P>
<P>
   In other securities industry developments Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   --In his congressional testimony, Levitt also defended the SEC's
plan to create an automated surveillance system to search the
Internet for investment fraud, which has raised privacy concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC ''has always been mindful of its responsibilities and
restrictions'' regarding privacy, he said, adding that the
surveillance project ''is in no way a new effort to seek out
information.'' SEC investigators now monitor the Internet manually
using computer search engines.
</P>
<P>
   --Houston day trader Fred Moldofsky was arrested on charges of
securities fraud for allegedly posting a fake press release about
Lucent Technologies Inc. on a Yahoo! online message board. In
addition to a criminal complaint, filed by the U.S. attorney for
the Southern District of New York and the U.S. Postal Inspection
Service, the SEC also sued Moldofsky in a civil action seeking an
unspecified fine.
</P>
<P>
   Moldofsky's attorney, Scott Schrader, did not immediately return
a telephone call seeking comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 0019 </TRAILER>
