<HEADLINE> PetroChina Shares Priced Low  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- Shares in PetroChina Inc.'s initial public
offering were priced at the lower end of their expected range,
after opposition from organized labor and human rights activists
appeared to dampen investor interest.
</P>
<P>
   The oil and gas producer, a subsidiary of China's state-run oil
company, sold shares in Hong Kong and New York on Thursday raising
$2.89 billion. The company had hoped to raise as much as $3.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Hong Kong shares were priced at 1.28 Hong Kong dollars (16.4
cents) each, the investment bank Goldman Sachs said Friday. The
shares had been expected to price between 1.23 Hong Kong dollars
and 1.49 Hong Kong dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The American depositary shares, which will trade on the New York
Stock Exchange, were priced at $16.44 each, on the low end of the
company's $15.93 to $19.40 range.
</P>
<P>
   Shares begin trading in New York on April 6 and in Hong Kong
April 7.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions and human rights activists in the United States
have mounted a campaign urging investors, particularly mutual
funds, to stay away from the Chinese oil company. Opponents say the
deal is risky and morally questionable because of Beijing's record
on human rights.
</P>
<P>
   PetroChina's chairman Ma Fucai last weekend dismissed criticism
that the company, or its parent, China's main state-owned oil and
gas company China National Petroleum Corp., violated human rights
in China.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: China National Petroleum Corp. at
http://www.cnpc.com.cn (in Chinese)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
