<HEADLINE> Student claims coaches saw hazing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRUMBULL, Conn. (AP) -- Two Trumbull High School coaches have
been implicated in the hazing of a 15-year-old special education
student by members of the wrestling team.
</P>
<P>
   A team member told police that both the wrestling and basketball
coaches at the school saw the victim hog-tied and did nothing, the
Connecticut Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''Somebody pushed (the victim) into a wall and he was crying,''
the 15-year-old student said in his statement to police. ''Then the
(wrestling) coach came in and saw (the victim) tied up and he
yelled at us for not warming up. He also saw another wrestler tied
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The student said that after practice, the wrestling coach
ordered the team members to put the mats away promptly or ''we
would have to run for what we did to (the victim).''
</P>
<P>
   As the victim, a freshman team member, was being untied, a male
basketball coach walked in, but said the nothing and left, the
student said.
</P>
<P>
   The wrestling coach was identified as Josh Tolk. The basketball
coach was not named.
</P>
<P>
   Tolk, who is not a teacher at the school, could not be reached
for comment Thursday. Calls to the school were referred to
Superintendent Ralph Iassogna, who said he could not discuss the
specifics of the case because the investigation is ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   He said action has been taken against Tolk, but he would not
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, wrestling team captains Daniel R. Scinto Jr., 18;
Jeremy Dommu, 18; and Christopher Ricci, 16, were arraigned in
Bridgeport Superior Court Thursday on charges of assault and
unlawful restraint. They are due back in court April 27.
</P>
<P>
   Eight students were arrested in February and seven expelled in
connection with the hazing. Police say the victim, a student with
learning disabilities, was stuffed inside a locker, slammed into a
wall and sodomized with a plastic knife handle in a series of
attacks that began in December.
</P>
<P>
   The victim suffered a serious knee injury in one incident and is
receiving counseling for emotional trauma.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement to police, the juvenile said that he, too, had
been hog-tied, thrown into a shower and locked in his locker ''a
few times'' during a two-month period. But he never filed a police
report.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was kind of like a ritual,'' the boy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
