<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 00:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yale, NLRB reach settlement in graduate student dispute  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- Yale University and the National Labor
Relations Board have agreed to settle charges that the school
threatened teaching assistants who were involved in a grade strike.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, about 80 members of the student organization refused to
release undergraduate grades in an effort to win union recognition.
Most of them backed down in January 1996 after Yale told them they
would be ineligible to teach the following spring if the strike
continued.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's agreement leaves open the question of whether the
graduate student teaching assistants are employees of the
university under federal labor law.
</P>
<P>
   Yale maintains the teaching assistants are not employees, but
are primarily students who are trying to get their graduate
degrees.
</P>
<P>
   University Provost Alison Richard said the agreement does not
affect Yale's position.
</P>
<P>
   The Graduate Employees and Students Organization claims that
graduate students who teach undergraduate classes should be
recognized as employees. The group's leaders took the ruling as a
sign that they could unionize.
</P>
<P>
   The labor relations board is scheduled to rule soon in a New
York University case on whether graduate teaching assistants are
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems to me the NLRB wasn't going to decide employee status
twice,'' said Rebecca Ruquist, the chairwoman of the Yale graduate
student group.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Yale will post notices around campus that
the National Labor Relations Act gives all employees the right to
form and join unions and bargain collectively.
</P>
<P>
   Yale also agreed not to interfere with or restrain employees
from exercising these rights.
</P>
<P>
   The NLRB case concerned statements made by four faculty members
that unions were inappropriate and that failure to comply with
teaching assistant duties could lead to the loss of teaching jobs
and negative evaluations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-31-00 0042 </TRAILER>
