<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Development supporters push plans despite criticism  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Some state lawmakers are asking whether
the major developers of Adriaen's Landing are putting enough of
their own money into the proposed project.
</P>
<P>
   The riverfront development in Hartford and football stadium in
East Hartford would be built with $455 million in public money and
over $210 million in private funds.
</P>
<P>
   The Waterford Group, the main private developer, has said it
will spend $20 million to build a hotel at Adriaen's Landing. But
Rep. Robert Landino said that isn't enough of a commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ''If they have no business risk, then the state of Connecticut
is on the hook,'' Landino, D-Westbrook, said Thursday during a
public hearing before the Legislature's appropriations and finance
committees.
</P>
<P>
   Waterford developed the Mohegan Sun casino in Montville and
operates hotels in Mystic, New London and Norwich. Wolman
Construction Co., owned Waterford, is building a $38 million
Marriott hotel in Groton. The firm operates 24 properties in eight
states.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Waterford Group expressed the most interest in Adriaen's
Landing,'' said Brendan Fox, executive director of the Capital City
Economic Development Authority, a quasi-public agency that would
own the project along with the state Waterford.
</P>
<P>
   About $355 million of the state money would be bonded for the
project, which includes a 700-room hotel, a convention center,
entertainment and retail space and nearly 400 housing units on
Hartford's waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we're going to bond that much, I could see what's going to
happen with other bonding projects like school construction,'' said
Rep. Anne McDonald, D-Stamford, co-chairwoman of the Finance
Committee. ''There could be a really serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   About 3,400 construction jobs and more than 1,100 permanent jobs
are expected to be created, and supporters say the project will
bring clout to Connecticut's capital city.
</P>
<P>
   ''What you have before you is good for the site, good for the
city ... and good for the state,'' Fox said during a public hearing
before the Legislature's finance and appropriations committees.
</P>
<P>
   The Adriaen's Landing plan has changed since first proposed two
years ago when it expected to revolve around a football stadium for
the New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots backed out of the deal last year, and a contingency
plan to build a domed stadium for the University of Connecticut's
football team went nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   Plans changed again when United Technologies Corp. donated its
75-acre Rentschler Field in East Hartford for the UConn stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The school is upgrading from Division I-AA to Division I-A and
needs at least a 35,000-seat stadium to make the transition.
</P>
<P>
   ''The move to Division I-A is right for UConn, and in my view
right for the state of Connecticut,'' said UConn President Philip
Austin. ''It will support us and help us build on our progress on
many fronts.''
</P>
<P>
   A report by the state's Office of Legislative Research
questioned many facets of the project, including why the apartment
rents at Adriaen's Landing are expected to start at about $1,400.
</P>
<P>
   Fox said private studies show that there is an interest in
high-priced downtown housing.
</P>
<P>
   The report also criticizes the 40,000-seat UConn stadium aspect
of the deal, which would cost the state $90.7 million. It points to
a study that assumes 25,000 fans would attend home games in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why do we need a 40,000-seat stadium for 25,000 fans,'' the
report asks.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement between the state, or ''memorandum of
understanding,'' says the state and UConn will split the money made
by the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ''The MOU has an Alice in Wonderland quality to it,'' the report
says. ''After all, UConn is part of the state. This makes the
elaborate dividing up of revenues from the stadium seem slightly
unreal.''
</P>
<P>
   The General Assembly is expected to decide in April whether to
fund the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-31-00 0043 </TRAILER>
