<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nine Injured in Laos Explosion  </HEADLINE>
By MATTHEW PENNINGTON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) -- An explosion Thursday night at a
restaurant in the Laotian capital injured at least nine people,
eight of them foreign tourists, diplomats and residents said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not immediately clear what caused the blast, a rare
violent incident in the normally placid city of Vientiane.
</P>
<P>
   Three people were seriously injured, including a Briton, a
German and one Laotian. All were taken for treatment to neighboring
Thailand. Six other tourists were treated for cuts and lacerations
at the Australian Embassy Clinic in Vientiane, diplomats said.
</P>
<P>
   Police sealed off the area around the restaurant. Infrastructure
damage was reportedly small.
</P>
<P>
   Two Australian journalists were detained by Laotian authorities
for four hours after filming the damaged restaurant. Their film was
confiscated, a diplomat at the Australian embassy said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The Laotian Foreign Ministry declined to comment on the
explosion. Laos is run by a highly secretive communist government.
</P>
<P>
   Violent crime has been on the upswing in recent years, with
authorities publicizing campaigns against guns and wayward youths.
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Laos has been troubled by guerrilla attacks in
remote central areas of the country. Ethnic Hmong insurgents have
been fighting the communist regime since it took power 25 years ago
but have rarely, if ever, staged attacks in urban areas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
