<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Maryland Close to Gun Lock Law  </HEADLINE>
By SETH HETTENA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) -- Maryland is a few legislative steps away
from becoming the first state in the nation to require built-in
locks on all new handguns. Opponents aren't sitting still.
</P>
<P>
   A National Rifle Association advertisement featuring Gov. Parris
Glendening fumbling to open one of the locks was to begin airing
today statewide, coinciding with a crucial vote before a divided
House committee.
</P>
<P>
   In the commercial, the narrator asks: ''If your family's safety
is threatened, how much time will you have to unlock the firearm
you depend on for protection?''
</P>
<P>
   The ad uses footage from a press conference earlier this month
when Glendening spent nearly two minutes struggling to open a
push-button combination lock on a handgun. His ''childproof gun''
bill would require similar locks on all new handguns sold in the
state, beginning in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Glendening conceded that he should have had some training with
the device before attempting a demonstration, but insisted the
locks themselves are effective.
</P>
<P>
   ''The lock worked perfectly. What didn't work is my knowledge
that I had to release the safety on the gun,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bill has been by far the most controversial piece of
legislation in the 2000 session, which draws to a close in less
than two weeks. The fight is holding up other major items,
including the state budget.
</P>
<P>
   Glendening signaled victory in the seesaw battle Thursday,
saying he had the votes to get his bill over the few hurdles that
remain.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the bill prohibits anyone convicted of a
violent crime as a juvenile from possessing a handgun until age 30
and requires gun manufacturers to provide a ballistic fingerprint
of shell casings of all new guns.
</P>
<P>
   Both President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore have praised
the measure, leading Republicans to accuse the governor, a Democrat
who leaves office in 2003, of advancing a flawed bill to curry
favor with the administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's putting the citizens of this state at huge, huge risk for
own political gain,'' said Delegate Carmen Amedori, one of six
Republican members of the House Judiciary committee, which was
expected to vote on the bill today.
</P>
<P>
   Glendening has attempted to make Maryland a leader in fitting
guns with technology permitting them to be fired only by their
owners. He has compared the effort to the push for air bags, which
followed government regulations imposed on the auto industry.
</P>
<P>
   The bill narrowly emerged from the Senate on Monday after the
governor agreed to drop a far-reaching provision calling for
electronic ''smart gun'' locks capable of recognizing an owner
through a fingerprint.
</P>
<P>
   Even with that concession by the governor, it took rare
parliamentary maneuvering to bypass Senate conservatives and force
the bill to a floor vote.
</P>
<P>
   To guarantee passage before the session ends April 10, the bill
needs to sail as is through the committee and the full House next
week. Any amendments would send the measure back to the Senate,
where opponents might be able to mount a successful filibuster.
</P>
<P>
   Amedori said she is pinning her hopes on voting to attach
anything to the bill, even if she didn't like it, ''if it would
change one comma.''
</P>
<P>
   Some committee members, including supporters of a strong gun
control bill, believe the Senate bill is so vague that a gun safety
would qualify as a locking device. The Maryland Attorney General's
office said this week after a review that a safety lever would not
suffice.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure the bill comes out untouched, the governor admitted he
has made deals with individual legislators, doling out promises of
money for community projects and school construction funding.
</P>
<P>
   ''I will use the full resources of my office to save the lives
of our children,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Synopsis of bill:
http://mlis.state.md.us/2000rs/billfile/HB0279.htmHistory
</P>
<P>
   NRA: http://www.nra.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 0124 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000331.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 01:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ill. Closes Nursing Home  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEXINGTON, Ill. (AP) -- A nursing home was closed amid
allegations that homeless drug addicts terrorized staff and elderly
residents after arriving from Chicago to fill beds at the
financially troubled center.
</P>
<P>
   John Lumpkin, Illinois public health director, said the
suspension of the Lexington Nursing and Rehabilitation Center's
license was necessary because of an ''immediate and serious
threat'' to residents' safety.
</P>
<P>
   The agency closed the home Monday night, moving all 26 residents
elsewhere. The home, which was only half full, received an average
of $75 a day per patient in state and federal reimbursements, the
Chicago Tribune reported. The home's owners had brought the addicts
in.
</P>
<P>
   Health Department spokesman Thomas Schafer said one staff member
was attacked by a drug patient and another worker was injured when
a patient jumped on the worker's back.
</P>
<P>
   In another instance, one of the drug patients tried to slash the
throat of another after they returned from drinking at a bar,
Lexington Police Chief Spencer Johansen said.
</P>
<P>
   Schafer said the home's other residents felt intimidated by the
drug treatment patients, who ranged in age from 21 to 46.
</P>
<P>
   The drug patients told police they had agreed to go to the home
in the quiet town about 100 miles southwest of Chicago after being
promised substance abuse treatment, use of a swimming pool and
horseback riding.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said the patients, who came from a Chicago shelter,
arrived to find no pool, a horse across the street that hadn't been
ridden in years and no drug treatment program.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators have identified the Chicago-area owners of the
nursing home as Richard Benkin, Michael Weis, Joel Gross and Lee
Cotton.
</P>
<P>
   ''The facility intends to contest this matter and adamantly
denies any justification for the department's actions,'' they said
in a statement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 0125 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000331.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 01:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clergy leaves meeting when Safir refuses to apologize for policeshooting  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Police Commissioner Howard Safir's refusal to
apologize for the death of Patrick Dorismond and for releasing his
sealed juvenile record abruptly ended a meeting he had called with
Brooklyn clergy members.
</P>
<P>
   And when Mayor Rudolph Giuliani showed up as a surprise
last-minute guest at Police Headquarters on Thursday, the clergy
members caucused, said they weren't prepared to talk to him, and
left.
</P>
<P>
   ''The police commissioner told me he was having this meeting and
I thought it would be a good thing if I came over and talked to
them,'' Giuliani said. ''When I walked in, they apparently weren't
prepared for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The 11 clergy members -- all part of the Community Action Project
-- were invited by Safir to discuss ways of improving police
relations in the predominantly minority communities of several
Brooklyn neighborhoods. Dorismond, the son of Haitian immigrants,
grew up in East Flatbush, Brooklyn. He was fatally shot by an
undercover police detective during a drug buy-and-bust operation in
Manhattan on March 16.
</P>
<P>
   Dorismond was the fourth unarmed black man fatally shot by
police in the last 13 months. His death has sparked outrage among
minorities, especially when Giuliani authorized Safir to release
Dorismond's sealed juvenile record, just hours after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Public Advocate Mark Green filed papers
seeking a judicial inquiry into how Giuliani and Safir obtained
Dorismond's records and whether they broke the law in making them
public. A state judge has ordered Giuliani or his attorneys to
appear in court April 13 to determine whether confidentiality laws
were violated.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the 30-minute meeting began shortly after 5 p.m.
The clergy members first thanked Safir for the NYPD's efforts to
find who has been desecrating religious statues at Brooklyn
Catholic churches. Several pastors whose churches had been
vandalized attended the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   But before any dialogue took place, the clergy members asked
Safir to apologize publicly to Dorismond's family for releasing his
sealed record and for misrepresenting his character.
</P>
<P>
   ''We told him the credibility of our negotiations hinges on his
acceptance to give an apology to mark a new beginning,'' said
Monsignor Guy Sansaricq, pastor of St. Jerome's Catholic Church.
''We certainly expected for him to admit there was some mistakes
made.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Safir said: ''They told me they wanted an apology,
and they wanted an apology by this Sunday for the Dorismond
killing, is the way they described it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I told them I had great sympathy for Mrs. Dorismond. . .I was
perfectly willing to publicly express that sympathy and the empathy
I have with her. . .But I was not prepared to apologize for the
Dorismond incident because all the facts have not come out, and
that we need to wait until the grand jury reviewed all the facts,''
Safir said.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioner's comments were another recent display of a
change in tone from top city officials. Both Safir and Giuliani
have taken a softer tact when discussing the Dorismond shooting.
</P>
<P>
   A senior City Hall aide described the shift as turning the
mayor's volume dial from a ''10'' last week to a ''7'' by the end
of last weekend, and the tone would continue to drop, The New York
Times reported Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said the group agreed to meet again after the grand jury
makes a decision. But clergy members stressed they would only meet
with Safir when he was ready to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Safir acknowledged that race has played a
major role in the deep divide between the NYPD and the minority
communities, adding that he will reach out to citizens to try and
bridge that gap.
</P>
<P>
   A black officers' group agreed there's a race problem in the
city, but said police tactics toward minorities are also to blame
for the disharmony, and that Safir's words are merely cosmetic.
Civil rights activists say his remarks show that Safir believes the
problem lies within the community, not police.
</P>
<P>
   ''He still believes that the Police Department is doing a pretty
good job, except that people misunderstand the police,'' said
Michael Meyers, executive director of the New York Civil Rights
Coalition. ''It's his way of saying there's an anti-police
prejudice out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Safir made his remarks at City Hall, responding to a question on
President Clinton's statement on Wednesday that with better
training and policies, crime can remain low in large cities and
community relations with the police can also improve. Clinton did
not criticize the NYPD or comment on the department's controversial
police shootings in the last 13 months.
</P>
<P>
   Safir said civilian complaints in New York City are the same as
in other large cities.
</P>
<P>
   But then he said: ''Let's face it, if we're all honest, this is
about race, it's something we have to fix, something we have to
talk to each other about. It's less about police than it is about
race.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Eric Adams, co-founder of 100 Blacks in Law Enforcement Who
Care, said he's glad Safir agrees that race plays a major role in
policing.
</P>
<P>
   ''However, it's also about tactics,'' Adams said. ''Our tactics
are flawed because we have failed to take into account the racial
component of our tactics. I think today the commissioner's
statement can only be perceived as cosmetic unless he's willing to
make steps in the right direction to rectify some of the racial
components that prevent us from policing correctly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
