<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Texas day trader arrested for posting phony earnings warning onweb  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A Houston man was held without bail after he was
accused of issuing a bogus press release on the Internet that
prosecutors say managed to devalue communications giant Lucent
Technologies by $7.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Moldofsky, 43, was charged with securities fraud for
allegedly posting a phony earnings warning that caused the value of
the stock of the world's top manufacturer of communications
equipment to fall as much as 3.6 percent from $62.62 to $60.37.
</P>
<P>
   ''This case is the latest example of our commitment to the
speedy investigation and prosecution of those who choose to use the
Internet as the medium through which to commit securities fraud,''
said U.S. Attorney Mary Jo White.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those who seek to deceive the investing public should be
forewarned that the Internet provides no anonymity and offers no
insulation from law enforcement,'' she said in a release.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors alleged Moldofsky used phony names and addresses on
the Internet to hide the truth behind his bogus press release
posted on March 22, the same day he traded 6,000 shares of the
company's stock. Prosecutors blame Moldofsky for causing the stock
to fall $7.1 billion in value.
</P>
<P>
   Moldofsky was arrested at his home early Thursday by U.S. Postal
inspectors. Later in the day, he appeared in U.S. District Court in
Houston, where Assistant U.S. Attorney George Tallichet requested
that he be held without bail as a risk of flight. Moldofsky agreed
to remain in custody until a bail hearing in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   A federal defender assigned to represent Moldofsky in Houston
did not immediately return a telephone message.
</P>
<P>
   The bogus Internet release alleged that the former division of
AT&AMP;T expected its operating results for its second fiscal quarter
of 2000 to be lower than analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The fake announcement was made at a time when companies
typically issue any warnings about their earnings prior to the
actual earnings reports later in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Murray Hill, N.J., company actually had warned
that its earnings would fall short of expectations, causing
analysts to slash estimates and the value of the company's stock to
fall.
</P>
<P>
   In court papers, U.S. Postal Inspector Thomas F.X. Feeney said
the phony posting was made on an electronic bulletin board attached
to the Web site entitled, ''Yahoo? Finance.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeney said a Yahoo user identified as ''hot like wasabe''
posted a message at 6:57 p.m. captioned, ''LUCENT RELEASES EARNINGS
WARNING! DAMN!''
</P>
<P>
   Attached to the message was the phony news release, Feeney said.
</P>
<P>
   Between March 22 and March 23, a user identifying himself with a
screen name that mimicked the name of someone who regularly gives
stock advice on the Internet posted messages such as ''LUCENT
Warns!'' ''We're all doomed tomorrow!'' and ''LUCENT WARNS! I'm
going to cut my throat.'' Each of the messages, he said, allowed
readers to connect to the bogus news release.
</P>
<P>
   Feeney said the wording of the phony news release was similar to
that of a Jan. 6 news release in which Lucent announced that its
first quarter earnings would be lower than analysts' estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Feeney said he eventually tracked down the man who posted the
bogus news release as an American Online user identifying himself
online as ''WALLSTREETWEEK.'' In a home page, Moldofsky said he was
a full-time online stock investor, according to the investigator.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, Moldofsky could face up to 10 years in prison and
a fine of $1 million or twice the gross gain or loss resulting from
the crime.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-31-00 0214 </TRAILER>
