<HEADLINE> Annual Clown Convention in Canada  </HEADLINE>
By TOM COHEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Peering down her bright red nose, Linda Berman --
aka Heart Throb -- stamped a gargantuan shoe to make an important
point about bubble blowing during her seminar at the World Clown
Association annual convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's absolutely no end to the amount of fun,'' she said,
''and you can make a LOT (pause) OF (pause) MONEY.''
</P>
<P>
   Berman was talking about how a clown can use soap bubbles at a
party -- but she could have been talking about the convention
itself: a gathering of practitioners of one of the oldest forms of
entertainment to share secrets on how to keep 'em laughing and make
a profit.
</P>
<P>
   More than 250 clowns, mostly from North America and the United
Kingdom, converged on Toronto's downtown Holiday Inn for the
four-day convention that opened Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Finding the meeting was easy -- just follow the clowns. While
some of the delegates attended sessions in street clothes, others
chose to wear the most recognized tools of their trade: painted
faces, colored wigs, baggy pants and of course, the giant shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Arlene Feen, president of the 4,000-member association, said the
convention offers a lot to those who pay $125 to attend. Seminars
covered everything from storytelling, magic and balloon-making to
clown history and religious-themed performance. Competitions for
balloon-making, makeup, wardrobe and performing skills will be
held.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the camaraderie, it's the educational value, fine-tuning
the skills you already have,'' said Feen, dressed as her
professional alter ego -- Giggles -- in a flowing pink top beneath a
garish striped costume, her face expertly painted and topped by a
metallic blue wig.
</P>
<P>
   A former schoolteacher, she got into clowning 19 years ago out
of disappointment over a performer at her daughter's birthday
party. Now she runs Giggles Entertainment in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.,
handling corporate events for IBM, Marriott, Hewlett-Packard and
others.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a phenomenal occupation. It's taken me all around the
world,'' she said. ''I'm an ambassador of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the seminars focused on the business side of clowning.
</P>
<P>
   Berman, who works out of Pasadena, Calif., gushed to the two
dozen people sitting in chairs around her plastic wading pool about
the benefits of including bubble-making at children's parties.
</P>
<P>
   ''It makes an enormous amount of money from soap, water and
air,'' she said, in full regalia, from purple wig to blue clown
shoes. ''It requires absolutely no skill.''
</P>
<P>
   No skill, maybe, but Berman knows her bubbles. Her lecture notes
provide 12 recipes for bubble water, some including white corn
syrup or glycerin to prevent evaporation in dry conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Bubble implements are everywhere, she told the listeners,
showing how a clothes net and even the plastic holder off a
six-pack make excellent bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   The convention also provides retailers the chance to demonstrate
clowning wares. George Kondiles, 47, of Funny Feet Fashion stood
behind a table of the orthopedically sound clown shoes that can
cost $200 a pair.
</P>
<P>
   ''The shoes are engineered so that every biomechanical motion
that you have when you walk ... works the same,'' said Kondiles, a
certified maker of orthopedic shoes.
</P>
<P>
   ''Clowns are the most giving, the most loving, the most
sharing'' people around, he said. ''I think it's part of the nature
of being a clown. ... When they put on that face, it brings it out
of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Feen said the thrill of performing and the desire to make money
motivates all clowns.
</P>
<P>
   ''But the really good entertainers,'' she added, ''it's from the
heart.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how well a top-notch professional clown does, she rolled
back her billowy sleeve to display a sparkling golden watch.
''Honey, it's a real Rolex.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: International Clown Hall of Fame:
http://www.clownmuseum.org/
</P>
<P>
   Institute of Canadian Clowning: http://www.clowning.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 0219 </TRAILER>
