<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Debate Over Heart of Fragmented LA  </HEADLINE>
By TOM VERDIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- There is no Central Park, Gateway Arch or
Golden Gate Bridge. It sprawls 467 square miles, a third larger
than New York City, but has no single monument that says: ''This is
Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's absence of a core institution or defining symbol --
there's no pro football team, not even a bad one -- is highlighted
by the pending sale of Times Mirror Co. and the proposed sale of
Atlantic Richfield Co.
</P>
<P>
   The two are the last two Fortune 500 companies in the city's
business district, and their imminent flight has stirred debate
over the role and future of the city's downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ''It certainly is much less of a first-class competitor in many
ways than it was a decade ago,'' said Joel Kotkin, a senior fellow
with the Pepperdine Institute for Public Policy.
</P>
<P>
   The Times Mirror and Arco deals come at a time when the region
is remaking itself as a center for trade and technology.
</P>
<P>
   That evolution was demonstrated this week when a Texas company
announced it will refurbish the historic Terminal Annex post office
near downtown into a high-tech village housing up to 50 Internet
companies and as many as 1,000 new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas-based Infomart plans to spend $60 million to convert the
62-year-old building into offices with high-speed transmission
lines attractive to Internet-based companies.
</P>
<P>
   Such change foreshadows a future in which major corporate
headquarters become less relevant to a region that is so culturally
and economically diverse that it doesn't need a central core, said
Sky Dayton, the 28-year-old founder of Earthlink, an Internet
service provider based in Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   Those who say Los Angeles is in danger of becoming a second-rate
metropolis are missing the point, Dayton said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fortune 500s are great, but we're in the middle of an
industrial revolution here that is 20 percent over,'' Dayton said.
''New empires are going to be created, and I think it's kind of
cool to not have these old, monolithic companies here, which just
makes room for us, for all these Internet companies to be
created.''
</P>
<P>
   Other major urban centers fit more easily into the traditional
notion of a big city. Chicago with its downtown Loop or Manhattan
with Times Square and Central Park are the focal points of regional
identity and power.
</P>
<P>
   Not Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ''This city is so large and spread out ... there is no center,''
said Larry Mascari, who for two decades owned downtown's Redwood
House Restaurant and Bar.
</P>
<P>
   It's a phenomenon rooted in history.
</P>
<P>
   When the Pueblo de los Angeles was founded in 1781, it was one
of two focal points of Spanish settlement in Southern California.
The other was the mission at San Gabriel.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Los Angeles is a sprawling matrix of suburbs and
satellite shopping centers, characterized by growing ethnic
populations, all interconnected by a serpentine system of freeways.
</P>
<P>
   Its attractions are far-flung, from the Hollywood sign to the
Coliseum to Disneyland to Universal City to the new Getty Center,
all of which are outside downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Power, wealth and influence radiate from Santa Monica, Beverly
Hills, the San Fernando Valley and Irvine. Even without Arco and
Times Mirror, the region is home to nearly two dozen Fortune 500
companies, including the Walt Disney Co. in Burbank and Pacificare
Health Systems in Santa Ana.
</P>
<P>
   ''What you find is a lot of people viewing the Times and now
Arco going as rather ominous,'' said Jack A. Kyser, chief economist
for the Los Angeles County Economic Development Corp. ''But
downtown is on the verge of a new role. It will not be a
traditional downtown, but it will be the center of a lot of
activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ''For the long run, I think it's going to hurt us,'' said
Nobuyuki Watanabe, who runs a gift shop and jewelry store in the
city's Little Tokyo section. ''If those companies are going to go
away, less people will be working downtown.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   City of Los Angeles: http://ci.la.ca.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 0229 </TRAILER>
