<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ahern Leads The Tradition  </HEADLINE>
By MEL REISNER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. (AP) -- During the 1999 Tradition, Jim Ahern
was conducting a corporate golf outing.
</P>
<P>
   That was early in a Senior PGA rookie season that turned out
well, but not well enough to get invited this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had to go through Monday qualifying, and it's tough,'' Ahern
said Thursday after shooting a 7-under-par 65 in the first round.
''But it can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahern is proof of that. His eight-birdie, one-bogey round tied
his career-best score and sent him into the second round with a
1-stroke lead over Tom Kite and Walter Morgan.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of others were close as the Cochise Course at
Desert Mountain, set up for a major, played tougher than Ahern
could remember.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm pretty long, but it's the longest I've ever seen this
course play. And if you drive it in the rough, you're busy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Nelson was alone in fourth at 68, with Jay Sigel, Bob
Dickson and Vicente Fernandez at 69.
</P>
<P>
   Kite had the second-best round of his rookie season, but other
noted players had problems.
</P>
<P>
   Four-time winner Jack Nicklaus, who designed the course, was
eight shots back in a group that also included two-time Tradition
champion Gil Morgan, defending champion Graham Marsh and Seniors
rookie Lanny Wadkins.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Fleisher, the only player to win two titles this year,
shot 74, and Hale Irwin, who won 21 times in three previous
seasons, continued his 2000 struggles with a 4-over 76.
</P>
<P>
   While others were making headlines on the PGA Tour, Ahern made
the fine print, playing in 60 events from 1973-75 without finishing
higher than ninth.
</P>
<P>
   When he lost his tour card, he considered it a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't belong out there, but I think I belong out here
now,'' he said about his improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Ahern worked as the head pro at the Des Moines Golf and Country
Club, and founded Executive Golf Ltd. in 1985, overseeing 100-guest
outings 8-10 weeks a year.
</P>
<P>
   But he kept his eye on the seniors tour and played in 16 events
last year after he turned 50 in February. He picked his spots, won
the Canada Senior Open and earned $478,963.
</P>
<P>
   This season, he got reacquainted with the blahs -- his best
finish in seven tournaments was a tie for 13th -- until the
Tradition, sponsored by Countrywide.
</P>
<P>
   He birdied the second and third holes with long putts, bogeyed
No. 4, but got it going again on No. 5, where he chipped in from 30
yards. Ahern broke out of a three-way tie with Kite and Morgan with
his last birdie on No. 16.
</P>
<P>
   He drove to the edge of another wash, leaving himself a 92-yard
shot that landed within 12 feet, and finessed the putt into the
cup.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really can't say I'm surprised, because I have been playing
well,'' Ahern said. ''It's nice to have those scores, though. When
those putts don't go in, a day like today is maybe a 69 or 70.''
</P>
<P>
   Kite had three birdies on each side.
</P>
<P>
   ''This was the first round I've had where I haven't made a bogey
in ... forever,'' said the winner of 19 regular tour events. ''I'd
hate to even guess how long it's been.''
</P>
<P>
   Morgan, who didn't play the PGA Tour because of a 20-year Army
career, also made six birdies in a bogey-free round. But he made
all of them on the back nine in an extraordinary surge that
included three putts longer than 15 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's tough for a guy who never won on the regular tour, so
I've got to do it out here,'' Morgan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
