<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Burundi Killers Break Silence  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUJUMBURA, Burundi (AP) -- By his own admission, as an
enthusiastic Tutsi militiaman, Emile had killed enough Hutus to
make him feel uncomfortable around most people.
</P>
<P>
   ''There isn't much I have to say to them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So the strong, quiet 28-year-old with a broad smile and a firm
handshake found friendship with someone who understood his past --
but from the other side of Burundi's civil conflict. Now, he shares
beer, cigarettes and cracks a few jokes with Victor, a disheveled
veteran of the seven-year Hutu rebellion against Burundi's
Tutsi-dominated government.
</P>
<P>
   Like Emile, Victor feels betrayed and used by teachers and
parents who taught them to hate their neighbors and shy away from
possible friends just because they were Hutu or Tutsi.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are hypocrites. They told us to kill and chase away Hutus
or Tutsis, while they stayed together, did business together and
still live together,'' said Emile, who like Victor would not allow
his last name to be used.
</P>
<P>
   The hatred ripping apart this tiny central African nation, best
known for its high-quality tea and coffee, has left more than
200,000 people dead -- both Hutus and Tutsis -- since 1993. In
October of that year, thousands of Hutus took up arms after Tutsi
paratroopers assassinated the country's first democratically
elected president, a Hutu.
</P>
<P>
   When former South African President Nelson Mandela stepped in
last year to mediate peace talks, hopes rose for a political
solution. Proposals include integration of Hutu rebels into the
Tutsi-dominated army and elections to choose a new government.
</P>
<P>
   But news from the northern Tanzanian town of Arusha, where the
negotiations have dragged on for the past 20 months, seem to have
little effect on life in this laid-back capital on Lake Tanganyika.
</P>
<P>
   In Bujumbura, progress is measured not by how many politicians
attend the talks but by the growing number of contacts between
people across the ethnic divide.
</P>
<P>
   ''At the bottom, this war is not about ethnicity, it's straight
interest,'' said Adrian Tuyoga, a founder of Jamaa -- or ''Friends''
in Kiswahili -- a Burundian organization that brings together former
fighters from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Although they share the same language, land and culture, Hutus,
who make up the majority of the 6.5 million Burundians, and Tutsis
remain divided by economic differences and the unofficial
segregation that has developed after so many confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after independence from Belgium in 1962, the Tutsi
minority took over the armed forces following a botched
Hutu-orchestrated coup. Since then, years of massacres of Hutus and
revenge killings of Tutsis are recited like mantras by one side or
another -- 1965, 1971, 1972, 1988, 1993 -- and used against any move
towards rapprochement. Similar massacres have killed hundreds of
thousands of people in Rwanda, Burundi's northern neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ''Look. I didn't profit from any of the killings. I was poor
before, and I am poor now,'' Emile told Victor. ''You're just like
me. They told us to kill, and now we have to pick up the pieces --
not them.''
</P>
<P>
   Since last year, the men have been meeting every day under a
tree behind an unfinished house off the capital's main boulevard,
discussing past wars and the future with a dozen other men, who
like them have abandoned the ranks of the Tutsi army and militia
and the Hutu rebels.
</P>
<P>
   All are unemployed. Many are haunted by visions of killings and
the faces of their victims.
</P>
<P>
   ''Emile killed many Hutus. Most of them intellectuals, but also
women and children. He feels remorse now. All of them do,'' said
Tuyoga.
</P>
<P>
   Playing soccer and drinking beer have strengthened ties between
the two groups. But the young men of Jamaa want more: funds to tell
their story and to encourage their peers to abandon their guns and
machetes and start talking to each other.
</P>
<P>
   After four years fighting for the National Liberation Front, one
of the most active Hutu rebel groups, Victor now says there was
nothing political about swinging a machete at Tutsis he didn't even
know.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was fighting for people in power. The rebel leaders were
staying in Tanzania or Nairobi, occasionally visiting or sending us
weapons. But there was no ideology behind our fight. Just interest
of individuals who told us to kill,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Victor believes he can recruit hundreds of Hutu fighters
still ambushing vehicles, attacking army positions or just hunting
for food and shelter, and get them safely back to civilian life.
</P>
<P>
   ''They need to see there is an alternative,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the group has enjoyed the tacit support of political
leaders and even their families. But unresolved questions of
amnesty and the prosecution of those responsible for the killings
hover.
</P>
<P>
   Victor and Emile grew up next door to each other in what is now
the heavily damaged Kamenge neighborhood, where people have started
returning to rebuild their homes and their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Emile returned to a neighborhood bar for the first time this
month. To the amazement of people dancing to a popular Burundian
tune, he braved his fear and walked in with Victor and other
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, people started coming up to their table. Some offered
drinks, some shook hands, others exchanged words and hugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''We realized we have no problem among ourselves,'' Emile said.
''We have problem with politicians, and we're now able to protect
each other.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 0230 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000331.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 02:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stankowski Leads Bellsouth Classic  </HEADLINE>
By ED SHEARER, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DULUTH, Ga. (AP) -- Paul Stankowski loves Atlanta, for good
reason.
</P>
<P>
   He has only two victories since joining the PGA Tour in 1994,
and one of those came in the BellSouth Classic at the Atlanta
Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   He's back again this week, and although it's on a different
course, Stankowski found himself with a 1-shot lead in the
unfinished first round.
</P>
<P>
   ''I loved Atlanta, a lot of great memories, and I'd like to win
again,'' Stankowski said after shooting a 6-under-par 66 Thursday
on the hilly TPC at Sugarloaf layout.
</P>
<P>
   He finished his round about an hour before play was suspended by
darkness with 39 players still on the course. A suspension of
almost two hours early in the morning because of lightning caused
the field to get backed up throughout the day.
</P>
<P>
   Stankowski said he's probably more comfortable at Sugarloaf than
he was at the Atlanta Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fairways here are very generous, so I don't complain too much
when we play golf courses like Muirfield Village or here,'' he
said. ''I like the place. The golf course is a lot of fun.''
</P>
<P>
   He played a bogey-free round, getting three birdies on each
nine, with half of his birdie putts in the 4-6 foot range to go
with a 25-footer on No. 2, a 15-footer on No. 12 and a 30-footer on
the 13th.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't hit the ball really well,'' he said. ''I struggled
with the driver, but the fairways are so big and there's not a
whole lot of rough. It was one of those days that could have been a
72 in a heartbeat, but I am thankful it was not.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was more like my 'D' game, but it was my 'A' putting game.
I rolled it well. I chipped it well. It was fun to get the ball in
the hole.''
</P>
<P>
   He held his 1-shot advantage over a half-dozen golfers headed by
Phil Mickelson, who won the Buick Invitational earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Mickelson at 67 were Kenny Perry, Blaine McCallister,
Steve Jones, Jay Don Blake and Jean Van de Velde, the French golfer
playing his ninth event in the United States as he prepares for the
Masters next week.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Price headed a group at 68 that also included Gary
Nicklaus, son of Jack Nicklaus. Gary has missed five cuts in nine
tournaments this year, with his best finish a tie for 28th in the
Honda Classic. His round included an eagle 3 on the 541-yard fourth
hole when he chipped in from 40 feet.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was the best ball-striking round I had all year,'' Nicklaus
said. ''I missed only two or three shots all day.''
</P>
<P>
   Also finishing at 68 were Joey Sindelar, Gabriel Hjertstedt,
Dave Stockton Jr., John Huston, Brian Henninger, David Peoples and
Tom Scherrer, who completed his final hole after play was suspended
at 6:59 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion David Duval struggled to a 73. Paul Azinger
led a group of nine at 69, defending Masters champion Jose Maria
Olazabal shot 71 and Justin Leonard 72.
</P>
</TEXT>
