<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 02:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore Team Eyes Governor  </HEADLINE>
By SCOTT LINDLAW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- When Gov. Gray Davis wanted more
federal aid for California public schools last year, he picked up
the phone and called Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   They discussed it again aboard Air Force Two and Gore delivered
a few months later, announcing $129 million in aid to help reduce
class sizes in upper grades in California.
</P>
<P>
   After two decades of friendship, these longtime public servants
have a symbiotic personal and political relationship that has made
Davis an appealing prospective running mate for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But the first-term governor repeatedly has said, in the
strongest possible terms, that he is not interested in the job.
He's even dismissed the vice presidency as a mere advisory role.
</P>
<P>
   The message, however, hasn't sunk in among Gore advisers. Gore
has refused to discuss his selection process, but some of those
close to Gore are open admirers of Davis.
</P>
<P>
   One Democratic strategist with ties to Gore's campaign noted
that Davis' focus on education dovetails with Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   California's 54 electoral votes make it the biggest prize on
Election Day, but the cost of advertising and traveling here is
immense. A Gore-Davis ticket would boost Gore's chances in the
state and allow Gore to channel some of his resources elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   A top-level Gore adviser said he will look for a running mate
who can tip the scales in a state that Republican George W. Bush
must win. Davis could fit the bill, as could Florida Sen. Bob
Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has strengths that would aid the ticket outside
California, Gore aides said. He is Roman Catholic, which could help
Gore in certain Midwestern battleground states.
</P>
<P>
   He has proven appeal among Hispanics, the nation's
fastest-growing ethnic group. And he and Gore could take credit for
putting a Hispanic in the governor's office if a Gore-Davis ticket
was elected. Lt. Gov. Cruz Bustamante, a fellow Democrat, would
automatically become governor.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, 57, is a Vietnam War veteran, which could lend him
commander-in-chief credentials.
</P>
<P>
   He was elected in a 1998 landslide and retains his sky-high
approval ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and Gore also are strikingly similar in background,
outlook and demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   Both are known for dry personalities and plodding styles. Davis
likes to josh that he has recruited Gore as his ''charisma
adviser.''
</P>
<P>
   Both went to law school and to Vietnam. Both marched steadily
through the ranks of government, carving niches as cautious,
moderate ''New Democrats'' who refuse to be outflanked by
Republicans on GOP issues such as crime and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, his first year in office, Davis burnished that
centrist image with an impressive string of achievements.
</P>
<P>
   He gave California the strictest regulations in the nation on
assault weapons and cheap ''Saturday Night Special'' handguns.
</P>
<P>
   Davis took steps to fix the deplorable state of California's
public schools with new plans for high school graduation tests,
special help for poorly performing schools and a new school ranking
system. He gave patients the right to sue their HMOs as part of a
sweeping health care package.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' stock as a prospective running mate could drop if Bush
pairs himself with a woman or minority, Gore aides say. If that
happens, pressure will mount on Gore to pick someone other than a
white male like Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has pledged to turn down the No. 2 slot if it is offered,
but changing his mind could cause political problems. He would be
criticized as fiercely as his Republican predecessor, Pete Wilson,
was for breaking a 1994 promise not to run for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Davis specifically ruled out running for president or vice
president during his gubernatorial campaign, and he has used
uncharacteristically strong language in dampening speculation ever
since.
</P>
<P>
   Asked in a December interview in Washington with The Associated
Press whether he was reconsidering, he said, ''No, exclamation
point.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Every time I come back here, I get down on my hands and knees
and thank the voters of California for electing me governor of
California,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the vice presidency, the former lieutenant governor said:
''If someone wanted to ask me to be vice president, they're
essentially asking me to be an adviser. That's what you are. You
have a wonderful title, and a nice house, but you're an adviser.''
</P>
<P>
   Art Torres, chairman of the California Democratic Party, said
Davis may have a tough time declining the vice president's job if
Gore offers it.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's nobody who places duty and loyalty higher than Gray
Davis, and when a presidential candidate calls and says the country
is calling, when major political leaders call and say it would
provide a winning combination, people need to consider that very
carefully,'' Torres said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
