<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chefs Learn Recipe for TV Success  </HEADLINE>
By RACHEL ZOLL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Louis Ekus, smiling and talking, dips a
spoon into an empty bowl and pretends to drop balls of raw dough on
a tray.
</P>
<P>
   The move is routine in any kitchen, except the ones on
television, where filling a cookie sheet incorrectly or using the
wrong pot could cost you ratings.
</P>
<P>
   ''Remember, those viewers are lost sheep,'' Ekus tells his
students, an audience of about 40. ''Those lost sheep don't think
for one minute they can do this.''
</P>
<P>
   Ekus, a presenter at this week's meeting of the International
Association of Culinary Professionals, teaches on-air tips to chefs
hoping to become the next Julia Child or Emeril Lagasse.
</P>
<P>
   ''(Cooks) think that their show is about the food in front of
them. They forget they're there to entertain,'' said Ekus, who has
trained cooks for shows on the Food Network, Lifetime and other
channels.
</P>
<P>
   One common blunder: offering to share the ''secret'' to cooking,
which Ekus believes is intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   ''Those lost sheep don't think for one minute they can do it.
Let them into the inner sanctum,'' Ekus said, suggesting instead to
say, ''there's no secret'' to cooking a recipe.
</P>
<P>
   The raw dough demonstration teaches the crucial tray-swapping
technique, part of an arsenal of tricks meant to sustain the
illusion that the chef is cooking in front of the TV audience.
</P>
<P>
   The important lessons, according to Ekus, are as much about
rolling with the punches, as rolling out the dough.
</P>
<P>
   He showed a clip of a woman who appeared on a TV show to bake
rhubarb pie only to discover that the host hated rhubarb. He shook
a piece of rhubarb at her while she tried to speak, then, on
camera, held a pie in one hand and chased the producer around the
set.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Ritchie, host of ''Cookin' with Carol'' on cable and local
television in the Dallas area, was doing a segment on cooking with
children, when a boy grabbed an ice cube and started sucking on it,
unaware that a microphone clamped to his shirt was picking up the
sound.
</P>
<P>
   ''It drowned everyone out,'' said Ritchie, who took the class to
learn tips to help her take her show national.
</P>
<P>
   ''Remember to keep your poise. It's OK to laugh at what you're
doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 0241 </TRAILER>
