<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Council Mulls Way To Get Iraq Aid  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- In an effort to get more food and medicine
to Iraq, the Security Council was considering a U.S. resolution to
double the amount Baghdad can spend on spare parts to repair its
ailing oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   Independent experts have said Iraq must rebuild and upgrade its
dilapidated pumping stations to continue exporting crude through
the U.N. oil-for-food program, which lets Baghdad buy humanitarian
goods using proceeds from U.N.-supervised oil sales.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq's oil industry -- its main source of revenue -- was targeted
during the Persian Gulf War and has been decimated by nearly a
decade of sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. oil-for-food program was started in 1996 to provide for
Iraqis suffering under sanctions imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion
of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council agreed in June 1998 to allow Iraq to use
$300 million every six months from oil-for-food proceeds to buy
spare parts for its oil industry.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary-General Kofi Annan and the independent experts
recommended last year that the amount be doubled so the vital
repairs can be made.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution expected to be considered today would allow Iraq
to spend $600 million every six months.
</P>
<P>
   The United States agreed to the measure and sponsored the
resolution after its tough line on Iraq sanctions came under
increasing fire at home and abroad in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy U.S. Ambassador James Cunningham introduced the draft a
week ago during an open debate of the council at which most
ambassadors and Annan himself criticized the U.S. policy.
</P>
<P>
   Primarily, they complained that the United States was paralyzing
repairs on the oil industry by placing more than $1 billion in
contracts for spare parts and other equipment on hold in the U.N.
sanctions committee.
</P>
<P>
   Washington says it has to review the contracts to make sure the
equipment isn't used to help Iraqi President Saddam Hussein rebuild
his weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
