<HEADLINE> Bush Rallies Wisconsin Republicans  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE (AP) -- Forget waiting until fall -- or the summer
political conventions, even. George W. Bush is already rallying
Republicans in the swing state of Wisconsin to ''man the phones,
distribute the literature, stand up and say, 'Let's go get 'em!'''
</P>
<P>
   Today, with a fund-raising luncheon in Green Bay, the
presumptive GOP presidential nominee adds another $50,000 to the
war chest for his seven-month campaign against Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   At a dinner Thursday night benefiting the Waukesha County GOP
outside Milwaukee, Bush asked the state's ground troops to
mobilize. He ridiculed his Democratic rival for traveling to
Wisconsin earlier in the week to unveil new campaign finance reform
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ''The man must think America has amnesia,'' Bush harrumphed to
knowing laughter from the sold-out crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Having staked a claim to two issues Democrats have traditionally
made their own -- Social Security and education -- Bush was
campaigning at a school today for the fourth straight day. And on
Social Security, he said, ''I can't wait for the debate between
somebody who's done nothing for seven years and a campaign who's
willing to lay out a vision that will save and secure Social
Security not only for today but for the years coming down the
road.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign spokesman Doug Hattaway countered that Bush's
tax-cut proposals would leave no money to spend on education or
Social Security or any other program.
</P>
<P>
   ''The real centerpiece of his agenda is an enormous tax cut that
may force him to go back on these promises,'' Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, meanwhile, was spending a quiet day off the campaign trail
today, celebrating his 52nd birthday with his family at home in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, Bush and his vanquished GOP primary opponent,
John McCain, took an important step toward party reconciliation
when their rival camps struck a deal giving Bush six of the
Michigan delegates that McCain won in the state before suspending
his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement allows Michigan Gov. John Engler to attend the
Republican national convention as a delegate for Bush, instead of
for McCain.
</P>
<P>
   In Wisconsin, Bush campaigned with Gov. Tommy Thompson and
looked ahead to the next momentous decision of the campaign:
Selection of a running mate.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter reminded Bush of the open speculation surrounding Bob
Dole's 1996 pick that led Thompson, who was passed over by Dole, to
complain at the time about the indignity of the process.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he had not yet put a strategy in place, but promised
''a quiet effort to screen potential candidates'' by a selection
committee of people who can ''keep their counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There does not need to be a lot of needless leaks, rumors and
gossip,'' Bush said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
