<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NJ Mayor Indicted in Bribery Case  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- When Milton Milan was elected mayor of New
Jersey's poorest city three years ago, he pledged put more police
officers on the streets and crack down on crime.
</P>
<P>
   But authorities say that once he was in office, he committed
several crimes himself, collecting more than $30,000 in bribes and
gifts from contractors and mobsters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Milan put the office of mayor up for sale. Whatever you needed
from him, you could buy from him,'' said U.S. Attorney Robert J.
Cleary.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Milan surrendered to authorities after a 19-count
indictment accused him of accepting cash bribes, vacations,
automobiles and home improvement work from individuals and firms
seeking to do business with the city.
</P>
<P>
   The official charges include mail and wire fraud, extortion and
money laundering, for allegedly handling $65,000 in drug profits.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment also alleges that former mob boss Ralph Natale
and mob associates ''made direct payments of money and other
benefits'' to Milan. Natale has been cooperating with federal
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Milan, a 37-year-old ex-Marine, called the indictment
politically motivated and vowed to be back at work today.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not going to stay down. I'm going to get back up and
fight. I'm going to continue to be mayor of this city,'' Milan said
after being freed on $150,000 bail. He said he was going right back
to work because ''I still have time on the clock.''
</P>
<P>
   Traffic stopped and spectators gawked at the sight of Milan, the
city's first Hispanic mayor, walking to the courthouse to answer
the charges. He is the third mayor of this desperately poor city of
87,000 near Philadelphia to be indicted in the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Milan, a first-term Democrat elected in 1997, had been under
scrutiny by federal authorities in a wide-ranging investigation of
alleged corruption in city government. The indictment charges him
with criminal activity dating to March 1996, three months after he
became a city council member.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney said Milan ''was corrupted from the minute he
set foot in City Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The mayor designed this pay-to-play system for his own selfish
benefit, and the people of this city be damned,'' Cleary said.
</P>
<P>
   Milan's name also was mentioned prominently in the recent
federal trial of two men convicted as leaders of a Camden drug
ring. Several witnesses testified that Milan sold drugs in Camden
in the 1980s and bought several shipments of cocaine before
becoming mayor.
</P>
<P>
   However, Camden County prosecutor's spokesman Greg Reinert said
he knew of no pending drug-related case or investigation involving
Milan.
</P>
<P>
   City Council member Ali Sloan-El, a persistent critic of Milan,
termed the federal indictment ''an embarrassment to this city.''
</P>
<P>
   But Milan said the entire matter was ''a political procedure.
What could not be done politically has been turned into a criminal
procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Milan include mail and wire fraud, extortion
and money laundering. If convicted on all counts, he could be
sentenced to up to more than 100 years in prison and face hundreds
of thousands of dollars in fines.
</P>
<P>
   Milan, however, was concentrating on work. Besides that, he
said: ''I'm scheduled to play a little golf.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   U.S. attorney's press release on the indictment:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.njusao.org/break.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
