<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Approves $13 Billion Measure  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN FRAM, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Supporters of legislation providing $13
billion for drug-fighting efforts in Colombia, peacekeeping in
Kosovo and for disasters at home are hoping that its House approval
will intensify pressure on Trent Lott to bring the bill to the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Lott, R-Miss., says the measure is too expensive and would slow
his chamber's work.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not if I can help it, not in that form,'' the Senate majority
leader said Thursday when asked if he would allow the bill to be
debated.
</P>
<P>
   The House easily adopted the measure Thursday by a 263-146 vote,
with majorities of both parties supporting it. President Clinton
and many senators also favor the measure, which is loaded with
money for popular causes like battling drugs abroad, financing the
military and helping victims of last fall's Hurricane Floyd
recover.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Ted Stevens, R-Alaska,
plans to push a roughly $6 billion version of the measure through
his panel next Tuesday in hopes that it will eventually reach the
full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton praised the House bill and urged swift Senate action.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is vital that Congress avoids delay,'' he said in a
statement issued in New York Thursday. ''The costs of delay are
great.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton complained that the bill did not provide funding for
areas of ''the highest importance,'' including embassy security in
Kosovo and other money for the Kosovo peace effort. At the same
time, it did providing ''unnecessary funding'' for other projects.
He said he hoped the Senate would produce a better version.
</P>
<P>
   Underlining the effort to spark Senate action, Barry McCaffrey,
director of the White House drug policy office, called a reporter
to say money in the bill for combating Colombian coca production
would help ''protect our country from what are essentially 52,000
dead a year.'' That is the number of Americans believed to die
annually from illegal drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Before the House approved the bill, lawmakers voted 219-200 to
kill a bipartisan amendment aimed at pressuring European allies to
contribute hundreds of millions of dollars they have promised to
help rebuild Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Under the provision, if Clinton had not certified by June 1 that
the Europeans were cooperating, he would have been required to
begin a ''safe, orderly and phased withdrawal'' of U.S.
peacekeepers the next day from the war-shattered Yugoslav province.
</P>
<P>
   The language reflected frustration among many lawmakers that
though the United States flew 70 percent of the bombing missions in
last year's war against Yugoslavia, European contributions for
economic, humanitarian and policing aid have lagged behind their
promises.
</P>
<P>
   Rejecting the proposal would ''continue your role as the
enablers of European dependence'' on U.S. defense dollars, said
Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., one of the sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials lobbied hard against the provision.
Defense Secretary William Cohen wrote lawmakers that it was ''in
reality a vehicle to bring about a U.S. withdrawal from Kosovo''
that would ''encourage extremists elements in Kosovo and Belgrade,
who are determined to see NATO's mission in the Balkans fail.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue, however, may not be dead.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman John Warner, R-Va., is
ready to push it in the Senate. And one of its House sponsors, Rep.
John Kasich, R-Ohio, said he might try again, perhaps adding
language letting the president waive its enforcement under some
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   The House also voted 386-28 to add $100 million for local
firefighting agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The bill -- more than twice the $5.5 billion Clinton wanted --
contains $1.7 billion for military equipment and training and other
aid for the Colombian government's battle against drug producers
and their leftist rebel allies, who control the southern part of
the country.
</P>
<P>
   Amid worries that the United States could be ensnared in a civil
war that has already lasted decades, the House voted by voice to
limit the number of American military personnel there to 300.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said privately that the measure, sponsored by Rep. Gene
Taylor, D-Miss., had loopholes and that the Pentagon has no plans
to exceed that figure anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Also included is $9 billion for the Pentagon, including $2
billion for U.S. forces in Kosovo and money for upgrading weapons,
buying fuel and buttressing the military's health-insurance
program.
</P>
<P>
   There is also about $2.2 billion for natural disasters at home,
including more than $300 million that North Carolina lawmakers say
are for that state's costs of rebuilding from last fall's Hurricane
Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: House Appropriations Committee:
http://www.house.gov/appropriations
</P>
<P>
   White House Office of Management and Budget:
http://www.whitehouse.gov/OMB
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
