<HEADLINE> Notorious Mexico Kidnapper Captured  </HEADLINE>
By AMPARO TREJO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Marcos Tinoco seemed a dapper and educated
man -- charming widows and secretaries in the richer neighborhoods
of Mexico's capital.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors said Thursday he used that charm to gather
information on wealthy victims -- most of them Jews -- who were
kidnapped and sometimes had fingers sliced off to force ransom.
</P>
<P>
   Tinoco, 41, was arrested this week while driving in the Polanco
neighborhood of Mexico City. On Thursday the federal attorney
general's office presented him to the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Appearing relatively calm before the flashing lights, Tinoco
asked for silence and then shouted, ''Innocent!''
</P>
<P>
   The head of the attorney general's organized crime unit, Jose
Trinidad Larrieta, said Tinoco was ''one of the most-sought
kidnappers'' and he led ''the most active and dangerous criminal
organization'' of the moment.
</P>
<P>
   Police say Tinoco is suspected of at least 11 kidnappings over
the past 15 months, 10 of them aimed at Jews whose relatives,
employees and acquaintances he would befriend to gather
information.
</P>
<P>
   ''The majority of his kidnappings last only a few hours,''
Larrieta said, calling Tinoco ''the king of the express kidnap.''
</P>
<P>
   But on one occasion, he said, a victim was held for 18 days. A
finger was sliced off and sent to the victim's family to force a
ransom payment.
</P>
<P>
   Ransoms ranged from $38,000 to $650,000, Larrieta said.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper Reforma reported that Tinoco was a fourth-year law
student when he dropped out of school. It said he tried his hand
running jewelry shops in Mexico City and Cancun, but failed.
</P>
<P>
   Quoting from a videotaped interview it said was conducted by
federal police, Reforma said Tinoco described himself as a
teetotaling sportsman who practiced skydiving and karate.
</P>
<P>
   Larrieta said Tinoco used his legal training to intimidate
victims. Kidnappers impersonating federal police would threaten to
frame them on drug charges if they did not offer a payoff.
</P>
<P>
   Tinoco ''created false arrest orders which he showed to his
victims to make them believe there really was a judicial order
against them,'' Larrieta said.
</P>
<P>
   The capture of Tinoco is one in a series of triumphs over famed
kidnapping gangs by federal officials -- though daily newspapers
from around Mexico still often carry reports of new abductions.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic arrest was the August 1998 capture of Daniel
Arizmendi, who was notorious for sending victims' ears to their
families. He is now serving a 50-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Larrieta said police were investigating a possible link between
Tinoco and one of Mexico's most famous drug smugglers, the
now-imprisoned and convicted Hector Palma. He said one of the
victims was held at a house owned by a brother of Palma.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
