<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 03:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New London expansion won't harm giant sequoia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW LONDON, Conn. (AP) -- As the city branches out along its
waterfront, it's taking care not to harm a very special tree.
</P>
<P>
   A 40-foot giant sequoia has been growing at the site of the
former Naval Underwater Sound Laboratory since 1966. The center's
staff planted it then when it was about a foot tall.
</P>
<P>
   The sequoia, a relative of the California redwood, rode east on
an airplane with the lab's former technical director, Harold E.
Nash, and his wife. Their donation was the first ornament planted
next to a memorial to World War II merchant mariners.
</P>
<P>
   The sound lab closed in the 1990s and moved to Newport, Rhode
Island, clearing the way for the city to plan a major development
for the waterfront. The tree will figure heavily in the project,
said Damon Hemmerdinger, the city's director of real estate
development.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a hotel to the waterward side of this tree, and a
condominium complex to its west, said Hemmerdinger.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have been working on how to be sure that both the memorial
and the tree are treated appropriately over time,'' Hemmerdinger
said. ''Rest assured that for the last nine months, or longer,
we've been very aware that there's a tree there that deserves
special attention.''
</P>
<P>
   The sequoia is a cypress tree with reddish bark that, in the
West, grows to great heights with gigantic trunks.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Dreyer, director of the Connecticut College Arboretum,
said he knows of four other giant sequoias in Connecticut and a few
more around New England. New England's largest sequoia, an
82-footer, is in Bristol, R.I. A 65-foot sequoia grows in New
Haven, said Dreyer.
</P>
<P>
   Members of New London Landmarks, a preservation organization,
recently learned of the New London tree and want it and the
merchant marine monument to remain a centerpiece of the expansion,
said member Stephen Hallquist.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is definitely unique,'' Hallquist said. ''It's not
something you find in everybody's neighborhood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-31-00 0303 </TRAILER>
