<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Waterbury Mayor defaulted on student loan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   WATERBURY, Conn. (AP) -- Mayor Philip Giordano defaulted on a
student loan, but agreed to pay back the $6,500 he owed after being
sued by the lender, the Waterbury Republican-American reported
today.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement came one month after Giordano filed a motion in
the case asking Hemar Insurance Co., to specify when he stopped
paying the debt, so he could determine whether the claim ''is
barred by the statute of limitations,'' the paper reported.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Republican-American the mayor at first denied
knowledge of the loan Thursday, but eventually told a reporter that
he ''missed a couple of payments.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the bills are sent to his law office, and that
since he had not stopped by there to pick up his mail in five or
six months, it had slipped his mind. He added that any delinquent
notices or phone messages from the bank regarding the debt would
also be waiting for him.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was an oversight,'' Giordano said. ''I've been paying it
off for years. I am very diligent about paying my bills.''
</P>
<P>
   But according to the lawsuit, the mayor has not made a payment
on the loan since at least July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   David Pite, a New Haven lawyer hired by Hemar to collect the
loan, said he will withdraw the lawsuit in the coming days since
Giordano has agreed to pay the debt's full amount.
</P>
<P>
   The 15-year loan, available to newly graduated law school
students studying to take the bar, was taken out by the mayor in
August 1990, after Giordano completed study at the Thomas M. Cooley
law school in Lansing, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   It carries a variable interest rate, now set at about 8.3
percent. Giordano, who earns roughly $85,000 a year, said his
monthly bill was $48 a month. The company said the mayor defaulted
on $6,521.36 in payments.
</P>
<P>
   Giordano, a Republican, is considering a run for the U.S. Senate
seat held by Democrat Joseph Lieberman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
