<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NASA Workers Satisfied With Jobs  </HEADLINE>
By CONNIE CASS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal workers who help explore space or
protect the environment are among the most satisfied with their
jobs, while those who enforce immigration and food safety rules are
the least happy.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, 60 percent of federal employees say they are very or
somewhat satisfied with their jobs, according to a government
survey released today. That compares with about 62 percent in
similar private sector surveys, federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Just 35 percent said their organization has made a priority of
Vice President Al Gore's seven-year effort to ''reinvent
government'' by encouraging employee innovation.
</P>
<P>
   Only 29 percent said creativity and innovation are rewarded; 49
percent said their opinions count at work.
</P>
<P>
   Almost three-fourths said their agency has goals aimed at
meeting customer expectations, another focus of the reinvention
effort. But less than half -- 43 percent -- said there are
well-defined systems for getting customer feedback and complaints
to the right employees.
</P>
<P>
   ''The government is a large organization and moving this kind of
fundamental change to the level where front-line workers see it in
their daily life is a long-term proposition,'' said Morley
Winograd, director of the National Partnership for Reinventing
Government, which co-sponsored the survey.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that job satisfaction jumped to 84 percent among
workers who said their agency stresses reinvention.
</P>
<P>
   The highest satisfaction scores went to the National Aeronautics
and Space Administration, which has suffered numerous setbacks to
its Mars program, at 78 percent; Environmental Protection Agency,
77; General Services Administration, 75; National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration, 75; the Census Bureau, 72; and Office
of Personnel Management, 72.
</P>
<P>
   In the lowest group were the Immigration and Naturalization
Service, 45 percent; Food Safety and Inspection Service, 49; U.S.
Customs Service, 50; and Occupational Safety and Health
Administration, 52.
</P>
<P>
   Error margins within agencies ranged as high as 9 percentage
points, so scores cannot be ranked accurately.
</P>
<P>
   OPM surveyed 32,265 randomly selected employees, out of 1.4
million federal workers, in September 1999. The overall margin of
error is plus or minus 2 points.
</P>
<P>
   Responses didn't change significantly from the first survey in
1998. Winograd said he was ''disappointed at the pace of
improvement'' but managers were making changes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
