<HEADLINE> Chen Forms New Taiwanese Party  </HEADLINE>
By ANNIE HUANG, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Riding the momentum from his strong
showing, the second-place finisher in Taiwan's presidential
election announced the formation of a new political party today
that could siphon support away from the once-powerful Nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   James Soong, a former top Nationalist official, finished close
behind the winner of last month's vote. His candidacy split the
vote for the Nationalists, ending the party's 51-year rule of
Taiwan and sweeping opposition candidate Chen Shui-bian to power.
</P>
<P>
   Soong said the ''People First Party'' was being formed to keep
''the new social force'' that had emerged in the election campaign
as a voice for reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ''We forged a huge social force that demanded peace, democracy,
social stability and ethnic unity, an immense force that will push
Taiwan to march forward,'' Soong said.
</P>
<P>
   Citing political analysts, Soong said his campaign had forced
the Nationalists to promise reforms and pressured president-elect
Chen to moderate his stance on China.
</P>
<P>
   Chen was a vocal supporter of Taiwanese independence, but
softened his position in the tight campaign. Chen now says he would
only call for a vote on independence if China attacked the island.
</P>
<P>
   Chen won 39 percent of the vote, while Soong received 37
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The formation of the new political party crushed hopes that
Soong might return to the Nationalist Party after President Lee
Teng-hui stepped down as party leader to take responsibility for
the upset.
</P>
<P>
   After Lee's resignation, the Nationalists began restructuring
their hierarchy in an attempt to attract new blood.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the United Daily News, a former Nationalist
Party elder, Hau Pei-tsun, said if Soong and the Nationalist
leaders fail to reconcile, Chen would have a ''100 percent'' chance
of winning the next presidential vote in four years.
</P>
<P>
   Hau, a former premier, was expelled by the Nationalists in 1996
for running against Lee.
</P>
</TEXT>
