<HEADLINE> Senate Candidate Sorry for Remarks  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNION CITY, N.J. (AP) -- U.S. Senate candidate Jon Corzine says
he's of Italian descent and he has the backing of Italian-American
politicians in a state where one out of every four Democrats is,
you guessed it, an Italian-American.
</P>
<P>
   But the former Wall Street executive who is battling former Gov.
Jim Florio for the Democratic nomination is being criticized for
recent remarks that might be considered insulting to Jews -- and
Italians.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, he apologized for offending Italian-Americans who
complained his statements perpetuate the stereotype that they are
involved with organized crime.
</P>
<P>
   ''I never intended to cause embarrassment. I never intended to
offend,'' Corzine said at a news conference where he accepted the
endorsement of the Unite garment workers' union. ''I shouldn't have
said what I am reported to have said, and if I did, I apologize.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, the former chairman of Goldman Sachs, is battling
Florio for the nod to succeed Democratic Sen. Frank Lautenberg, who
is retiring.
</P>
<P>
   With the primary set for June 6, a Quinnipiac College poll
released Wednesday found Corzine trailing Florio 2-to-1, despite
spending $4 million to grab the public's attention.
</P>
<P>
   He's received plenty of publicity this week.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Alfano, chairman of the Italian-American One Voice
Committee, demanded an apology from Corzine for ''ethnic slurs.''
Alfano said Corzine's first offensive remark was made several
months ago, at a Newark restaurant where he was seeking the support
of six prominent Italian-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   After being introduced to a lawyer named David Stein, Corzine
remarked, ''He's not Italian, is he? Oh, I guess he's your Jewish
lawyer who is here to get the rest of you out of jail,'' according
to Alfano, who wasn't at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Alfano said the second remark occurred two weeks ago when
Corzine met an Italian-American contractor and quipped: ''Oh, you
make cement shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   Corzine campaign manager Steven Goldstein said the candidate
''never, ever'' uttered the alleged reference to the ''Jewish
lawyer.'' Stein acknowledged he met Corzine in the past six months,
but doesn't recall the comment.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine didn't dispute the remarks about Italian-Americans,
though he said he doesn't remember the exact wording.
</P>
<P>
   Alfano said Thursday that he has not yet decided who to support
in the campaign, but said the Italian-American stereotypes had to
end.
</P>
<P>
   ''This constant barrage of mob movies,'' he said, ''people think
they can say anything to Italians and we're not going to be
offended.''
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of four national Italian-American groups also said
Corzine's comments showed ''both insensitivity and arrogance.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all Italian-Americans denounced Corzine.
</P>
<P>
   He found support Thursday from Italian-American politicians
including U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli, state Assembly Minority
Leader Joseph Doria and more than 20 other Italian-American
politicians who said Corzine's apology was ''sincere and
heartfelt.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Florio, also an Italian-American, he said: ''I am proud
of my background.'' To make ''derogatory stereotypes of whole
classifications of people is at a minimum insensitive and at a
maximum is callously stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Corzine campaign: http://www.VoteCorzine.org
</P>
<P>
   Florio campaign: http://www.FlorioNJ.com
</P>
</TEXT>
