<HEADLINE> HUD to Focus on Predatory Lending  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL SHEPARD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. Barbara Mikulski, who got an earful from
Baltimore residents angry about unscrupulous home lending, quickly
passed along their frustrations to a Senate panel.
</P>
<P>
   The Maryland Democrat asked why predatory lending is becoming a
''virus,'' spreading across the country.
</P>
<P>
   ''The result is the destabilization of neighborhoods. Its
another form of old-fashioned block busting. And it must be
stopped,'' Mikulski said Thursday at a Senate Appropriations
Committee hearing.
</P>
<P>
   In answer, Housing Secretary Andrew Cuomo announced his agency
will propose new laws to fight the discriminatory policies that are
capturing the attention of an increasing number of national
policy-makers.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan decried the
practice for the first time. Comptroller of the Currency John D.
Hawke Jr., who oversees nationally chartered banks, also criticized
the practice in a speech to a community investment group last week.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a national crisis,'' Cuomo said, announcing that a task
force will convene next week and make recommendations to Congress
after two months of study. ''This will be the genesis for national
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   The task force will focus on unscrupulous home lending patterns
in a variety of cities including Baltimore, where Cuomo said some
of the worst abuses occur.
</P>
<P>
   Dubbed predatory lending by its critics, some mortgage and
home-equity loan companies seek low-income borrowers who have a
hard time securing traditional mortgages and charge extraordinarily
high fees and interest.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, consumer finance companies have taken advantage
of people with low incomes or damaged credit histories, many of
them minorities, who cannot get conventional loans and are
desperate to become homeowners or raise cash by borrowing against
their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Another common form of fraud is ''property flipping,'' in which
a property is bought and then resold -- or ''flipped'' -- several
times, each time at a falsely inflated higher price, among a single
group of people.
</P>
<P>
   Also at Thursday's budget hearing, Sen. Christopher S. ''Kit''
Bond, R-Mo., said Cuomo's leadership at the Department of Housing
and Urban Development was to blame for a lack of affordable housing
nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Bond, a frequent critic of HUD leadership, said the agency has
attempted to shift the blame for a lack of low-cost housing to
Congress while HUD hasn't done enough to maintain the housing in
its inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Bond also played video clips of news reports that raised
questions on HUD's performance in maintaining its properties.
</P>
<P>
   Cuomo called the issues raised by the programs as ''long-term
problems'' at the agency and added he didn't disagree with many of
the findings.
</P>
<P>
   ''I do disagree with people who say we haven't made any
progress,'' Cuomo said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Department of Housing and Urban Development:
http://www.hud.gov/news.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
