<HEADLINE> Attorney: Al-Amin Is a Victim  </HEADLINE>
By ASHLEY ESTES, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- A petition filed by attorneys for Jamil
Abdullah Al-Amin claims Georgia officers planted a rifle near the
Alabama field where the former black militant was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   The court papers filed in Montgomery Circuit Court contend
Al-Amin, who changed his name from H. Rap Brown, is the victim of a
conspiracy between corrupt law enforcement officers and organized
crime in Atlanta, where he is accused of fatally shooting a deputy.
</P>
<P>
   The petition, filed Wednesday, also claims Al-Amin was
mistreated during his March 20 arrest in Lowndes County.
</P>
<P>
   The attorneys have said that Al-Amin is the victim of a
conspiracy and is suffering mistreatment, but the court filing
provided some of the first details of their claims.
</P>
<P>
   FBI agents involved in the arrest said the mistreatment claims
were untrue. Georgia authorities have said the conspiracy
allegation is false.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin is charged with murder and aggravated assault in the
March 16 shooting of two Fulton County, Ga., deputies. Deputy Ricky
Kinchen died and Deputy Aldranon English was wounded. The deputies
were attempting to serve Al-Amin with an arrest warrant at his
grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   The warrant was issued after Al-Amin failed to appear in court
on charges of theft by receiving stolen property and impersonating
an officer. Those charges stemmed from an incident last May, in
which Al-Amin was allegedly stopped in a stolen car and flashed a
badge.
</P>
<P>
   In the petition, defense attorney said Al-Amin became a target
after he and others attempted to stop an Atlanta drug and
prostitution ring.
</P>
<P>
   ''Corrupt law officers and organized crime elements ... are
engaged in an unlawful conspiracy to deal drugs and violate young
black women on the Metropolitan Parkway, and they want (Al-Amin)
dead,'' the petition said.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut said Georgia officers planted a rifle found near the
site of Al-Amin's capture. The discovery was made ''only after
Georgia officers visited the scene alone and in two vehicles,'' the
petition said.
</P>
<P>
   It claims planting weapons on black suspects is common in large
cities with a high percentage of blacks.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the FBI in Mobile on Thursday denied the
allegations, but said he couldn't comment further because the
agency would likely respond to the petition in court. Atlanta
police denied comment, saying the petition didn't specifically
accuse them of anything.
</P>
<P>
   Chestnut's petition also criticizes Alabama Gov. Don Siegelman
for signing Al-Amin's extradition papers without investigating the
circumstances surrounding his arrest. Siegelman spokeswoman Carrie
Kurlander said the governor's office followed the law.
</P>
</TEXT>
