<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guard at state prison camp killed in logging accident; trooper enroute crashes, kills woman  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GEORGETOWN, N.Y. (AP) -- A 70-year-old woman was killed when the
car she was riding in was hit by a state trooper, who was
responding to a logging accident that left a state prison guard
dead.
</P>
<P>
   William Lockwood, 72, was making a U-turn on the crest of a hill
when the accident happened Thursday morning about 20 miles from
where the fatal logging accident occurred. The trooper, who was not
identified, was driving with his lights and sirens on, Madison
County deputies said.
</P>
<P>
   The trooper was unable to avoid the Lockwood's car, which was
turning into the path of the trooper's car, deputies said. The
police car hit the side of the Lockwood's station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   Lockwood suffered only minor injuries but his wife, Shirley,
sustained head trauma and internal injuries from the impact. She
was pronounced dead at St. Elizabeth Medical Center in Utica at
12:17 p.m. The trooper was evaluated for foot and hand pain.
</P>
<P>
   The accident is under investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The trooper was on his way to a state wildlife management area
to help investigate the death of Raymond J. Curtis, 53, of Eaton, a
corrections officer who was supervising an eight-member inmate work
crew from nearby Camp Georgetown, a minimum-security prison.
</P>
<P>
   Inmates said Curtis slipped and fell while carrying a log on his
shoulders. Curtis hit his head on a tree stump and the log then
landed on his head.
</P>
<P>
   ''The call came in as an accident but we're not satisfied with
that call until we do a complete investigation,'' Madison County
Undersheriff Doug Bailey said today. ''We're trying to piece this
whole thing together.''
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy was planned, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The inmates were trimming trees and thinning the woods in the
Tioughnioga State Wildlife Management area, about 30 miles
southeast of Syracuse. The accident happened in a ravine about 150
feet from the road.
</P>
<P>
   An inmate called other guards to the area, but Curtis was
pronounced dead at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis had been a guard for 10 years, including the past five at
Camp Georgetown.
</P>
</TEXT>
