<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Up 42.48; Dow Up 4.96  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened higher today as investors searched
for bargains following a harrowing day for technology and Internet
issues on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading, the Nasdaq composite index was up
42.48 at 4,500.37 after skidding nearly 187 points on Thursday. The
Nasdaq, which is dominated by techology issues, is still considered
to be in correction territory, defined as a drop of 10 percent or
more.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 4.96 at 10,985.21. And
the Standard &AMP; Poor's index was up 6.78 at 1,494.70.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to bargain hunting, investors also were reacting to
two economic reports released this morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department reported that personal income rose 0.4
percent in February but that Americans' spending rose more than
twice as fast. That pulled the nation's savings rate down to an
all-time monthly low.
</P>
<P>
   In a second report, orders to U.S. factories were down for the
second straight month, falling a smaller-than-expected 0.8 percent
in February. Orders for airplanes and other transportation
equipment took their biggest plunge in 10 months, dropping 8.9
percent. Industrial machinery orders fell 4.8 percent, the steepest
decline since October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In corporate news, shares of drkoop.com, the online health
information provider, fell 43 percent, or by 2 47/64, to 3 33/64
after auditors questioned the viability of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Net2Phone jumped 11 percent on news an investor group
led by AT&AMP;T is buying a 32 percent stake the provider of cheap
long-distance calls over the Internet. Shares of Net2Phone were up
6] at 61}.
</P>
<P>
   Other big winners in morning trading included Intel, up 4 11/16
at 131 11/16, and Qualcom, up 3 16/64 at 148{.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered declining by almost five to three
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 137.98 million
shares, up from 136.56 million the same time Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of small company stocks was up 3.58 at
535.15.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.51 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.55 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 1.29 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
down 0.13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
