<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 11:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Software Maker Sells Bulk of Co.  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- Policy Management Systems Corp., a maker
of insurance and financial services software, said late Thursday it
had agreed to sell almost all of the company to a New York
investment firm.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh Carson Anderson and Stowe will spend $604 million to buy
between 75 percent and 93 percent of the Blythewood-based company.
</P>
<P>
   Shareholders, who have seen the stock languish between $8 and $9
a share since February can sell their stock for $14 a share or they
can keep it. PMSC shareholders must agree to the deal.
</P>
<P>
   In Friday morning trading on the New York Stock Exchange, the
shares were at $12.37{, up $3.62{, or 41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock traded at more than $50 last year and
shareholders are suing the company because of the lost value.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, PMSC reported a $72 million loss for 1999 because
of write-offs on older software products. It had earned $53.3
million the previous year. Revenues for 1999 were up 6 percent at
$644 million.
</P>
<P>
   PMSC, which had previously said it would change its name to Mynd
to reflect its changing focus to Internet business, has fought
losses, a sharp drop in its stock price and shareholder lawsuits in
the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Company chairman and chief executive Larry Wilson said the deal
is ''the right step at this moment in the company's transition to a
new business model.''
</P>
<P>
   PMSC will remain a public company under current management, the
newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh Carson specializes in buying stock of health care and
information management companies. The investment firm also owns
stakes in the online news service Bridge Information Systems and
the e-commerce company Control Data Systems Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
