<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Up on USDA Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices were sharply
higher in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
</P>
<P>
   The market received a boost from the U.S. Agriculture
Department's quarterly stocks and acreage report, released before
the start of trading.
</P>
<P>
   The government reports wheat stocks total 1.4 billion bushels as
of March 1. Analysts say that is smaller than the market expected.
The USDA also estimates 14.8 million acres of wheat will be planted
this year, down from last year's 15.3 million acres.
</P>
<P>
   The news was a boost to wheat futures prices.
</P>
<P>
   The Agriculture Department's report is considered neutral for
corn futures, yet those prices also rose. There is concern about
inadequate rainfall as the planting of the corn crop gets underway.
</P>
<P>
   Soybean futures soared as the USDA reported soybean stocks
totaled 1.39 billion bushels, lower than analysts estimates of 1.4
billion bushels. Weather concerns also helped lift soybeans higher.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery was 3{ cents higher at $2.59 a bushel;
May corn was 3{ cents higher at $2.36} a bushel; May oats were 2
cents higher a $1.23 a bushel; May soybeans were 10 cents higher at
$5.47{ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle futures prices were higher and pork futures prices were
mixed in trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Live cattle were .05 cent higher at 71.90 cents a pound; April
feeder cattle were .15 cent higher at 83.95 cents a pound; April
lean hogs were .88 cent higher at 64.15 cents a pound; May pork
bellies were .65 cent lower a 96.55 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
