<HEADLINE> Papers Honored for Business Stories  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Four daily newspapers -- The Boston Globe, the
San Jose (Calif.) Mercury News, The Des Moines (Iowa) Register and
The Herald-Sun in Durham, N.C. -- and the weekly Atlanta Business
Chronicle were double winners in the sixth annual Best in Business
contest of the Society of American Business Editors and Writers.
</P>
<P>
   The contest recognizes the best overall publications and
deadline reporting in business journalism during 1999. Winners were
announced on Friday and awards will be presented April 30 at the
Sheraton Colony Square Hotel in Atlanta, during SABEW's Annual
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen daily or weekly publications were named Best in Business
for overall excellence, and eight were recognized with certificates
of merit. Fourteen news organizations were named Best in Business
for spot news coverage which recognizes superior work under tight
deadlines. Six were recognized with honorable mentions.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 246 entries from daily newspapers, business weeklies,
wire services and business news online sites were received,
including 150 stories or story packages in the spot news portion of
the contest.
</P>
<P>
   The Society of American Business Editors and Writers Inc.,
headquartered at the Missouri School of Journalism in Columbia, is
an association of more than 3,000 business journalists in North
America. Formed in 1964 to promote superior coverage of business
and economic events and issues, it is the only business journalism
association for editors and writers.
</P>
