<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 13:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Coke Gets Settlement Offer  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- The Coca-Cola Co. has reportedly received a
detailed settlement offer by plaintiffs in a race discrimination
lawsuit against the soft-drink giant and is preparing its response.
</P>
<P>
   Neither side would discuss the offer which was reported Friday
by The Atlanta Journal-Constitution. The report offered no details
of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the trustee of the New York State Common Retirement
Fund, which owns $370 million in Coke stock, wrote Chairman Doug
Daft that ''this lawsuit has already damaged Coca-Cola's reputation
and its shareholder value.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It is important that you take the steps necessary to halt this
damage and strengthen Coca-Cola's commitment to tolerance and
inclusion in the work place,'' New York Comptroller H. Carl McCall
wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was sent because of McCall's irritation with the
decline of the company's share price by more than 20 percent since
Jan. 1and its inability to end the litigation, McCall spokesman
Jeffrey Gordon said. The fund owns 7.4 million Coke shares.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Ware, the company's highest-ranking black executive, called
McCall on Thursday and scheduled a meeting with him next week in
New York. Coke has a conference with analysts Tuesday in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're always attentive to the concerns of our shareholders,''
Coke spokesman Chuck Reece said.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, the Rev. Jesse Jackson left Atlanta Thursday after
two days of meetings with Coke officials in which he pressed the
company to settle the suit.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, president of the Rainbow/Push Coalition, was joined at
Thursday's meeting by Larry Jones, a former company manager who is
organizing a bus ''ride for justice'' to Coca-Cola's annual meeting
in Delaware on April 19.
</P>
<P>
   The federal suit, filed by eight current and former employees,
claims Atlanta-based Coke has discriminated against blacks in pay,
promotions and performance evaluations. The company has denied the
allegations and is fighting efforts to have the suit declared a
class action, enveloping 2,000 plaintiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Talks with a federal mediator concerning the lawsuit are
scheduled for April 17-18. Daft has said the company is ''working
toward an expedient and equitable resolution'' of the suit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 1312 </TRAILER>
