<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC President Sets Target Prices  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Venezuelan Oil Minister Ali Rodriguez,
who is the new president of OPEC, said Friday that the cartel plans
to maintain a price range of $22 a barrel to $28 a barrel for the
OPEC basket of crudes.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuela's proposal for a price-band system -- frequent supply
changes designed to keep oil prices within a set range -- was
accepted by members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries during their meeting earlier this week in Vienna,
Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez told a news conference that if the basket price moves
outside the target range for 20 consecutive days, OPEC will
increase or decrease production by 500,000 barrels a day until the
price moves back within the stipulated band.
</P>
<P>
   He said the 500,000-barrel output change would be divided among
the member nations based on their individual production quotas.
Venezuela's portion amounts to 11.8 percent or 59,000 barrels a
day, he said.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC keeps watch on prices by calculating the value of a
''basket'' of seven different crude oils. The year-to-date average
basket price is $26.24, which is about the level being bid for
future deliveries.
</P>
<P>
   At midday, crude for delivery in May was priced at $26.67 on the
New York Mercantile Exchange, while front-month Brent crude from
the North Sea was at $24.98 on the International Petroleum Exchange
in London.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez was a key negotiator in helping to bring about the
agreement in Vienna that raised oil output to ease prices down from
nine-year highs.
</P>
<P>
   Including Iran, which reversed its initial decision not to raise
output, the cartel is expected to increase production by about 1.7
million barrels a day, or more than 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Taking into account non-OPEC members Mexico and Norway's
decision to increase production -- and the probability of continued
cheating on quotas by major producers -- the total increase is
likely to reach about 2 million barrels a day. That's the level
sought by the United States and other oil-importing nations that
were under pressure from consumers angry over steep gasoline and
heating oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said Friday that Venezuela will raise its own
production by 125,000 barrels a day within a month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
