<HEADLINE> Boeing Gets $2.2B in New Orders  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing Co. has received about $2.2 billion in new
orders from two airlines, including the first orders for its new
777-300X model.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Airlines Co. Ltd. will take possession of the first
777-300X by 2004, with seven more to be delivered by 2008, Boeing
said Friday. Boeing did not give a value for the eight-plane order,
but based on company list prices it would be worth about $1.5
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is great news, because it shows the strength that's
coming back in the Asian markets,'' Boeing spokeswoman Marta
Newhart said.
</P>
<P>
   British carrier easyJet also placed firm orders for 17 smaller
737-700s, worth $765 million to $850 million, depending on
interiors selected by the airline. Deliveries are to begin in July
2001.
</P>
<P>
   EasyJet, which previously ordered 15 next-generation 737-700s
and 12 new 737-300s, plans to use the additional planes on its
routes from London to cities in Europe as well as short routes to
cities within the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   The twin-engine 777-300X is an extended-range version of the
777-300, capable of flying 8,300 miles, compared to 6,854 miles for
the earlier model. At a bit more than 242 feet, the 777-300 is the
longest commercial jet built and can be configured to carry up to
359 passengers in three classes.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is offering the new jets to compete with Airbus Industrie
in the Asia-Pacific market. Airbus has a long-range version of its
four-engine A-340, and is developing the larger A340-500 and
A340-600 models.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
