<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.H. Judge Thayer Resigns  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- New Hampshire Supreme Court Justice Stephen
Thayer, under pressure from state and federal investigations of his
personal finances, resigned Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Thayer hand-delivered his resignation to Gov. Jeanne Shaheen a
month after he was put on leave while authorities investigated him
for failing to disclose a personal loan.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the FBI said its investigation found no evidence of
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   But Attorney General Philip McLaughlin said Friday an
investigation by his office resulted in Thayer's resignation.
McLaughlin said he would release a full report of the investigation
later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Thayer, 54, a former U.S. attorney, was appointed to the New
Hampshire Supreme Court in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, William Brennan, did not immediately return a phone
call Friday. He said this week the intense attention to Thayer's
actions had been costly.
</P>
<P>
   ''This process has taken its toll, not only on him, but also the
institution he has served for the last 16 years,'' Brennan said.
</P>
<P>
   Allegations arose during Thayer's recent divorce that he had
failed to disclose some of his debts on home loan applications.
Federal banking laws require that all debts be disclosed on
mortgage and loan applications.
</P>
<P>
   Independently, the state's Judicial Conduct Committee is
investigating Thayer's failure to report a $50,000 loan from lawyer
Emile Bussiere on annual financial disclosure forms for judges from
1997 to 1999. Thayer later amended the forms to disclose the loan.
</P>
<P>
   The committee also is looking into Thayer's failure to report
the Bussiere loan on a 1997 bank application for a $55,000 home
equity loan, and whether he omitted other debts from a 1993
mortgage application -- the same allegations investigated by the
FBI.
</P>
<P>
   Thayer's colleagues on the court placed him on administrative
leave with pay last month, but did not say why. Thayer had been
fighting the suspension in federal court.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 1408 </TRAILER>
