<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 14:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Fed. Agency Books Better  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- More federal agencies are keeping their books
in order, but serious problems remain in tracking transactions
worth billions of dollars, according to a report made public
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Treasury Department's annual look at the financial
statements of 24 federal agencies for the fiscal year that ended
Sept. 30 found that 13 received clean ratings by auditors, up from
six when the survey was first conducted in 1996 and 12 last year.
</P>
<P>
   Four agency statements got qualified, or acceptable, opinions
and five -- down from 13 in 1996 -- came back with disclaimers, which
means they were unsatisfactory. Two agencies, the departments of
Interior and State, did not meet filing deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   ''Significant progress continues to be made in the areas of
financial management,'' Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers wrote
in the report, prepared with the White House's Office of Management
and Budget and the General Accounting Office, Congress'
investigative arm.
</P>
<P>
   ''More agencies are completing their financial statements on
time, and the quality of the data continues to improve,'' Summers
said.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Stephen Horn, R-Calif., who discussed the report at a
hearing of his House Government Reform Committee panel, said
agencies as a whole still earned no better than a ''D+'' in
providing reliable, accurate financial information.
</P>
<P>
   Horn acknowledged some progress but said he was ''disheartened,
but not surprised,'' that significant accounting discrepancies and
financial weaknesses remain. Horn graded all 24 agencies, giving A
grades only to NASA and the National Science Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Horn cited as examples of poor bookkeeping an overpayment of
Medicare claims by $13.5 billion last year, down from $23 billion
in 1996, and the IRS' issuance of a $15,000 tax refund to a person
with an overdue tax bill of near $350,000.
</P>
<P>
   Horn also asked why trustees of the Medicare and Social Security
trust funds came out with a report on Thursday, just a day before
Treasury's report, that gave a far rosier outlook of the financial
solvency of the two programs.
</P>
<P>
   General Accounting Office Comptroller General David Walker
agreed that the lack of coordination in the two reports ''makes the
government look foolish.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker praised the Social Security Administration for making
good progress in financial management, while singling out the
Pentagon, which holds a large percentage of government assets, for
being unable to consistently produce auditable financial
statements.
</P>
<P>
   The GAO also found high risk financial management at the IRS,
the Forest Service and the Federal Aviation Administration.
</P>
<P>
   The government was ''unable to support significant portions of
the $1.76 trillion reported as the total net cost of government
operations,'' the GAO said.
</P>
<P>
   It said $313 billion reported as a liability for remediation of
environmental contamination and disposal of hazardous waste may not
be complete, and data were not available for an accurate estimate
of a reported $196 billion military retirement health benefits
liability.
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Gotbaum of the Office of Management and Budget said this
still marked a major improvement from 10 years ago, when almost no
agencies prepared audited financial statements.
</P>
<P>
   He noted that last October the American Institute of Certified
Public Accountants recognized federal accounting standards as
''generally accepted accounting principles,'' a ''significant
milestone in improving public confidence'' in federal financial
management.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: OMB site: http://www.whitehouse.gov/omb/
</P>
<P>
   The GAO site: http://www.gao.gov/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
