<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russians Attack Chechen Rebels  </HEADLINE>
By LYOMA TURPALOV, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GUDERMES, Russia (AP) -- Russian troops fanned out across
Chechnya's rugged southern mountains on Friday in a bid to save 39
comrades missing since their convoy was ambushed by Chechen rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian forces also unleashed air and artillery attacks on
areas where rebel bands are concentrated. Elsewhere, the United
Nations' top human-rights official arrived in Russia on a trip to
assess allegations of rights violations as international criticism
of the war continues.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-nine Interior Ministry troops were in the convoy that was
ambushed Wednesday near Vedeno, deep in the mountains, said Sergei
Yastrzhembsky, the Kremlin spokesman for Chechnya. Four soldiers
were killed in the attack, he said, according to the Interfax news
agency. Six managed to escape.
</P>
<P>
   Federal troops spread out around Vedeno to search for the 39
missing fighters, the military command said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Interior Minister Vladimir Rushailo, who flew to the
Vedeno region Friday, outlined the problems Russian troops were
having with the search: ''The difficult land formations, the
difficult weather conditions, and besides, the danger of the land
being mined.''
</P>
<P>
   ''There probably will be more dead, and more missing in
action,'' he told NTV television.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Gen. Valery Manilov, first deputy chief of Russia's General
Staff, said Friday that Russian forces had all of Chechnya under
''practical control,'' and the federal troops are better equipped
and numerically superior to the Chechen fighters. Nonetheless, the
ambush was the latest in a series of attacks demonstrating Russian
forces' vulnerability.
</P>
<P>
   Russian ground forces that entered Chechnya in late September
have driven most rebels into the mountains that make up the
republic's southern third. The rebels are skilled guerrilla
fighters who use the rough terrain to their advantage, while
Russian forces struggle to move their heavy equipment in the
mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials repeatedly have said the rebels are on the
verge of defeat, but the fighters continue to resist fiercely, and
many rebels are believed to have filtered back into Russian-held
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights groups have repeatedly charged that Russian forces
are committing widespread violations in the breakaway republic,
including torturing detainees and summarily executing civilians.
Russia has rejected the allegations. But in an apparent bow to
international pressure, the Kremlin invited the U.N. High
Commissioner for Human Rights, Mary Robinson, to visit Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am aware that there has been violence on both sides. There
has also been Chechen violence and the background is quite a
complex one,'' she said after arriving Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's Chechnya tour is to include a visit to detention
facilities. Some groups charge that, in the past, Russia has moved
tortured detainees out of such facilities before allowing access by
journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the German newspaper Suddeutsche Zeitung reported in
Saturday's edition that the body of Gen. Gennady Shpigun, who was
kidnapped a year ago in Chechnya, has been found. Shpigun, the
Interior Ministry's envoy to Chechnya, escaped from custody in
February and froze to death while fleeing, the newspaper cited
Chechen and Russian sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Russian spokesmen could not be reached for comment. Rushailo
said on March 20 that Shpigun was still alive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
