<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rick and Darva: Together Again?  </HEADLINE>
By FRAZIER MOORE, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The problem with TV isn't so much its tacky
programs and even tackier personalities. No, the big problem comes
when TV lies.
</P>
<P>
   I have come to understand this from Rick Rockwell and Darva
Conger and their marriage on the rocks, all arising from the
by-now-notorious Fox network special ''Who Wants to Marry a
Multimillionaire?''
</P>
<P>
   Note: Bad taste made ''Multimillionaire'' a triumph. But what
did it in was bad faith.
</P>
<P>
   Here's former Air Force nurse Conger, who admits she took part
in the ''Multimillionaire'' matchup as a lark, then fibbed her way
through her marriage vows. ''I was playing a role,'' she told Larry
King, just one stop on her publicity tour to tell the world she
wants her privacy back.
</P>
<P>
   Surely Conger knows that showing her pretty face on CNN's
''Larry King Live,'' ABC's ''Good Morning America'' and ''Dateline
NBC'' isn't the best way to restore her anonymity. And that
responding to questions about posing for Playboy, particularly in
the affirmative (''I couldn't say 'definitely not' to anything
right now,'' she declared on NBC's ''Today''), isn't the best way
to repair her good name.
</P>
<P>
   And here's Rockwell, a smalltime actor/comic born Richard Balkey
whose very status as a multimillionaire was being questioned only
days after the broadcast. Even as he insists he's a dreamy-eyed
romantic who was hoping for a soul mate, he is milking his
''Multimillionaire'' stunt for maximum reward.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, Rockwell was on CNN's ''TalkBack Live,'' part of
his campaign to reignite his show-biz career. ''It's going very
well, it's going really well,'' he said of the standup gigs his
newfound fame has won him.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the groom who never so much as glimpsed his bride's
backside quipped that he hopes Conger does pose for Playboy: ''I
want to see her.''
</P>
<P>
   These are the sort of characters who make you long for Joe
Isuzu. (Come to think of it, an Isuzu Trooper was one of Darva's
''wedding presents.'') Or Jon Lovitz's truth-defying alter ego who
would gloat, ''Yeah, that's the ticket,'' with each self-promoting
falsehood. Unlike their flesh-and-blood counterparts, make-believe
liars are funny. Not toxic.
</P>
<P>
   But not all of ''Multimillionaire's'' duplicity was on camera.
Consider the bad faith exhibited behind the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the producers chose to represent their ''Mr.
Multimillionaire'' chiefly as a real estate magnate with a golf
course and a plane, not as the goofball who starred in ''Return of
the Killer Tomatoes'' and can tell jokes for 30 hours straight. In
short, not as a guy who might do anything, like take a wife, to
land himself some TV face-time.
</P>
<P>
   Even more deceitfully, the program, which placed Rick and Darva
in holy matrimony, left viewers with the feeling that this was a
viable marriage, however ill-advised or short-lived it might prove
to be.
</P>
<P>
   But remember that the show was prerecorded. Its taping date was
Feb. 8. By the time ''Who Wants to Marry a Multimillionaire?''
aired on Feb. 15, the marriage was clearly a nonstarter. Still on
their honeymoon cruise, Rick and Darva were barely even sharing
hellos, as the show's production company, which had sent along two
escorts, surely knew.
</P>
<P>
   As for viewers, kept in the dark that the marriage they were
witnessing was already moot -- well, they were conned. All 22.8
million of them.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was thrilled.
</P>
<P>
   But then came to light a pesky 1991 restraining order issued
against Rockwell after an ex-girlfriend accused him of hitting and
threatening to kill her. (These were charges Rockwell denied,
although he owned up to having let the air out of her tires.)
</P>
<P>
   Then Fox network boss Sandy Grushow grandly pronounced the end
of all such ''exploitative reality specials,'' in his words.
''They're gone; they're over.'' Which was for the best. They might
have pre-empted the ongoing Fox series ''World's Wildest Police
Videos'' and ''Cops.''
</P>
<P>
   But will anything pre-empt Rick and Darva?
</P>
<P>
   Don't bet against seeing Rick Rockwell as the host of some
third-tier cable talk show.
</P>
<P>
   And what of Darva Conger? Well, it doesn't take a nurse to tell
she's bitten by the TV bug. Despite past talk of escaping the
limelight, she virtually canvasses for a high-profile job in an
interview in this week's TV Guide -- a job that would combine
''health education, public speaking and the media.'' (Look out, Dr.
Bob Arnot!)
</P>
<P>
   Alone, each could make it. But a far greater draw would be this
twin bill: Rick and Darva, the couple that never was, reunited for
money and glory on TV. Maybe on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   The sad truth is, if you think it couldn't happen, you're lying
to yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere in television ...
</P>
<P>
   'TWENTY-ONE': Soybean grower Grant Hansen of Ames, Neb., wants
to win enough money to pay off his farm. A graduate of Pace
University where he studied finance, Rob Renz is currently a
bellman at Manhattan's Waldorf Astoria hotel, where he has carried
Hillary Clinton's bags and once collided with Frank Sinatra with a
luggage cart. He'll be looking to collect a nice ''tip.'' These are
two of the contestants who'll appear on the quiz show
''Twenty-One,'' Monday at 9 p.m. EDT on NBC. Maury Povich is host.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Frazier Moore can be reached at fmoore ''at'' ap.org
</P>
</TEXT>
