<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Angolan Journalist Convicted  </HEADLINE>
By CASIMIRO SIONA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUANDA, Angola (AP) -- An Angolan court on Friday sentenced a
prominent journalist to six months in jail after a trial during
which defense witnesses were barred from speaking.
</P>
<P>
   Rafael Marques, 28, was convicted of defaming the country's
president in a newspaper article. In addition to the jail time, he
was ordered to pay $1,000 in fines and court costs. However, the
sentence was suspended while Marques awaits the outcome of an
appeal to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The charges stemmed from an article late last year in which
Marques said President Jose Eduardo Dos Santos should be held
accountable for the country's near-collapse amid government
corruption fostered by civil war.
</P>
<P>
   The article appeared in the Luanda-based weekly Agora, and the
court sentenced its editor, Aguiar dos Santos, to two months in
prison for publishing it. That sentence also was suspended pending
an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The case has prompted fierce criticism at home and abroad. The
U.S. State Department expressed concern at the way the trial was
conducted and the government's heavy-handed reaction to criticism
in the media.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, U.S. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke urged the
government to rescind or dramatically reduce the sentence so that
Marques spends no more time in jail. Marques was jailed for more
than a month before being charged and released in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not trying to interfere in an internal event in Angola,
but I think this jail sentence is extraordinarily harsh,''
Holbrooke said.
</P>
<P>
   Marques' trial began March 21 in Luanda and initially was to be
open to the public. But Judge Joaquim Cangato ordered it closed
before the first session, saying a photographer had breached rules
by taking pictures of the empty courtroom before the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The judge barred the defense's witnesses from speaking and
refused to accept evidence the defense said proved the allegations
Marques made in his article. The judge also banned Marques's
attorney, Luis Nascimento, from the case and from practicing law
for six months after he walked out of the courtroom in protest.
</P>
<P>
   The new defense lawyer -- Antonio Joao Francisco, who was named
by Cangato -- reportedly had no legal experience.
</P>
<P>
   Several countries and human rights groups have condemned the
Angolan government for harassing and jailing dozens of independent
journalists since the country's two-decade civil war resumed in
December 1998. The government and UNITA rebels began fighting after
the southwest African country gained independence from Portugal in
1975.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 1505 </TRAILER>
