<DOCNO> APW20000331.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Board Considering Rail Merger Rules  </HEADLINE>
By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Government regulators will consider setting
performance standards and may even seek ways to increase
competition when evaluating future railroad mergers.
</P>
<P>
   The Surface Transportation Board disclosed Friday this and other
measures under consideration as it revamps its merger rules.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, the board ordered a halt to merger talks among
major rail carriers, citing service problems that have occurred
following a pair of recent combinations. The board blocked all
merger activity while it reconsiders the rules under which it will
review such deals.
</P>
<P>
   That step disappointed two companies that had been discussing a
possible marriage, Canadian National and Burlington Northern Santa
Fe.
</P>
<P>
   But the board said it is concerned that a continuation of such
deals could result in a transcontinental rail ''duopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, board chairman Linda J. Morgan set June 11, 2001, as
the date to issue those new rules and listed the matters being
considered.
</P>
<P>
   She said the agency plans to drop its current ''one case at a
time'' policy so it can consider the downstream effects of any
future deals, including likely responses by other railroad
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Current rules also include maintaining competition in the areas
of merging roads. The board said it will also consider whether to
go beyond that and seek increased competition in some cases.
</P>
<P>
   Finding ways to protect customers and shortline railroads that
connect to major carriers from merger-related service disruptions
will also be a major topic, the board said. This might include
setting performance standards and requiring compensation for
service failures.
</P>
<P>
   The board said it also plans to address in its new merger rules:
</P>
<P>
   --Ways to ensure adequate and coordinated consideration of safety
issues.
</P>
<P>
   --Protection for railroad workers when contracts are merged
between roads.
</P>
<P>
   --Safety regulation and defense issues that could result from the
combination of major U.S. and Canadian railroads.
</P>
<P>
   Burlington Northern and Canadian National had asked the board to
let their $6 billion merger move forward while the government
developed new rules. But the board rejected that plea, contending
it did not want to be creating new merger regulations in the middle
of what might turn out to be the final round of railroad
combinations.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Surface Transportation Board: http://www.stb.dot.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
