computer chip maker, said it would post a first-quarter gain of 17
cents a share after an Internal Revenue Service review found it did
not owe $600 million in taxes. The company said yesterday it had
set aside the money in the event it had a tax liability regarding
how it allocated profits between national and international
divisions. The gain will be posted when earnings are released April
18.
</P>
