   UPS Agrees To Create Jobs
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- United Parcel Service has agreed to create 4,000
new full-time jobs this spring. The plan ends a dispute with the
Teamsters union over a 1997 contract, which included job creation.
All 4,000 new jobs will be created by June 10 and offered to
current part-time employees, UPS spokesman Norman Black said today.
Atlanta-based UPS employs 344,000 workers, 117,500 of them in
part-time positions.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread Rail Track Defects Found
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- CSX Transportation announced an internal
review of its track maintenance today after federal railroad
inspectors found deteriorating conditions in its system used by
passenger, freight and commuter trains up and down the East Coast.
The Federal Railroad Administration had begun a special safety
audit of the railroad in February after a series of derailments.
George Gavalla, associate administrator for safety, said the agency
audited CSX in 1997 and became concerned because it hadn't seen a
reduction in derailments and other problems. John W. Snow, chairman
and chief executive officer of CSX Corporation, responded that his
company ''has repaired or is in the process of repairing all of the
defects identified in the report. The company said Snow will
personally head an internal company review of all track maintenance
and improvement programs.
</P>
<P>
   Tobacco Lawyer Urges Against Biases
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A tobacco attorney today acknowledged the
unpopularity of cigarette makers in America but asked the jury
setting damages for three sick smokers not to bury the industry
under a huge award. Philip Morris attorney Dan made the plea in the
defense's final comments against a $14.4 million compensatory
damage claim. He called on the jury to set aside ''your biases,
your sympathy and your prejudice'' and award no money to the
smokers with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;M Opens First U.S. Store
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Hennes &AMP; Mauritz opened its first U.S. store
today, attracting thousands of shoppers who were eager to grab up
the cheap-yet-chic clothes from the popular Swedish chain. From
curious New Yorkers to European tourists, they piled into H&AMP;M's
store on tony Fifth Avenue, combing through the racks filled with
fashionable $9 shirts and $20 pairs of pants. The enthusiastic
crowd offered a temporary distraction from troubles that beset H&AMP;M
last week, when its chief executive quit and the company reported a
12 percent drop in projected quarterly profits. Stockholm-based H&AMP;M
has built a strong reputation for offering trendy fashions at
affordable prices.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Inspects 767 Part for Cracks
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- The Boeing Co. has notified all its 767-300
customers that parts of the wing structure near the central fuel
tank may be susceptible to cracking. Boeing is inspecting 16 model
767-300 jets in various stages of production for cracks in
''stringers,'' which run the width of the fuel tank and help
support the wing. No cracks have been reported in planes currently
in service with carriers, Boeing spokeswoman Debbie Heathers said
today. Boeing said the problem came to light recently when an
8-inch crack was found in a stringer on a 767-300 in production at
the company's widebody jetliner plant in Everett.
</P>
<P>
   Japan Jobless Rate at Record High
</P>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Japan's unemployment rate rose in February to a
record 4.9 percent, up from 4.7 percent a month earlier. Economists
has been expecting no change. The number of jobless people totaled
3.27 million, up 4.5 percent from the same month a year ago, the
Management and Coordination Agency said today. The February figure
surpassed the previous high unemployment rate of 4.8 percent, most
recently recorded in July.
</P>
