<BODY>
<HEADLINE> De Beers Certifies Diamond Sources  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- De Beers, the South African conglomerate that
dominates the world diamond trade, has begun selling stones with a
guarantee that they don't come from rebels in Angola or other
African countries.
</P>
<P>
   The certification process began this week, but an unrelated
legal dispute means De Beers isn't selling diamonds from any source
in Angola for the time being.
</P>
<P>
   Under pressure from the United Nations to cut off the financial
resources of Angolan rebel leader Jonas Savimbi, De Beers announced
in October that it would be certifying that any diamonds it sold
came from legitimate sources.
</P>
<P>
   The only Angolan diamonds it will sell will be through a
contract signed in 1990 with SDM, a joint venture of Ashton Mining
of Canada, Odebrecht of Brazil and Endiama, Angola's state diamond
company.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have curtailed all of our outside buying on the outside
market, and all the diamonds that come to us come from our own
mines, our partners in Botswana and Namibia, and those we buy and
contract from Russia and Canada,'' Andrew Lamont, spokesman for
Diamond Trading Co. Ltd., De Beers' London marketing arm, said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Angolan government issued a decree on Jan. 31, however, that
all diamond transactions have to go through Ascorp, a new venture
in which former diamond dealer and businessman Lev Leviev has a
stake, according to The Financial Times.
</P>
<P>
   Leviev, chairman of Africa-Israel Investments Ltd., was quoted
as saying that his new marketing system would prevent ''dirty
diamonds'' from rebels getting to market.
</P>
<P>
   ''It really improves greatly the security of the diamond
deliveries and helps the social and economic environment in
Angola,'' Leviev was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   But De Beers chairman Gary Ralfe, speaking at a diamond
conference in Israel on March 24, said his company has ''a lawful
contract operating with SDM which is underpinned by a very large
loan and will defend our contractual right in any jurisdiction
where the remedies of law are available.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, police in Belgium seized a consignment of rough
diamonds bound for Ascorp after De Beers contended it had a valid
contract for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 1516 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
