<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka, Tamil Battle To Continue  </HEADLINE>
By ASIF ANSAR, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) -- President Chandrika Kumaratunga said
Friday the military offensive against Tamil rebels will continue
until the guerrillas agreed to lay down their arms, state-run
television Rupavahini reported.
</P>
<P>
   Kumaratunga's statement came as the rebels and government
soldiers battled near a strategic causeway linking the mainland
with northern Jaffna peninsula, 185 miles north of Colombo, the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas launched a fresh offensive last weekend to
recapture Jaffna, which they had lost to the military in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The clandestine rebel radio station Voice of Tiger said more
than 700 government troops had been killed and wounded since
Sunday. The rebel Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam said they lost
only 60 fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The radio report, monitored in the northern garrison town of
Vavuniya, also said that 36 civilians who had sought refuge in a
Hindu temple near the Elephant Pass were wounded by an army
artillery barrage.
</P>
<P>
   The military said it killed 150 Tiger rebels and wounded more
than 350 guerrillas since Sunday. It put its loses at 85 soldiers
killed and another 613 wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Four rebels were killed Thursday when soldiers fired on
infiltrating rebels near Elephant Pass, the Defense Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   Government forces and rebels also exchanged artillery fire. Navy
guns and air force jets attacked a rebel convoy near the pass.
</P>
<P>
   If the rebels succeed in overrunning the pass, they would cut
off the peninsula from the rest of the country and recapture
Jaffna.
</P>
<P>
   She did not discuss the fate of a peace initiative launched by
the Norwegian government earlier this year to bring the government
and the separatist guerrillas to the negotiating table after a gap
of nearly five years.
</P>
<P>
   Over 61,000 people have been killed since the war began in 1983
in this small island nation off India's southern coast.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels are fighting for an independent homeland for minority
Tamils in the north and east of the country. They accuses the
majority Sinhalese community of discriminating against the minority
Tamils in education and jobs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
