<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Photographer Freund Dead at 91  </HEADLINE>
By MARILYN AUGUST, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Gisele Freund, whose photographs captured the
attitudes of France's Left Bank literary elite, died Friday. She
was 91.
</P>
<P>
   Cochin Hospital in Paris reported she died there of a heart
attack.
</P>
<P>
   Freund was one of Europe's most prominent photographers and
became a pillar among French feminist intellectuals after settling
in Paris in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   President Jacques Chirac praised Freund as ''one of the world's
greatest photographers.'' Chirac said she ''was able, better than
anyone, to reveal the essence of beings through their
expressions.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1908 to a wealthy Jewish family in Germany, Freund
became a student activist who battled the rise of Hitler's national
socialism. She studied sociology in Frankfurt but was forced to
flee in 1933, escaping just as police were about to arrest her.
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, she pursued her doctoral studies at the Sorbonne,
where her enthusiasm for photography was met with some skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   She met militant feminist writer Adrienne Monnier while browsing
at La Maison des Amis du Livre, Monnier's book shop on the Left
Bank. The shop was frequented by Jean-Paul Sartre, Simone de
Beauvoir, James Joyce and Ernest Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   Monnier became her lifelong mentor and companion, introducing
her to the Parisian intellectual set and encouraging her to pursue
photography.
</P>
<P>
   In 1935, Freund executed an acclaimed series of photographs
documenting the misery of British coal miners, and met Andre
Malraux. Her portrait of the author of ''Man's Fate'' -- wrapped in
a trench coat with a cigarette dangling from his mouth -- is among
her most well-known photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Her use of color clashed with the prevailing style of retouched
black-and-white studio portraits, but she persevered, saying color
''was closer to life.''
</P>
<P>
   Freund specialized in conveying attitudes. She focused on hands,
body posture and clothing. Some of her most famous photographs were
published in Life and Time magazines.
</P>
<P>
   The Nazi invasion of France in 1940 brought her career to a
halt. Freund fled again, this time to southern France and later
Argentina where she worked until the war's end in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   She returned to France where she earned an international
reputation as the photographer of Sartre, De Beauvoir, Jean
Cocteau, and Joyce, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Her works include ''Three Days with Joyce,'' a collection of
black and white photographs showing the Irish writer with friends
and family, and correcting proofs of his famous novel ''Finnegan's
Wake.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Freund was involved in the lives of the artists and writers
she photographed,'' said art critic Ann Cremin who knew Freund.
''She was more of a witness than a reporter.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Lionel Jospin hailed Freund as an ''unparalleled
sociologist and reporter who traveled the world with a generous and
lucid approach to places and events faraway.''
</P>
<P>
   Freund won France's National Grand Prize for Photography in
1980. She took the official photograph at the presidential
inauguration of Socialist Francois Mitterrand in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   No details concerning survivors or funeral arrangements were
immediately available.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 1530 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
