<HEADLINE> Italian Candidate Takes To the Sea  </HEADLINE>
By VANIA GRANDI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- Media magnate and former premier Silvio Berlusconi
took to the sea Friday aboard a luxury liner for a campaign cruise
aimed at building support for his conservative party in Italy's
April 16 regional elections.
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi -- whose Fininvest media empire includes three
television stations and a publishing company -- called the cruise an
''antidote'' for a law approved last month that bars political ads
on TV.
</P>
<P>
   The gleaming white-and-blue liner Excellent, leased by
Berlusconi's Forza Italia party for $1.25 million, departed the
northern port of Genoa and headed to Italy's southern tip.
</P>
<P>
   The voyage will include shipboard rallies and fireworks and
stops at 10 ports, winding up April 8 in Venice. The ship is
scheduled to be accompanied by a plane trailing a banner reading
''Italy  Liberty.''
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi's spokesman, Fabrizio Casinelli, said about 100
Italian journalists are aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi, who served briefly as premier in 1994, heads the
opposition to Premier Massimo D'Alema's center-left government.
Berlusconi says D'Alema should resign if the center-left is
defeated in the April 16 nationwide regional elections.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema rejected that advice and denounced the cruise as an
''arrogant show of wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema's 19 months at the helm of the government have been
rocked by a government crisis, which forced him to temporarily
resign, and a stream of bitter internal squabbles.
</P>
<P>
   The center-left pushed through the ban on political ads after
Berlusconi's conservatives scored big in European and regional
elections last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
