<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 15:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Questions Clinton's Ethics  </HEADLINE>
By SANDRA SOBIERAJ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHWAUBENON, Wis. (AP) -- George W. Bush swatted back at
President Clinton on Friday, calling him ''campaign manager for Al
Gore'' and seizing his latest legal woes as a reminder that Clinton
has ''fallen 41 presidents short'' of his promise to be the most
ethical of all U.S. presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spoke to reporters assembled in a music room of Pioneer
Elementary School, where the Texas GOP governor and likely
presidential nominee campaigned on education one day after Clinton
used a Democratic Party fund-raising speech to criticize Bush on
several fronts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the speech marked the fifth or sixth time in the 2000
presidential race that Clinton ''has taken time out of his busy
schedule to serve as campaign manager for Al Gore. And I am honored
that he would take my campaign so seriously that he would spend
time talking about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Vice President Gore, the presumptive Democratic
nominee, have not yet campaigned together this year. They are
expected to make a joint appearance on April 15, at a Democratic
National Committee fund raiser in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Key to Bush strategy is stirring voter fatigue with Clinton
scandals and lashing Gore to them.
</P>
<P>
   As such, when Brittany, a fifth-grader at Pioneer, asked Bush
what his ''first major step'' as president would be, he said: ''To
remind the administration ... the people that I've asked to serve
in the Cabinet that there's only one standard -- the highest of high
ethics.''
</P>
<P>
   To reporters, his assessment was more harsh, and he used the
swirl around 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez as another opportunity to
underscore that Gore is inextricably linked to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The little boy's fate is subject of an accelerating tug-of-war
between U.S. relatives and his father in Cuba. Gore broke with the
administration by backing legislation to grant Elian and members of
his Cuban family permanent U.S. residency status and by calling for
a family court to decide the case instead of the Immigration and
Naturalization Service.
</P>
<P>
   ''The vice president frequently touts his experience and his
influence'' in the administration, Bush said, challenging Gore to
insist ''that the administration he is part of'' let Elian remain
in the United States while a family court decides his best
interests.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about a federal judge's ruling this week that the
president criminally violated a woman's privacy by releasing her
letters during the Monica Lewinsky scandal, Bush called it
''another series of incidents that continue to undermine the
credibility of the Clinton-Gore administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush recalled that Clinton, when sworn in 1993 as America's 42nd
president, promised to preside over the most ethical White House in
history.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's fallen about 41 presidents short,'' Bush cracked.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in a speech to a Democratic audience on Thursday in New
York, rebuked Bush for ''completely unfair'' campaign ads against
Republican John McCain during the primary season.
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton was especially harsh in noting that Bush opposed
hate crimes legislation in his state after the murder of James
Byrd, a black Texas man dragged to death on the back of a pickup.
</P>
<P>
   ''All he had to do was to lift his hand and they would have had
a hate crimes bill,'' Clinton said of Bush. ''And it did not pass
because they (Republicans) did not want it to pass. Because they do
not believe that gays and lesbians should be protected by hate
crimes legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush did not comment Friday on Clinton's specific criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seems like the administration would like to spend a lot of
time trying to tear me down,'' said Bush, who complained this week
that the Education Department was politicizing its business to
serve Gore's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''Spare me,'' replied Doug Hattaway, a spokesman for Gore, who
took Friday off to celebrate his 52nd birthday at home with his
family.
</P>
<P>
   ''The whole Republican Party in Washington has been working hand
in glove with Bush to attack Al Gore personally and keep this
campaign away from the real issues that matter to people.''
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Jake Siewert said Bush could expect more
from Clinton. ''The president is the leader of the Democratic Party
and when he's addressing a Democratic function, he'll make clear he
supports the vice president and his plans for the future, not those
of Governor Bush,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before leaving Wisconsin for a weekend at home in Austin, Texas,
Bush collected $50,000 for his campaign over a broiled chicken
lunch at Brett Favre's Steak House.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
