<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia: Weapons Disposal Not Started  </HEADLINE>
By JEROME SOCOLOVSKY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- Russia admitted Friday that it
hasn't yet started to destroy its chemical weapons stockpiles and
pleaded for increased Western financial aid to help it meet its
commitments under the Chemical Weapons Convention.
</P>
<P>
   The Organization for the Prohibition of Chemical Weapons said
the United States has already destroyed 17 percent of its
32,000-ton arsenal, comprising around 3 million chemical munitions.
</P>
<P>
   Under the chemical weapons treaty, which went into force in
1997, all 121 signatory states are required to have eliminated 1
percent of their chemical weapons by April 29 and the rest of their
stockpiles by 2007.
</P>
<P>
   Russia and the United States account for virtually all of the
world's 8.4 million chemical munitions, according to the
Hague-based organization.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Gen. Valery Kapachin, head of Russian's chemical weapons
elimination program, said Moscow remains committed to getting rid
of its 40,000-ton chemical weapons arsenal, containing 4 million to
5 million munitions. However, he said it cannot cover the $6
billion price tag on current promises of assistance from the United
States and other countries.
</P>
<P>
   ''We haven't destroyed anything as of today,'' Kapachin told
reporters after meetings with OPCW officials.
</P>
<P>
   He declined to specify the amount of requested aid.
</P>
<P>
   Valery Semin, a Russian foreign ministry official, said Canada
and Norway this week joined the seven other donor countries in
pledging to help Russia.
</P>
<P>
   However, pledge figures were not given because donor countries
want to target their assistance to specific projects.
</P>
<P>
   Max Gevers, the Dutch representative to the OPCW, said ''very
little money, if any'' had been spent so far because of delays in
setting up chemical weapons elimination and conversion projects in
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ''There has been a considerable amount of delay. It's not a
matter of whose fault it is, it's a diplomatic fact,'' he said.
''We are at this moment considering together with Russia different
options with respect to speeding up the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Last November, Russia requested an extension. The OPCW's
executive body is scheduled to discuss the request next week and
issue a decision in May, said Ron Manley, the organization's acting
director of verification.
</P>
<P>
   However, he said the extension is likely to be granted if
officials are persuaded that Russia is serious about its
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's important at the end of the day is that Russia's
chemical weapons are destroyed,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 1532 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000331.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sierra Leone Arrests Dissidents  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Peacekeepers in Sierra Leone have
arrested 16 alleged dissidents suspected of fomenting instability
in neighboring Liberia, a senior official said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Without identifying the suspects, National Security Adviser
Sheka Mansaray said the 16 were apprehended in the Gola Forest,
about 230 miles east of Freetown near the Liberian border.
</P>
<P>
   Mansaray said in a state radio broadcast that officers of a
multinational West African peacekeeping force, ECOMOG, believed the
suspects planned to cause instability in Liberia.
</P>
<P>
   He did not give details of the arrests, but said that Sierra
Leone was committed to preventing dissident groups from using its
territory as a base.
</P>
<P>
   Liberia and Sierra Leone have frequently exchanged accusations
of supporting each others' rebel movements.
</P>
<P>
   A peace accord last July ended Sierra Leone's 8-year civil war,
in which tens of thousands were killed or maimed by rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Liberia's 7-year war ended in 1996 after more than 200,000
people were killed by various factions, including one led by
President Charles Taylor, who won elections in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
