<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Up 106.10; Nasdaq Rises 140.01  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned mostly higher today as investors
shook off their distress over plummeting technology shares and
began looking for bargains after a weeklong selloff.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the
Nasdaq composite index was up 140.01 at 4,597.90 after dropping 187
points on Thursday. The index had been lower for most of the
morning.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 106.10 at 11,075.80, and
the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was up 27.47 at 1,515.39.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq began moving higher on the strength of stalwarts like
Dell Computer, up 2} at 54 15/16, and Intel, up 7 11/16 at 134
11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Cisco Systems rose 3} to 77] and JDS Uniphase gained 5 5/16 to
121 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   CheckFree Holdings rose 8{ to 69{ after a Lehman Brothers
analyst issued a ''buy'' rating on the stock.
</P>
<P>
   Some steep losses by technology stocks prevented the Nasdaq from
recovering even more ground. Shares of drkoop.com, the online
health information provider, fell 42 percent, or by 2 19/32, to 3
21/32 after auditors questioned the viability of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Another Internet company hit hard was Ariba, which helps
companies track sales on the Web. The stock was down 14 at 206
after a Prudential Securities analyst downgraded the stock to
''accumulate'' from ''strong buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel and Hewlett-Packard, up 4 9/16 to 135 5/16, paced the Dow.
</P>
<P>
   Conseco fell about 16 percent after the insurance and financial
services company said it will record a $350 million charge and may
sell its consumer finance unit. Shares were down 2 3/16 at 11{.
</P>
<P>
   The market was somewhat rattled by a pair of economic reports
released this morning that provided a mixed picture of the
economy's strength.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department reported that personal income rose 0.4
percent in February but that Americans' spending rose more than
twice as fast. That pulled the nation's savings rate down to an
all-time monthly low, and fueled expectations that the Federal
Reserve will raise interest rates at least once more this year in
its bid to slow the economy to sustainable levels.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are no signs of any significant slowdown for consumer
spending,'' said Stan Shipley, senior economist at Merrill Lynch.
''The economy is clearly growing too fast for the Fed.''
</P>
<P>
   Some market watchers drew encouragement from a second report
that showed orders to U.S. factories were down for the second
straight month in February. Orders for airplanes and other
transportation equipment took their biggest plunge in 10 months,
dropping 8.9 percent. Industrial machinery orders fell 4.8 percent,
the steepest decline since October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by nearly a 2-to-1 margin
on the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 704.52 million
shares, down from 778.66 million shares at the same time Thursday.
Breadth on the Nasdaq improved, with advancers leading by a 4-to-3
margin.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of small company stocks was up 11.72 at
543.29.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
