<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Braun To Receive German Prize  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARMSTADT, Germany (AP) -- Volker Braun, an author from the
former East Germany who predicted the fall of that communist
country's society, is to be awarded Germany's top literary honor,
the Academy for Languages and Poetry said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Braun, 60, a socialist who developed into a strong critic of the
Stalinist East German system, is to receive the $30,000 George
Buechner Prize in Darmstadt in October, academy spokeswoman Corinna
Blattmann said.
</P>
<P>
   The academy announced its decision during a meeting in Krakow,
Poland, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Braun's 1987 book, ''The Temporary Society,'' predicted East
Germany's demise two years before the Berlin Wall fell in November
1989.
</P>
<P>
   Other works he wrote were suppressed and not available to the
public. Those include the 1970 documentary ''Lenin's Death,'' which
described the depressing reality in post-revolutionary Russia. It
was unavailable until 1988.
</P>
<P>
   The author is seen as an excellent representative of East German
literature and a literary pioneer in foreseeing the changes that
took place there, the academy said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
