<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Wants Syrian Proposals  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The standoff in peacemaking between Israel and
Syria grew more intractable Friday as the Clinton administration
said it had no basis for reopening negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ''One needs something to work with,'' State Department spokesman
James Foley said, ''and right now we don't have that.''
</P>
<P>
   And in Damascus, Syrian Foreign Minister Farouk al-Sharaa was
quoted as saying the solution to making the peace process work is
in the hands of United States and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ball is in his court now,'' al-Sharaa said in reply to
President Clinton's statement Tuesday that the options for peace
are now before Syrian President Hafez Assad after their weekend
summit in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ball is not in Syria's court, but in Israel's court,''
al-Sharaa said in an interview with the Lebanese newspaper
Al-Mustaqbal. ''If we want to escalate, we might add that the ball
is also in America's court.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday's Clinton-Assad meeting in Switzerland had been
expected to produce Syrian agreement to resume peace negotiations
with Israel, which broke down in mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Sharaa said that at the summit, Clinton conveyed Israel's
demand for ''full sovereignty over the Jordan River waters and the
Sea of Galilee.'' Assad rejected the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Friday at the State Department, Foley would not discuss the
issues in dispute.
</P>
<P>
   He said, however, ''If we are going to be able to carry the ball
forward, we need some elaboration from the Syrian side'' on its
position.
</P>
<P>
   Assad has insisted on recovering all territory held by Syria
before it was defeated in the 1967 Middle East war. Clinton said
Tuesday that Israel has made ''very significant'' proposals, and
Assad has to say more in response.
</P>
<P>
   ''It may take time,'' Foley said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
