<HEADLINE> French NATO Officer Shot in Kosovo  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- A French officer in the NATO peacekeeping force in
Kosovo was shot to death by a fellow French soldier, NATO
peacekeepers said Friday. It was not immediately clear if the
shooting was an accident.
</P>
<P>
   The 29-year-old French lieutenant, whose name was not
immediately released, was shot Thursday night in the ethnically
divided city of Kosovska Mitrovica by a French soldier who had
recently arrived in Kosovo, Lt. Fabrice Turco said.
</P>
<P>
   The army spokesman said the attack did not appear to be linked
to military affairs, although the reasons behind it were still
unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The soldier accused in the shooting had enlisted two years ago
and served in previous missions abroad, said Lt. Col. Charles de
Kersabiec, an army spokesman. The soldier, whose name was not
released, was sent back to France for psychological reasons, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The two men were talking privately when people nearby heard
gunshots and rushed over, de Kersabiec said. The soldier
immediately claimed responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   French defense authorities in Kosovo have opened an inquiry into
the shooting.
</P>
</TEXT>
