<HEADLINE> Pay Soars for GM Boss and Top Execs  </HEADLINE>
By JUSTIN HYDE, AP Auto Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT (AP) -- A banner year for the American auto industry
resulted in banner year for salaries of top executives at General
Motors Corp., including chairman and CEO Jack Smith who saw his pay
more than double.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was paid $6.9 million in salary, bonus and dividends,
compared with $3.2 million in 1998. In addition, Smith cashed in
previously granted stock options worth $6 million, was given $5.25
million in stock under a long-term executive incentive plan and was
granted an estimated $7.9 million in stock options.
</P>
<P>
   Smith -- who will hand over the title of CEO on June 1 to G.
Richard Wagoner, currently GM's president -- had a total
compensation package worth about $26 million, compared with $12.4
million in 1998. The totals assume a current value for stock
options that could change based on future stock performance.
</P>
<P>
   Like most large corporations, top executive pay at GM is
determined in large part by formulas how each automaker met
financial and management goals for the year and, in the case of
stock options, over several years. Thanks to a record market for
new vehicles in the United States last year, GM hit most of its
targets, with earnings of $5.6 billion, up 87 percent over 1998,
when strikes shut down North American production.
</P>
<P>
   The compensation totals can also vary widely year to year based
on the amount of previously granted stock options the executive
decides to cash in and the extent to which the company's financial
performance affects long-term incentive plan payouts.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to last year's compensation, GM's board of directors
gave Smith a 5 percent raise at the beginning of the year, boosting
his base salary to $2.05 million.
</P>
<P>
   Compensation for Smith, Wagoner and three other top GM
executives are included in GM's annual proxy statement filed Friday
with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission:
</P>
<P>
   --Wagoner was paid $4.3 million in salary, bonus and dividends;
he also received stock options worth $4 million, was paid $2.25
million in stock under the long-term incentive plan, and cashed in
stock options worth $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   --Harry Pearce, GM's vice chairman, was paid $4.3 million in
salary, bonus and dividends; received stock options worth $3
million, was paid $2.25 million in stock under the long-term
incentive plan, and cashed in $683,000 in stock options.
</P>
<P>
   --J. Michael Losh, the chief financial officer, was paid $2.4
million in salary, bonus and dividends; received stock options
worth $1.8 million, was given $1.8 million in stock under the
long-term incentive plan and cashed in stock options worth $3.7
million.
</P>
<P>
   --Ron Zarella, GM's vice president for North America, was paid $2
million in salary, bonus and dividends; received stock options
worth $1.8 million, was given $1.5 million in stock under long-term
incentive plan and cashed in stock options worth $2.4 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
