<HEADLINE> Census Officials Await 'Census Day'  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- As lawmakers squabble over the intrusiveness
of questions, Census Bureau officials hope those who haven't yet
mailed back their forms will do so Saturday, Census Day.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau sent questionnaires to the country's 115 million
households in March, but officially they want to know how many
people are living in your home on April 1. That is because the
once-a-decade count must be tied to a specific point in time.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, 49 percent of census forms were mailed back.
Census officials hoped to get 70 percent of the forms back by late
April.
</P>
<P>
   Several congressional Republicans grumbled this week about the
intrusiveness of census forms, citing complaints from constituents
that the questionnaire invaded their privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Sen. Trent Lott of Mississippi, the Senate majority
leader, said they strongly urged people to return forms but
suggested that callers worried about privacy could leave intrusive
questions unanswered. That was a better solution than not returning
a form, Lott's staff said.
</P>
<P>
   Census director Kenneth Prewitt said he was unsure how the
controversy would affect the willingness of people to completely
fill out and return forms. Census officials were hoping for a spike
in the response rate after April 1, thinking some people may have
held on to their forms until then.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton called this year's census ''the largest
peacetime mobilization in our history.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The data collected will determine how more than $185 billion
annually in public funds are shared fairly'' as well as determining
apportionment of the House of Representatives, Clinton said in a
memo for federal employees.
</P>
<P>
   ''Census 2000 is an event that offers us an opportunity to
engage in the spirit of civic participation that is so important to
our representative democracy,'' Clinton said. He urged federal
employees to complete and return their census forms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
