<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State Dept. Clears Russia Oil Loans  </HEADLINE>
By HARRY DUNPHY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The State Department lifted its objections
Friday to loans that would help Russia's oil industry, clearing the
way for $500 million in funds to buy equipment from American
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeline Albright decision Friday came after
an ''extensive and deliberative process to ascertain the facts and
assess how circumstances were changing,'' since she imposed the ban
Dec. 21, said State Department spokesman James P. Foley.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to halt U.S. Export-Import Bank guarantees of loans
to Russia's Tyumen Oil Co. came made amid heavy fighting in
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   But Foley dismissed as coincidence the fact that Albright acted
just days after Vladamir Putin was elected Russia's new president.
Putin has pledged to bring order to the country and wants to create
a favorable climate for foreign and domestic investment.
</P>
<P>
   In December, administration officials denied that her decision
was related to strong U.S. objections to Russian military action
against Chechen rebels, although members of Congress and
presidential candidates had pushed for a halt to such loans at the
time.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers also had called for the bank to stop the loans because
of reports that the oil company forced a business with partial
American ownership into bankruptcy to obtain the giant Samotlor oil
field in western Siberia.
</P>
<P>
   Foley said Albright's action to block the loans had a tonic
effect, noting that Tyumen, then partially owned by the Russian
government, has since been successfully privatized. He said the
company, known as TNK, has begun negotiating with shareholders and
creditors of bankrupt companies involved in the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, TNK president Simon Kukes said the decision would
create thousands of American and Russian jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Broadly speaking, these projects will also help integrate
Russia even further into the world economy,'' Kukes said. The loans
are to be used for upgrading Tyumen's refinery near Moscow and for
rehabilitating the Siberian oil field.
</P>
<P>
   Foley said the United States has ''opened a dialogue with Russia
to impress on them the need to address weaknesses in their legal
system that led to abuses in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the decision on Tyumen doesn't mean that all
concerns about the protection of investor and creditor rights in
Russia have been addressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's obviously a work in progress,'' Foley said.
</P>
<P>
   The loans would be extended by private banks, with Ex-Im
guarantees. Proceeds would go to Halliburton Co. of Dallas and 24
other U.S. companies in payment for U.S-made oil and gas equipment
and services to be purchased by the Russians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 1647 </TRAILER>
