<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> USA Today Redesigning Paper  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- USA Today will have a new look on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The changes were described by the editor, Karen Jurgensen, in a
front-page story on Friday. They include the adoption of a new,
easier-to-read typeface and using a ''more consistent typographical
approach,'' such as putting all headlines in the same typeface.
</P>
<P>
   Jurgensen said the revamp was necessary in order to adapt the
newspaper to a new size that is 1\ inches narrower and a half-inch
longer, a format readers have found to be more appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the time required to adjust the newspaper's 36
printing presses throughout the world, some readers will see the
narrower format on the current paper size. The transition is
expected to take about six months.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Curley, president and publisher of USA Today, said that
considerations of cost as well as style were behind the decision.
The smaller format will require about 7 percent less newsprint, the
largest cost behind putting out a newspaper. But Curley also said
the paper's managers wanted the paper to have a different feel.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to tone down the graphics a bit,'' Curley said in
an interview. ''We feel that we have been shouting and that too
many people have been shouting to get attention, so we're making a
conscious effort to tone down.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the new typeface is more narrow, the paper will actually
be able to publish slightly more stories under the new format, even
though the size of the format is smaller. ''What we set out to do
was to make sure that the reader wouldn't lose any content,''
Curley said.
</P>
<P>
   Other newspapers have also gravitated toward using narrower
formats, such as the one used by the Washington Post. Last fall The
Fayetteville Observer of North Carolina moved to a narrower format,
and The Plain Dealer of Cleveland made the move a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   USA Today is the flagship of Gannett Co., the nation's largest
newspaper company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
