<HEADLINE> Workers Encouraged To Nap on Job  </HEADLINE>
By SUSANNE YOUMANS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Craig Yarde doesn't mind if his employees
sleep on the job.
</P>
<P>
   In fact Yarde, president of Yarde Metals Inc., is encouraging
workers at his Bristol headquarters to take a midday snooze Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Bringing a lawn chair or blanket of their own, employees will
get an eye mask to block out the light and a turkey sandwich, whose
ingredients have long been believed to bring on sleep.
</P>
<P>
   To help, fiddlers and guitarists will play soothing music.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're going to start off real mild and mellow,'' Yarde said,
then ''jazz it up'' at the end of the session so workers can head
back to work.
</P>
<P>
   The event is part of the first National Workplace Napping Day,
started by a Reading, Mass., couple who wrote two napping guides
and believe the breaks boost productivity and employee morale.
</P>
<P>
   ''The nap is just wonderful for any employee who feels that
tired, draggy feeling in the beginning of the afternoon,'' said
Camille Anthony, who co-wrote the 1999 book, ''The Art of Napping
at Work,'' with her husband, Bill.
</P>
<P>
   Bill, executive director of the Psychiatric Rehabilitation
Center at Boston University, also wrote the 1997 tome, ''The Art of
Napping.''
</P>
<P>
   At least six companies across the nation and a group of students
at the College of William and Mary in Williamsburg, Va., have
signed on with the event, Camille Anthony said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we're trying to do is show ... it makes good sense for
companies, if they have employees who want to nap, to let them,''
said Anthony, who became a devotee of the power of naps while
working for a public relations firm.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the program's intent is to chip away at the negative
perception that taking a midday break equates with laziness,
Anthony said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not as if napping isn't already going on. People go to
the parking lot, to the bathroom,'' she said. ''If you want to
increase productivity, encourage employees to take a 10- to
30-minute nap. It'll be like having two work days.''
</P>
<P>
   Yarde, whose metal distribution and processing company has 400
employees in eight branches across the Northeast, said he expects
about 100 workers in Bristol to take part. It didn't take much
convincing for him to support the event.
</P>
<P>
   He has been a strong believer in employee perks, next month
planning to break ground on a facility in Pelham, N.H., which will
include kennels for workers' dogs, a coffee-roasting room, gym and
children's play area. He hopes to open a similar facility by year's
end in Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   ''Associate loyalty is priceless,'' he said. ''The customer side
is important, but if we can motivate the associates here ... we can
still make money and everybody's happy and motivated.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Information on the books by Bill and Camille Anthony
and National Nap at Work Day can be found at
http://www.napping.com/napping-day.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 1653 </TRAILER>
