<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 16:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chiapas Bishop Honors Predecessor  </HEADLINE>
By ALEJANDRO RUIZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) -- The newly appointed
bishop for this conflict-ridden region of Mexico's Chiapas state
said Friday he would not challenge the work of his controversial
predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am conscious of the fact that I'm not going to San Cristobal
de las Casas to compete with or destroy, but to complement,''
Felipe Arizmendi Ezquivel said of retiring Bishop Samuel Ruiz
Garcia. ''I value the illustrious 40-year episcopal commitment of
Monsignor Samuel Ruiz.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Friday, Pope John Paul II named Arizmendi to succeed
Ruiz, 75.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz became known among supporters as the ''bishop of the poor''
for his work with poverty-stricken and exploited Indian peasants.
But the government and conservatives harshly criticized Ruiz,
linking him with Zapatista rebels and dubbing him the ''red
bishop'' for what they considered to be his socialist views.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatistas staged a brief uprising in Chiapas in January
1994 to demand democracy and Indian rights. Peace talks are
stalemated.
</P>
<P>
   Arizmendi, who is currently the bishop of Tapachula on the
Chiapas coast, is known as a moderate with some conservative
positions. He has sharply criticized the Zapatista National
Liberation Army for choosing to wage an armed rebellion.
Nonetheless, he also has supported Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz expressed his confidence that Arizmendi would continue his
pastoral work in the indigenous communities, saying he is a bishop
committed to the peace process. Arizmendi will assume his new
duties May 1, Ruiz said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
