<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Spain's Almodovar Blase About Oscar  </HEADLINE>
by DANIEL WOOLLS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADRID, Spain (AP) -- Now that Spanish film director Pedro
Almodovar has won an Oscar, he'd like people to stop talking about
it and get on with their lives. He certainly plans to.
</P>
<P>
   Winning Hollywood's top honor was great, he told a sea of
reporters Friday. So was rubbing elbows with stars and being
treated like a king.
</P>
<P>
   But Almodovar wants to get back to writing and directing cinema
-- he has three screenplays in the works -- and also to the pleasures
of doing nothing.
</P>
<P>
   After a heady year watching his film ''All About My Mother''
(Todo Sobre Mi Madre) land a number of prizes, culminating in
Sunday's Oscar for best foreign film, Almodovar wants to relax a
bit. He wants to watch TV, or see friends, or take in somebody
else's flick.
</P>
<P>
   More than anything, though, he wants other Spaniards to cut out
all the chatter about him, his movie and his statuette.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would like very much for the whole subject of 'Todo Sobre mi
Madre' and the Oscar to be put to rest, ideally right after this
press conference, because there is nothing left to say,'' Almodovar
said.
</P>
<P>
   He added: ''I was nominated for an Oscar. I won. It was
marvelous. But there's not much else to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Almodovar, 48, declined to reveal anything about his next movie,
saying he himself did not know which of his three unfinished
screenplays would make it onto the screen first.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that for the time being he has no interest in
making movies in Hollywood, and fired off a barb at the Oscar
ceremony organizers.
</P>
<P>
   He said they treated him disrespectfully by rushing him off
stage when his acceptance speech, pronounced in heavily accented
English and with odd references to saints and virgins, ran
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's simple. They cut me off,'' Almodovar said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The ceremony is geared mainly toward Americans watching it in
on television,'' he said. ''Naturally, the awards for best
short-length movie, documentary or foreign film don't matter much
to them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
