<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Civilian Control for Engineers Corps  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Pentagon is making management changes in
the embattled Army Corps of Engineers aimed at restoring civilian
control and increasing accountability.
</P>
<P>
   Army Secretary Louis Caldera announced the changes, which
followed allegations that top Corps officers doctored data to
justify the $1 billion cost of lengthening seven locks on the
Mississippi and Illinois rivers. Internal documents that a Corps
whistle-blower included with an affidavit alleging the impropriety
suggested the agency is intent on enlarging its construction
budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Corps' $4 billion civil works program has been officially
under the Army assistant secretary since the 1980s, but Pentagon
control over Corps decision-making has deteriorated over the years,
Army spokesman Jim Stueve said.
</P>
<P>
   Caldera said effective immediately all final decisions on Corps
project recommendations will be by Joseph Westphal, the Army's
assistant secretary for civil works. Corps military leaders also
are banned from lobbying Congress on their own, and Caldera shifted
responsibility for evaluating top Corps officials to Westphal from
the Corps' military commander, Lt. Gen. Joe Ballard.
</P>
<P>
   ''My purpose in making these changes is to support the Corps of
Engineers ... and to ensure that decisions are timely, objective,
fair and deserving of the full confidence of the American public,''
Caldera said in a statement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary William Cohen sent a letter to ''strongly
endorse'' Caldera's efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Some congressional Republicans say Caldera's move was
unnecessary and could hamstring the Corps.
</P>
<P>
   ''My only concern is that civilian oversight ... could lead to a
little more politicizing of the issues,'' said Rep. John Shimkus,
R-Ill. ''I would hate to see us move rapidly until the full details
come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, who believe increased barge traffic and
construction would seriously damage the Upper Mississippi River
ecosystem, say the changes do not go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Faber, with Washington-based American Rivers, said the way
the Corps studies proposed projects should be fairer and more
environmentally conscious. He suggested requiring regular
independent reviews of cost-benefit analyses and a ban on projects
where the cost of mitigating for environmental damage is too high.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our concern is that the assistant secretary won't use his new
authority to reform the agency,'' Faber said. ''These are things he
could do tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   In a related move, Sen. George Voinovich, R-Ohio, asked the
General Accounting Office, Congress' investigative arm, to examine
the restoration projects on the Mississippi River and the
Everglades in Florida. He wants to see whether ''the objectivity
and standards of the Corps of Engineers are being compromised.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We must be able to continue to rely on the Corps of Engineers
to only recommend to the Congress those projects which make maximum
net positive contributions to economic development and
environmental quality,'' said Voinovich, chairman of the Senate
Subcommittee on Transportation and Infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   The allegations by Corps economist Donald Sweeney that started
the controversy prompted the federal Office of Special Counsel to
conclude the Corps probably violated the law and to order a full
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Caldera asked for a review by the Army inspector
general and the National Academy of Sciences and requested the
management study that yielded this week's changes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 1717 </TRAILER>
