<DOCNO> APW20000331.0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Income, Spending Both Rose in Feb.  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- American consumers, the driving force behind
the supercharged economy, spent with abandon in February at a pace
more than double their income growth. It dragged the personal
savings rate to a record low.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said Friday's report shows that the Federal Reserve
has not finished raising interest rates to slow the economy and
keep inflation from becoming a problem.
</P>
<P>
   Continuing their buying binge, Americans increased their
spending 1 percent last month, the fastest pace since December, the
Commerce Department said.
</P>
<P>
   People are feeling wealthy and in the mood to spend because jobs
are plentiful, incomes are rising, the stock market is strong and
inflation is low, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Consumers are buying anything and everything they can get
their hands on,'' said economist Mark Zandi of RFA Dismal Sciences.
''There's no significant constraint on consumer spending at this
point in time.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Americans' personal income, which includes wages,
interest and government benefits, increased by just 0.4 percent
last month, the slowest pace since December.
</P>
<P>
   With spending outpacing income growth, the rate of personal
savings, or savings as a percentage of after-tax income, fell to
0.8 percent in February, a record monthly low. In January, the rate
was 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the savings rate isn't as dire as it would seem, economists
said. The savings rate measures only the amount of money being put
aside each month for savings.
</P>
<P>
   It does not represent a calculation of personal wealth, which
would account for gains households have realized on their savings
in previous months from such as rising stock market values and
higher real estate values for their homes. Thus, the savings rate
reflects money socked into a 401(k) but it doesn't capture an
increase or decrease in its value.
</P>
<P>
   The rising value of investments with the booming stock market
has contributed to the low national savings rate because consumers
feel more confident that they can afford to save less and spend
more because their investments are doing well.
</P>
<P>
   However, economists caution that the economy could be in for a
shock if the stock market suddenly were to plunge and trigger a
sharp cutback in consumer spending, which accounts for two-thirds
of total economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average gave up solid
early gains to close down 58.33 points to 10,921.92. But the Nasdaq
finished the day higher.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve boosted interest rates last week for a fifth
time since June 30 to slow the speeding economy, which grew at a
breakneck 7.3 percent rate in the final three months of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the higher rates made borrowing more expensive for
consumers and businesses, they haven't yet significantly slowed the
economy or its main engine, consumer spending.
</P>
<P>
   Given that, many economists believe the central bank will bump
up rates again on May 16.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the type of report that has to truly worry (Fed)
members as there are no signs that the 'Shop till you drop, and
then pick yourself up so you can shop some more' philosophy has
changed at all,'' said economist Joel Naroff of Naroff Economic
Advisors. ''This economy is still red-hot, and the Fed is going to
do more, maybe a lot more, to cool the flames.''
</P>
<P>
   Stan Shipley, economist for Merrill Lynch, estimated that the
economy is growing at a 5.5 percent rate in the current quarter,
slower than the previous quarter but still much faster than what
the Fed believes is prudent.
</P>
<P>
   Most consumer spending last month was on durable goods,
big-ticket items expected to last at least three years, such as
cars, which rose 1.5 percent. Spending on nondurable goods, such as
food and fuel, grew by 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The report also showed that Americans' wages grew by 0.3 percent
in February, while farm proprietors' income rose by 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In January, total income grew by 0.7 percent, while total
spending increased by 0.6 percent, slightly higher than the
government previously reported. It was the first time since October
that income rose faster than spending.
</P>
<P>
   In another report, orders to U.S. factories were down for the
second month in a row, falling a smaller-than-expected 0.8 percent
in February. But economists said it's too early to view this as a
sign of a slowdown in the economy. Orders for airplanes and other
transportation equipment led the decline with a 8.9 percent plunge,
the steepest drop in 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The personal income and spending report:
http://www.bea.doc.gov/bea/newsrel/pi0200.htm
</P>
<P>
   Factory orders report: http://www.census.gov/indicator/www/m3
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 1726 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
