<DOCNO> APW20000331.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xerox To Eliminate 5,200 Jobs  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Business machines giant Xerox Corp.,
struggling to compete in both the large and small office markets,
plans to slash 5,200 jobs, close manufacturing plants and take a
$625 million charge against earnings in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The job cuts represent 5.5 percent of the company's worldwide
work force of 94,600.
</P>
<P>
   ''While these are difficult actions for our people, Xerox can no
longer operate business as usual and expect to win,'' said Rick
Thoman, the Xerox president and chief executive. ''We're
intensifying our drive to become a faster, leaner and more flexible
enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Thoman said the marketplace has changed from the days when the
company was a leader in photocopying technology.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox said the cutbacks will help the company focus on its two
core markets: business machines such as copiers for home and
medium-sized offices, and larger systems that enable big companies
to organize and share information in the form of digital documents.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement had been expected for months. Xerox said in
January that an overhaul was coming, and analysts this week had
predicted deep job cuts and a restructuring charge of as much as
$900 million.
</P>
<P>
   The moves were praised by analysts, who said Xerox needs to make
the cuts to compete with Hewlett-Packard and Canon. But Xerox stock
dropped 2 percent Friday on the New York Stock Exchange, falling
56\ cents to close at $26 a share.
</P>
<P>
   ''They are going to try their best to compete in any way
possible, not just by cutting but also by announcing new
products,'' said Marjorie Saint-Aime, an analyst with brokerage
firm Pittsburg Institutional Inc. ''They are going in the right
direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Runkle, an analyst with Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, said
the company is making the right moves, but may need to go further.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the key here is that the company needs to recreate an
infrastructure that is more efficient, lower-cost and (one) that
generates higher returns, which goes far beyond just taking out
some general and administrative costs,'' Runkle said.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement Friday was the company's fourth major
restructuring in the last decade. In 1998, the company took a $1.1
billion charge and cut about 9,000 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox said none of the cuts in the latest overhaul will affect
its sales force or research and development efforts. The company's
struggle to realign its sales force along industry lines rather
than geographical boundaries has been blamed in part for its
disappointing performance in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The company's profits fell 52 percent in the fourth quarter,
with revenue down 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company has said it expects to see another decline in
earnings in the first quarter, which ended Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The $625 million charge includes about $175 million for closing
facilities and scrapping some of the company's inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox spokesman Jeff Simek said some manufacturing plants will
be closed, along with some warehouse and distribution facilities.
Simek would not say where plants will be closed.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox said the job cuts would affect all work levels and
geographic areas, with more than half coming from offices in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The job cuts will hit especially hard at Rochester, N.Y., the
company's manufacturing hub. Xerox said about 2,000 out of 14,650
jobs in the Rochester region will be eliminated. The company's
cross-town rival, Eastman Kodak Co., has eliminated 6,300 jobs in
Rochester over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Simek said jobs will be eliminated across the board, but the
hardest-hit ranks will be U.S. upper- and middle-management, which
will be cut by 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Employees at the company's headquarters were reluctant to talk
about the job cuts.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, who would not give her name, said the cutbacks would
be good for the company in the long run.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know we're going to have some cuts, but it's very important
for us (as a company),'' she said. ''I know we're going to do
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Xerox, traditionally a high-end copier company, in the last few
years has made a move to become a major player in the home office
and small business environment, through low-end retail channels
such as Staples and Office Max.
</P>
<P>
   In September, the company announced it would buy the color
printing division of Tektronix Inc. for $950 million in a deal that
will make Xerox second only to Hewlett-Packard in the office color
printing market.
</P>
<P>
   Xerox also announced a $2 billion alliance with Sharp and Fuji
Xerox to develop and manufacture inkjet products for small and home
offices.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.xerox.com
</P>
</TEXT>
