<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans, Gold, Silver Rise  </HEADLINE>
By HERBERT G. McCANN, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were higher Friday on the
Chicago Board of Trade, with weather worries influencing trading in
the market.
</P>
<P>
   The market also received support from the release before the
start of trading of the U.S. Agriculture Department's quarterly
stock report and planting estimates.
</P>
<P>
   In other markets, gold and silver futures recovered some of the
week's losses and sugar futures prices were higher.
</P>
<P>
   Soybean futures rose to close at their highest price in nearly a
year. The market was bolstered by forecasts of dry weather into the
middle of next week.
</P>
<P>
   Also boosting soybean prices was USDA data showing soybean
stocks totaled 1.39 billion bushels, lower than analysts estimates
of 1.4 billion bushels. However, the government also estimated
soybean planting would total 74.87 million acres, an increase from
last year's 73.78 million acres.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Joe Victor of Allendale Inc. noted that farmers usually
plant anywhere from 500,000 to 1 million more acres than the
government's initial estimate.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat futures prices were boosted by worries about possible
freeze damage next week to the hard red winter wheat crop, with
cold weather forecast for parts of the Great Plains.
</P>
<P>
   The USDA reports wheat stocks total 1.4 billion bushels as of
March 1 -- Analysts say that is smaller than the market expected.
The USDA also estimates 14.8 million acres of wheat will be planted
this year, down from last year's 15.3 million acres.
</P>
<P>
   Corn futures prices were higher despite weather forecasts
calling for weekend rain in crop-producing areas of the Midwest.
The USDA's acreage and quarterly stock data for corn was considered
neutral, according to analysts.
</P>
<P>
   It is estimated 77.8 million acres of corn will be planted this
year, only slightly above last year's 77.4 million acres. The USDA
placed corn stocks at 5.6 million bushels.
</P>
<P>
   Wheat for May delivery was 6} cents higher at $2.62\ a bushel;
May corn was 2} cents higher at $2.36 a bushel; May oats were 1\
cents higher at $1.22\ a bushel; May soybeans were 8 cents higher
at 5.45{ a bushel.
</P>
<P>
   Gold futures prices were higher in trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange, with the modest gains attributed to the
weakness of the U.S dollar against the Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
   Silver gained as investors viewed the metal a bargain after its
price dropped below $5.
</P>
<P>
   Gold and silver prices were hurt earlier in the week by the
renewed strength of the stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   June gold was $2.30 higher at $281.40 a troy ounce, May silver
was 6.2 cents higher at $5.045 a troy ounce.
</P>
<P>
   Sugar futures prices, driven by commodity fund buying, moved
higher in trading on the New York Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Demand from several Asian nations gave a lift to the market, as
did ideas world supplies will shrink as several producing nations
cutback acreage.
</P>
<P>
   May sugar was .35 cent higher at 5.90 cents a pound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
