<P>
   Net2Phone Backed by 3 Big Firms
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp., Yahoo! Inc. and America Online Inc.
are making big investments in Net2Phone Inc., propelling an upstart
provider of cheap phone calls via the Web to the forefront of
efforts to merge voice and computer networks. In addition to
cementing relationships with several of the most prominent
providers of consumer services on the World Wide Web, the deals
announced today may help forge Net2Phone's technology as a standard
for the way phone calls are carried over the hodgepodge of data
networks that make up the Internet. Net2Phone, based in Hackensack,
N.J., is a pioneer in enabling people to use their personal
computers and Internet connections to avoid costly charges from
local and long-distance carriers. Net2Phone shares were at 59[, up
3}.
</P>
<P>
   Intel Escapes $600M IRS Bill
</P>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Intel Corp., the world's largest
computer chip maker, said it would post a first-quarter gain of 17
cents a share after an Internal Revenue Service review found it did
not owe $600 million in taxes. The company said yesterday it had
set aside the money in the event it had a tax liability regarding
how it allocated profits between national and international
divisions. The gain will be posted when earnings are released April
18.
</P>
<P>
   Prognosis Is Dim for DrKoop.com
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Shares of the Internet health company DrKoop.com
Inc. plunged today after the company's accountant said the Internet
firm may not survive. In the company's annual report filed late
yesterday with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
PricewaterhouseCoopers LLC said Drkoop.com has sustained losses and
negative cash flows from operations since its inception. And the
auditor expressed ''substantial doubt'' about the company's ability
to continue as a going concern. Koop stock was down 2 9/16, or 41
percent, at 3 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Personal Income Rises in February
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP -- Personal income went up in February but
spending rose more than twice as fast, pulling the nation's savings
rate down to an all-time monthly low. The Commerce Department said
today personal income -- wages, interest and government benefits --
increased by 0.4 percent last month. Spending wasup 1.0 percent. In
another report, the Commerce department said orders to U.S.
factories were down for the second straight month, falling a
smaller-than-expected 0.8 percent in February. Orders for airplanes
and other transportation equipment took their biggest plunge in 10
months, dropping 8.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   OPEC Said To Seek $22-$28 Oil Price
</P>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- OPEC plans to increase oil output
whenever the price of the cartel's crude basket exceeds $28 a
barrel and lower output when the price dips below $22, Venezuelan
Oil Minister Ali Rodriguez said today. Rodriguez, the new president
of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, said the
price-band plan was approved by OPEC members during their meeting
earlier this week in Vienna, Austria. The system, which will allow
quick supply changes to keep oil prices within a set range, had
been proposed by Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread Rail Track Defects Found
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- CSX Transportation announced an internal
review of its track maintenance today after federal railroad
inspectors found deteriorating conditions in its system used by
passenger, freight and commuter trains up and down the East Coast.
The Federal Railroad Administration had begun a special safety
audit of the railroad in February after a series of derailments.
George Gavalla, associate administrator for safety, said the agency
audited CSX in 1997 and became concerned because it hadn't seen a
reduction in derailments and other problems. John W. Snow, chairman
and chief executive officer of CSX Corporation, responded that his
company ''has repaired or is in the process of repairing all of the
defects identified in the report. The company said Snow will
personally head an internal company review of all track maintenance
and improvement programs.
</P>
<P>
   H&AMP;M Opens First U.S. Store
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Hennes &AMP; Mauritz opened its first U.S. store
today, attracting thousands of shoppers who were eager to grab up
the cheap-yet-chic clothes from the popular Swedish chain. From
curious New Yorkers to European tourists, they piled into H&AMP;M's
store on tony Fifth Avenue, combing through the racks filled with
fashionable $9 shirts and $20 pairs of pants. The enthusiastic
crowd offered a temporary distraction from troubles that beset H&AMP;M
last week, when its chief executive quit and the company reported a
12 percent drop in projected quarterly profits. Stockholm-based H&AMP;M
has built a strong reputation for offering trendy fashions at
affordable prices.
</P>
<P>
   De Beers Certifies Diamond Sources
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- De Beers, the South African conglomerate that
dominates the world diamond trade, has begun selling stones with a
guarantee that they don't come from rebels in Angola or other
African countries. The certification process began this week, but
an unrelated legal dispute means De Beers isn't selling diamonds
from any source in Angola for the time being. The United Nations
has been exerting pressure for a cutoff of the financial resources
of Angolan rebel leader Jonas Savimbi.
</P>
<P>
   Farmers To Cut Biotech Plantings
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Farmers are turning away from genetically
engineered crops, especially a biotech corn that's toxic to
insects, amid consumer resistance that started overseas and is now
being felt in the United States. Plantings of the gene-altered corn
are projected to drop 24 percent this year, according to findings
of an Agriculture Department survey released today. The report also
suggested declines in biotech varieties of cotton and soybeans.
''We don't want to go out here and spend any more money ... than we
absolutely have to,'' said Allan Morris, who farms near Mason, Ill.
Biotech crops had caught on quickly in the late 1990s despite the
relatively high cost of the seed.
</P>
