<HEADLINE> Trinity College students avoid jail  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN, 
o0055nyc--
r n AM-CT--TrinityDrugDeath 1stLd-Writethru 480 03-31 0548
AM-CT--Trinity Drug Death, 1st Ld-Writethru, 480   
Trinity College students avoid jail   
Eds: INSERTS new graf 9 bgn ''These young... to ADD quote from
Trinity. Picks up graf 9 prvs bgn ''Eaves and.   
jcstfsy   
By JOHN CHRISTOFFERSEN
Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A dumbfounded Superior Court judge asked
two Trinity College students Friday why they participated in a drug
binge that left a classmate dead only months before graduation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why does a young man with brains, with a future ... what in
the world possessed you and your friends to make this drug cocktail
mixed with alcohol?,'' Judge Howard Scheinblum asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a severe lack of judgment,'' responded William Bachman,
a senior from Natick, Mass., who has been suspended and may not
graduate. ''I wish with all my heart I could take it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Joshua Eaves, a senior from Downingtown, Pa., who was expelled
from Trinity, said he and his friends had taken the opportunities
given them for granted.
</P>
<P>
   ''I realize now that is the most horrendous of offenses,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered Bachman to undergo drug and alcohol treatment
and Eaves to participate in drug treatment. He also agreed to allow
the students to make charitable contributions in lieu of community
service.
</P>
<P>
   The students, who were charged with possession of narcotics,
avoided jail time. Their cases were continued while they complete
their programs and if they stay out of trouble for a year, their
records will be wiped clean.
</P>
<P>
   ''These young men could have paid for their actions with their
lives,'' said Trinity spokeswoman Linda Campanella. ''One of their
close friends did. We are very pleased they are alive and that they
will be getting help.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaves and Bachman, both 22, were among four roommates who were
drinking and doing drugs in their dormitory room on March 17.
Authorities said the students apparently had mixed prescription
anti-anxiety drugs, sleeping pills and a migraine medication and
also may have taken heroin.
</P>
<P>
   One of the students, 22-year-old Joshua Doroff of Harrison,
N.Y., died after friends brought him to the Hartford Hospital
emergency room. The other student, Clement ''Nick'' Kaupp III, of
Mendham, N.J., had been in critical condition for several days
after the binge.
</P>
<P>
   Kaupp, 22, is scheduled to appear in court on April 11 on a
charge of possession of narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   During Bachman's case, the judge said he would grant the
applications for treatment because the student had no prior record,
there was no evidence he had anything to do with Doroff's death and
he may not be able to graduate from Trinity. He also noted that the
student had volunteered as a tutor.
</P>
<P>
   Eaves' attorney, Gerald Klein, noted that his client was
expelled from college and lost a close friend. Klein said heroin
residue was found in the dorm room.
</P>
<P>
   ''If that's not shock therapy, then I don't know what is,''
Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   After court, Eaves vowed to change his life.
</P>
<P>
   ''I miss my best friend very dearly,'' Eaves said. ''My life is
at rock bottom now but at least I have a life.''
</P>
<P>
   Eaves' parents, Rebecca and Willard Eaves, said they were sorry
for the death of Doroff.
</P>
<P>
   ''But for the grace of God, there could have been four of
them,'' Willard Eaves said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
