<HEADLINE> Gore Agrees to Foreign Policy Debate  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Al Gore accepted an invitation to an April
foreign policy debate with George W. Bush on Friday, even though
the Texas governor has said repeatedly it's still way too early.
</P>
<P>
   ''We hope he will reconsider his decision,'' Gore spokesman Doug
Hattaway said in a statement. ''Bush still has the opportunity to
agree to Gore's challenge to drop radio and TV ads and hold regular
debates on the issues.
</P>
<P>
   The debate has been proposed by CNN and the Council on Foreign
Relations. It was scheduled to run 60 minutes in late April and
feature questions from journalists and international affairs
experts.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Scott McClellan said, ''There'll be plenty of
time for debates when the voters are paying attention to the
election. There will be debates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
