<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 18:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AM-NJ--World Bank Protest, Bjt,550  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORHAM PARK, N.J. (AP) -- Hundreds of activists planned a
Saturday rally outside a World Bank and International Monetary Fund
conference, touting the protest as ''picking up where Seattle left
off.''
</P>
<P>
   Organizers of the New Jersey/New York Mobilization for Global
Justice said protesters did not plan to disrupt the weekend
meetings sponsored by the two organizations and the Brookings
Institute.
</P>
<P>
   But two women who were part of the World Trade Organization
protests in Seattle in December were arrested Thursday for
unfurling a 40-foot banner from the top of the Hamilton Park
Conference Center.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Kuhn, 19, of Salt Lake City and Judith Karpova, 54, of
Hoboken were charged with criminal trespassing, criminal mischief,
and possession of burglary tools, authorities said. The two used
bolt cutters to cut the chain on a trap door to the roof of the
hotel before unfurling the banner that read ''World Bank and IMF 
Corporate Colonialism'', authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Rally organizer Ted Glick said the coalition didn't advocate
violence or civil disobedience, but ''a number of us thought that
was a nice action.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Ultimately, we can't stop them,'' he said of groups who may
decide to protest more forcefully.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 officers, some with horses and police dogs, have
been patrolling the conference center near Morristown since the
conference began on Thursday, said Steven Foley, a spokesman for
the Morris County Prosecutor's Office. Police erected metal
barricades and first aid tents and videotaped protesters from a
hotel window.
</P>
<P>
   Foley said the preparations were precautionary, but a reaction
to the violence and destruction that paralyzed Seattle sessions of
the World Trade Organization. Those protests caused $2.5 million in
damage, a state of emergency in the city and the arrests of 500
protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Activists, in a news release, said the protest here would be
''picking up where Seattle left off.''
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of people are expected to protest on April
16-18 at World Bank and IMF meetings in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition blames the WTO, the World bank and the IMF for
globalization of the world economy. They believe the World Bank and
the IMF, charged with using international corporations to try to
improve life in developing countries, instead throw the countries
into debt while enriching corporations and degrading the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people attending the conference are meeting to discuss
the collapse of economies in Asia and its effect on developing
countries. Bank spokesman Andrew Kircher said the bank has noticed
a rising level of awareness of the meetings in the United States,
especially since the Seattle protests.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters began a vigil on Thursday, and four slept by the
side of the road Thursday night, surrounded by signs with messages
like ''Break the Boomerang of Debt'' and ''Honk for Global
Justice.'' On Friday, mounted police, including officials standing
on the hotel roof with binoculars, outnumbered the 20 or so
protesters that marched about a mile from a teach-in on Drew
University's campus.
</P>
<P>
   Police will keep protesters inside a barricaded parking lot on
the campus of Fairleigh Dickinson University next to the conference
center on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
