<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Extend Their Gains  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices extended gains Friday, sending the
yield on long-term Treasurys sliding to the lowest level in 10
months.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond rose | point,
or $6.25 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the
opposite direction, fell to 5.83 percent from 5.87 percent late
Thursday. That's the lowest rate since it closed at that level on
May 28, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Bond prices have risen in recent days as investors seek the
safety of fixed-rate government bonds as a haven for their funds
from the turbulence on the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, bonds gained on end-of-quarter adjustments to
portfolios by investment fund managers.
</P>
<P>
   In the broader bond market, prices of short-term and
intermediate Treasury securities also rose. Short-term notes rose
1/32 point to 1/16 point, while intermediate notes rose 3/32 point
to 5/16 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial information
service.
</P>
<P>
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 5.88 percent as the
discount rose 0.01 percentage point from Thursday to 5.71 percent.
Six-month yields were 6.15 percent, as the discount rose 0.01
percentage point to 5.88 percent. One-year yields were 6.25 percent
as the discount rose 0.02 percentage point to 5.90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the
discount is the interest at which they are sold.
</P>
<P>
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, fell to 6.18} percent from 6.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively
traded municipal bonds rose [ to 95 15/32. The average yield to
maturity fell to 5.97 percent from 5.98 percent Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
