<HEADLINE> Bausch &AMP; Lomb Bids For Wesley Jessen  </HEADLINE>
By BEN DOBBIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) -- After failing to negotiate a buyout of
Wesley Jessen VisionCare Inc., Bausch &AMP; Lomb Inc. is going straight
to the cosmetic contact-lens company's shareholders in a bid to
gain control.
</P>
<P>
   Bausch &AMP; Lomb, which has strength in premium disposable lenses,
said Friday it will commence a tender offer Monday for all
outstanding shares of Des Plaines, Ill.-based Wesley Jessen at a
price of $34 a share in cash.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed purchase price amounts to a 37 percent premium over
Wesley Jessen's stock price on March 22 when Bausch &AMP; Lomb made an
unsolicited offer to buy the cosmetic color lens maker for $600
million.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Wesley Jessen have since risen past that level,
finishing regular trading at $35.93}, down 31\ cents on Friday.
Shares of Bausch &AMP; Lomb rose $3.18} to $52.18} on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiations had been under way for a few weeks when Wesley
Jessen, preferring to take its own expansionist route, announced
March 20 it had agreed to buy Ocular Sciences Inc., a rival contact
lens maker in South San Francisco, for $413 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Surprised by the move, Bausch &AMP; Lomb said it had no interest in
acquiring Ocular Sciences and moved instead to take its offer
directly to Wesley Jessen shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Once its tender offer is complete -- if successful, the process
could take weeks or even months -- the company said it intends to
acquire any shares not purchased in the tender offer for the same
cash price.
</P>
<P>
   Bausch &AMP; Lomb's chief executive, William Carpenter, said he
would still prefer to negotiate ''a mutually acceptable transaction
in which Wesley Jessen management would become part of our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, Wesley Jessen rejected Bausch &AMP; Lomb's takeover
offer as inadequate and said it remained committed to its pending
merger with Ocular Sciences.
</P>
<P>
   Wesley Jessen controls about two-thirds of the highly profitable
cosmetic color-lens market. It had $311.7 million in sales last
year while Bausch &AMP; Lomb had contact-lens revenues of $475 million.
</P>
<P>
   If Bausch &AMP; Lomb grabs control of Wesley Jessen, it would come
within distance of market leader Johnson &AMP; Johnson, which had about
$900 million in contact-lens revenues in 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 1820 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
