<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nasdaq Is Up 114.94; Dow Off 58.33  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks came back from the brink
Friday, pulling the Nasdaq composite index higher for the first
time this week. But investors turned toward well-established
computer makers and networking companies, and shunned Internet
businesses now seen as risky investments at the end of a volatile
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index rose 114.94 to close at 4,572.83. In
earlier trading, the Nasdaq had fallen as much as 76 points and
appeared to be in danger of extending its losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq finished the week with a loss of 390 points, and is
9.4 percent below its March 10 record high close of 5,048.62.
</P>
<P>
   But even after its recent slump, the Nasdaq ended the first
quarter with a 12.4 percent gain. The Dow Jones industrial average
fell 5 percent during the quarter, while the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
rose 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, the Dow average gave up solid early gains and closed
down 58.33 at 10,921.92. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 10.66 to
1,498.58.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq rose as investors bought stocks that were beaten down
in this week's technology selloff. Stalwarts like Dell Computer, up
1} to 53 15/16, and Intel, up 4 15/16 to 131 15/16, led the
advancers.
</P>
<P>
   Investors also embraced companies that build the infrastructure
of computers and the Internet. Cisco Systems gained 3 11/16 to 77
5/16 and JDS Uniphase rose 4 5/16 to 120 9/16.
</P>
<P>
   But in light of technology stocks' disastrous performance this
week, investors were exercising extreme caution, said Charles
White, president and portfolio manager at Avatar Associates in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ''The stocks doing well today are the ones you've always wanted
to own, the ones with good products, strong revenues and solid
business models,'' he said. ''The companies without those
attributes are going to have a very hard time for the foreseeable
future.''
</P>
<P>
   White pointed to drkoop.com, the online health information
provider, which fell 41 percent, or by 2 9/16 to 3 11/16, after
auditors questioned the viability of the company.
</P>
<P>
   E.Spire Communications, a struggling provider of Internet access
and phone services, fell for a second consecutive session after
saying it might not have enough cash to continue its operations and
repay its loans through the end of this year. Shares fell 2 21/32
to 7 1/32.
</P>
<P>
   Business-to-business Internet companies declined broadly after
Prudential Securities downgraded several stocks in the sector.
Ariba fell 10] to 209|.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one will argue that technology stocks are cheap, but some
are more justifiable than others,'' White said. ''You have to be
selective.''
</P>
<P>
   The resurgence of the Nasdaq drew some money out of the
blue-chip stocks that have performed well this week. General
Electric fell 3[ to 155|.
</P>
<P>
   Conseco fell about 16 percent, or by 2\ to 11 7/16, after the
insurance and financial services company said it will record a $350
million charge and may sell its consumer finance unit.
</P>
<P>
   The market was somewhat rattled in early trading by a pair of
economic reports that provided a mixed picture of the economy's
strength.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department reported personal income rose 0.4
percent in February but that Americans' spending rose more than
twice as fast. That pulled the nation's savings rate down to an
all-time monthly low, and fed expectations that the Federal Reserve
will raise interest rates at least once more this year in its bid
to slow the economy to sustainable levels.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are no signs of any significant slowdown for consumer
spending,'' said Stan Shipley, senior economist at Merrill Lynch.
''The economy is clearly growing too fast for the Fed.''
</P>
<P>
   Some market watchers drew encouragement from a second report
that showed orders to U.S. factories were down for the second
straight month in February.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 2-to-1 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange. On the Nasdaq, three stocks rose for every
two that fell.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 1.46 billion shares, compared with 1.43
billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 7.53 to 539.09.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.5 percent.
Germany's Xetra DAX index fell 0.6 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100
rose 1.5 percent, and France's CAC-40 fell 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
