<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tobacco Lawyer Urges Objectivity  </HEADLINE>
By CATHERINE WILSON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A tobacco company attorney asked jurors Friday to
set aside any bias they might have against an unpopular industry
and reject the $14.4 million in damage claims by three smokers with
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The smokers' attorney suggested the jury should ''just bury
these tobacco companies,'' Philip Morris Inc. attorney Dan Webb
said in closing arguments. But he told jurors that the smokers,
rather than the nation's five biggest cigarette makers, ''must
accept the legal responsibility for the consequences of the choices
they made.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I know the tobacco companies on trial in this case are not
popular in this country today,'' Webb said, but he urged jurors to
set aside ''your biases, your sympathy and your prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury decided in July that the industry fraudulently
conspired to produce a dangerous product and will be asked next
week whether the smokers are entitled to compensatory damages.
</P>
<P>
   If the jury awards any money, it will hear more evidence on
punitive damages for about 500,000 sick Florida smokers covered by
the lawsuit. The industry, which already owes states about $250
billion, fears a $300 billion punitive award.
</P>
<P>
   The jury will be asked to set damages for the medical bills,
lost income, lost services, pain and suffering from lung cancer in
Mary Farnan and the late Angie Della Vecchia and throat cancer in
Frank Amodeo.
</P>
<P>
   Focusing on Farnan, R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. attorney Ben Reid
cited defense testimony that bronchioalveolar cancer -- a form of
lung cancer that the jury did not blame on smoking -- was the kind
of cancer in her case.
</P>
<P>
   Smokers' witnesses blamed smoking for all three of their
cancers.
</P>
<P>
   Noting 50 million Americans have quit smoking, Reid rejected
nicotine addiction as an issue, saying: ''There's nothing about
cigarettes that keeps people from quitting if they want to quit.''
The jury ruled last July that cigarettes are addictive.
</P>
<P>
   The defendants are Philip Morris, Reynolds, Brown &AMP; Williamson
Tobacco Corp., Lorillard Tobacco Co., Liggett Group Inc. and the
industry's Council for Tobacco Research and Tobacco Institute.
</P>
