<HEADLINE> Mayor shrugs off indictment, heads to golf course  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOUNT LAUREL, N.J. (AP) -- Camden Mayor Milton Milan stood at the
tee, gripped a 7 iron and promptly fired his ball into a creek.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm probably hitting them the best I ever hit them, at least
my short game,'' Milan joked Friday. ''I'm just here to relax.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-four hours earlier, Milan surrendered to federal
authorities who accused him of running a ''pay to play'' scheme
inside City Hall that netted him free cars, home improvements and
more than $30,000 in bribes from mobsters.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday morning he was at Ramblewood Country Club, a suburban
golf course about 10 miles from Camden, the nation's fifth-poorest
city.
</P>
<P>
   The round of golf was already scheduled and Milan said he saw no
reason not to play -- not even a 19-count indictment that linked him
to the head of Philadelphia's organized crime family.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel good, I'm not embarrassed, I'm not humiliated. There's
nothing they can't take from me,'' Milan said. ''That's the
difference between growing up in an urban city and not having
anything and growing up in a suburban community where you would
have everything whipped out from under you.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday U.S. Attorney Robert J. Cleary said Milan ''was
corrupted from the minute he set foot in City Hall.'' In a 54-page
indictment, the government alleges that Milan extorted public
officials, collected bribes, stole campaign funds and laundered
drug money.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday state Department of Community Affairs Commissioner
Jane Kenny said Milan's administration repeatedly ignored standard
financial practices. She gave the city two weeks to correct the
problems or else face consequences that could include a state
takeover.
</P>
<P>
   But Milan continued his public denials of all charges. He issued
denials on the steps of City Hall before turning himself in to
federal marshals. On the steps of the federal courthouse three
hours later after posting bail, Milan again denied the accusations.
</P>
<P>
   In a break in his golf match, Milan thanked his upbringing,
''the Marine Corps and the good Lord'' for the strength to be
upbeat.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today I stand strong as a mayor, feeling good, very
confident,'' Milan said. ''Yesterday was the first time I was down,
but I was back up three hours later.''
</P>
<P>
   Milan's civil attorney, Carlos Morcate, was in the mayor's
fivesome.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it says a lot a lot about his spirit, that he showed
up,'' said Morcate, one of the witnesses who appeared before the
grand jury that indicted Milan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
