<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Camden's faulty financial practices could force state takeover  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- State overseers on Friday gave Mayor Milton
Milan's administration two weeks to correct long-standing improper
financial practices or face consequences that could include a state
takeover.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement came a day after Milan was indicted on charges
that include extortion, money laundering and mail fraud.
Authorities say Milan accepted payoffs and gifts from city
contractors and took bribes from organized crime figures.
</P>
<P>
   Although the state's poorest city does not meet any of the legal
requirements for a takeover, Department of Community Affairs
Commissioner Jane Kenny said she asked the attorney general for
''options'' if the deadline is not met.
</P>
<P>
   ''State takeover is one of the options. If the city doesn't
comply with the deadline, it's one of the options we can look at,''
Kenny said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Camden does not keep proper financial records, including a
general ledger and an account of city payouts, all of which are
required by state law, Kenny said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny said she could withhold $13.4 million in state aid that
Camden needs to balance its budget. Without that aid, the city
would fail to meet its payroll and other obligations, Kenny said.
It also would then meet one of the legal criteria to have the state
assume city operations, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have been unwilling to withhold financial aid from the city
of Camden for obvious reasons,'' Kenny said.
</P>
<P>
   Since July city finances have been scrutinized by a state review
board. But that oversight committee was only appointed after Milan
threatened to file for bankruptcy and shut down city services.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State DeForest B. Soaries, Jr. said city officials
have ignored any help offered by the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''But stonewalling has been in large measure the option they
have chosen,'' Soaries said.
</P>
<P>
   Milan rejected any talk of a takeover and said the state should
aid his city by bringing in more businesses. Gov. Christie Whitman
should allow a $20 million fund designated for the Camden
waterfront to be used throughout the city, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor, if she wanted to help, she wouldn't be taking us
to the grindstone with the damn financial review board,'' Milan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny and Soaries joined Camden County Prosecutor Lee Solomon in
a meeting with representatives of Camden's nonprofit social
services. Solomon's office is supervising Camden's police
department.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting was to assure those groups that the state would
continue to fund programs and help them provide services, Kenny
said.
</P>
<P>
   That assurance is needed now, Soaries said, because the city's
financial plight is ''exacerbated by the chaos caused by the
indictments at City Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenny said the public needed to know ''we are not abandoning
Camden.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the state does not assume city operations, Kenny said
her office will take action if officials fail again to make the
corrections.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are going to do something,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-31-00 1838 </TRAILER>
