<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Blair Reappoints Bluebloods to Lords  </HEADLINE>
By MAUREEN JOHNSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Just months after expelling aristocrats from the
House of Lords, Labor Prime Minister Tony Blair has reappointed a
clutch of bluebloods to Britain's upper chamber, while the
Conservatives gave a title to a billionaire tax exile who is a
major party donor.
</P>
<P>
   The appointments sparked renewed calls Friday for the Lords to
be elected or chosen by an independent commission, rather than
appointed by the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-member list of new peers announced Thursday -- including
20 Laborites -- revived charges that Blair is packing the chamber
with cronies, and that opposition Conservatives exchanged a peerage
for cash.
</P>
<P>
   ''This sort of thing contaminates the honors system,'' said
Labor lawmaker Tony Wright, chairman of an all-party constitutional
committee.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Blair expelled about 600 peers with inherited
titles of nobility, and the Lords now mainly consist of commoners
given lifetime titles. Their power is restricted to delaying
legislation for up to one year.
</P>
<P>
   A blue-ribbon committee recommended in January that the new
House of Lords be mainly chosen by an independent commission.
Blair, who pledged to completely reform the body after Labor came
to power in 1997, has not said whether he will accept the
recommendations.
</P>
<P>
   Also Friday, critics said a title was given to expatriate
Michael Ashcroft in reward for his $4.8 million in donations to the
Conservative party, some of whose own members criticized the
appointment.
</P>
<P>
   ''Cash for coronets has plumbed new depths,'' sniped Labor
legislator Peter Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft, currently based in Belize, has lived outside Britain
for 15 years. The Conservative party treasurer, he was refused a
peerage last year because of concerns over his business dealings.
</P>
<P>
   ''It reminds me of the way medieval popes made their nephews
into cardinals,'' said Viscount Cranborne, the Conservatives'
former Leader of the Lords, said of his appointment.
</P>
<P>
   However, officials announced Thursday that Ashcroft would be
made a baron if he returns to live in Britain. Cranborne said it
was unprecedented to grant a peerage with conditions attached.
</P>
<P>
   Menzies Campbell, a spokesman for the Liberal Democrat party,
said Ashcroft's peerage was further proof that Britain needs an
elected second chamber.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rules would not have been bent if Mr. Ashcroft had not
been a 3 million (pound) supporter'' of the Conservatives, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Tory leader in the upper house, Lord Strathclyde, accused
Labor of making a fuss to divert attention from Blair's
''stuffing'' the House with his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Ashcroft said he was ''both thrilled and honored.'' He is
expected to announce within days that he is stepping down as United
Nations ambassador for Belize as the first step toward taking up
the peerage. He said he would come back to Britain by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   With the new appointments, the 701-member Lords will have 236
Tories and 202 Laborites. Most of the rest are independents or
belong to other parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 1843 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
