<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Yemen President Leaves Conference  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RACHMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Yemen's president abruptly left a conference
here Friday after being asked about allowing Israelis to visit the
Arabian Peninsula nation, event organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   A Yemeni diplomat did answer the question, but then he and
President Ali Abdullah Saleh walked out of the luncheon meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''The first question he got was to clarify the policy on
Israelis and Jews coming to Yemen,'' said organizer Hadass Tesher.
''Then everybody left.''
</P>
<P>
   Yemeni Ambassador to the United Nations Abdalla Ashtal
acknowledged there was controversy over the issue of allowing the
thousands of Jews of Yemeni origin to return to their ancestral
homes. But he insisted that nothing out of the ordinary happened at
the luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   ''The president didn't storm out,'' Ashtal said. ''He just left
a little early.''
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Cohen, a senior analyst with the Washington-based Center
for Middle East Peace and Economic Cooperation, which organized the
conference, said the Yemeni diplomats had dealt with the sensitive
issue, and did not want to return to it.
</P>
<P>
   The conference attended by policy experts dealt with Yemen's
role in the Mideast peace process and its relations with the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   A briefing for journalists after the luncheon was canceled.
Cohen blamed organizational confusion.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1950s, most of the 50,000 Jews living in Yemen
emigrated to the new state of Israel. They left behind synagogues
and property in impoverished Yemen, which now has a Jewish
population of about 400.
</P>
<P>
   Yemen has said it will not establish ties with Israel before an
overall Middle East settlement is in place. Yemen allows Israeli
Jews of Yemeni descent to visit, provided they have special travel
documents, Ashtal said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of Jews returning to Yemen was inflamed this week when
a dozen Israelis, including politicians and theologians, went there
for a four-day visit but were ignored by senior officials. The
group had hoped to be considered an official delegation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
