<HEADLINE> Custody Deal in Switched Babies Case  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL TOLME, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAFFORD, Va. (AP) -- A judge signed a custody agreement Friday
that ended a legal struggle between the families of two girls
switched at birth at the University of Virginia Medical Center in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   No family members attended the hearing where Stafford Circuit
Judge James W. Haley Jr. signed the agreement announced last week.
Under the settlement, the 4-year-old girls will remain with the
families who have been raising them and both sides will have
regular visitation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this is far and away the best disposition of this
case,'' Haley said, complimenting lawyers for both families.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Johnson agreed to drop her effort to adopt Rebecca
Chittum, her biological daughter. Johnson will continue raising
Callie Conley and became the girl's legal guardian.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the closest thing to being a mommy without adoption,''
said Kenneth Mergenthal, a lawyer for Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was sent home from the state-operated hospital in
Charlottesville with Callie, the biological daughter of a Buena
Vista couple, Kevin Chittum and Whitney Rogers. Chittum and Rogers
took home Johnson's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   The switch was discovered in July 1998 when DNA tests were
performed in a child-support dispute between Johnson and her
ex-boyfriend, Carlton Conley. That same month, Chittum and Rogers
died in a car crash without ever learning of the switch. Their
parents have taken turns caring for Rebecca.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
