<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Falls Sharply Against Yen  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The yen jumped against other currencies Friday,
reaching its highest level against the dollar since the beginning
of the year, on expectations that Japan may report strong economic
data on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   In late trading in New York, the dollar was quoted at 102.64
Japanese yen, down sharply from 105.46 on Thursday. It was the
yen's highest level since Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The sharp move came as currency traders anticipated a strong
reading of Japanese business sentiment when the Bank of Japan
releases its quarterly survey on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The report, known by its Japanese abbreviation of Tankan, is
closely watched by economists as an indicator of future business
activity. If it shows a long-awaited improvement in sentiment, it
could lift hopes for a turnaround in Japan's sluggish economy.
</P>
<P>
   Previous upward jolts in the yen have been met with market
intervention by Japan's central bank, which sees an overly strong
yen as a threat to Japan's economy. A high yen cuts down the
profits of large Japanese companies like Sony, which rely heavily
on overseas markets for their sales.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Japan was not seen to be intervening in markets
Friday, but that could change on Monday if the Tankan report comes
in with strong numbers, traders said.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar was less changed against other currencies, trading at
1.6643 Swiss francs, up from 1.6576, and 1.4499 Canadian dollars,
down from 1.4554.
</P>
<P>
   The euro was quoted at 95.59 cents, down from 96.13 cents, and
the British pound fell to $1.5934 from $1.5954.
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
Based on Friday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.0458 German
marks, up from 2.0348; 6.8615 French francs, up-down from 6.8244;
and 2,025.39 Italian lire, up from 2,014.43.
</P>
</TEXT>
