<HEADLINE> FEC Awards Round of Matching Funds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The seven presidential candidates will receive
$5.9 million in the latest round of government matching funds --
more than half going to Sen. John McCain, the Federal Election
Commission announced Friday.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who suspended his presidential campaign after the Super
Tuesday primaries March 7, will receive $3.7 million from the
government, a sign of his fund-raising strength after he won the
New Hampshire primary in February. That brought his total to $10.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore will receive another $718,485, bringing
his total to $13.1 million. Former U.S. Sen. Bill Bradley, who has
abandoned his campaign, will receive another $849,553, bringing his
total to $12.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government matches the first $250 of each individual
contribution for candidates who agree to limit their total primary
spending to $40.5 million. Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who has
raised a record $75 million, is not accepting federal funds and can
spend as much as he can raise in his GOP presidential bid.
</P>
<P>
   Two third-party candidates also are receiving federal funds.
</P>
<P>
   The FEC said that Patrick Buchanan, seeking the Reform Party
nomination, will get $174,185, bringing his total to $3.3 million,
and John Hagelin of the Natural Law Party will get $100,000, his
first installment of federal funds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
