<HEADLINE> Al-Amin Extradition Hearing Set  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) -- Jamil Abdullah Al-Amin, the 1960s black
militant formerly known as H. Rap Brown, will remain jailed for at
least three weeks until his extradition hearing, a judge said
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Montgomery County Circuit Judge Charles Price set the hearing
for April 21. Alabama officials have agreed to send Al-Amin to
Georgia in the slaying of a deputy in Atlanta; Al-Amin's attorney
has promised to fight it.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney J.L. Chestnut has alleged Al-Amin was framed by
organized crime and corrupt law enforcement in Atlanta after he
tried to stop prostitution in a black community. Chestnut said
after Friday's hearing he hasn't revealed ''what is really at the
bottom of this,'' but he would not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin, 56, is charged with murder and assault in the March 16
shooting of two Atlanta sheriff's deputies who were attempting to
serve him with a warrant. Both deputies were wounded; Kinchen later
died.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Amin was apprehended four days after the shooting in rural
Lowndes County, west of Montgomery.
</P>
</TEXT>
