<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N.C. Candidates Get Free Air Time  </HEADLINE>
By MELINDA DESLATTE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Four North Carolina TV stations Saturday
will begin airing free, two-minute spots in which the state's five
leading gubernatorial candidates answer issues-oriented questions.
</P>
<P>
   They join a handful of outlets nationwide heeding a White House
commission's call to furnish free air time to candidates before
primaries and general elections.
</P>
<P>
   Capitol Broadcasting Co. will run three issue messages every day
in April, leading up to the May 2 primary, on its four stations --
WRAL in Raleigh, WJZY in Charlotte, WRAZ in Durham and WILM in
Wilmington. Each candidate filmed three segments that will be
rotated throughout the month during morning, evening and late-night
newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bottom line is we just don't think issues get out there
enough. It seems they get overshadowed by negative commercials,''
said John Harris, director of special programming of WRAL, who
helped develop the format.
</P>
<P>
   The Alliance for Better Campaigns said 25 stations nationwide
plan to offer similar spots to candidates this year. Supporters
also say free air time could reduce the influence of money on
campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   The five candidates -- Democrats Dennis Wicker and Mike Easley
and Republicans Leo Daughtry, Chuck Neely and Richard Vinroot --
were required to devote one TV spot to the lottery and another to a
childhood education program. They were allowed to choose any
subject for the third spot, with one condition -- no attacks on the
other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The stations plan to repeat the format in October, before the
general election.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Goodmon, president and CEO of Capitol Broadcasting, served
on the 22-member White House commission that recommended in 1998
that TV stations donate five minutes of air time to candidates in
the month before primaries and general elections.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the industry has ignored the proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
