<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bakeries May Be Banks in Brazil  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) -- A proposal approved by the government
this week could have Brazilians depositing their dough at the same
place they buy their bread.
</P>
<P>
   The National Monetary Council has signed off on a Central Bank
resolution that allows commercial banks to farm out a number of
day-to-day banking operations -- from opening up savings accounts
to applying for loans -- to general businesses, the Central Bank
press office said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal is part of a national de-bureaucratization program
the government hopes will help shrink lines at bank agencies and
serve residents who live in neighborhoods that do not have a bank,
the Central Bank said.
</P>
<P>
   Though bakeries, pharmacies and other traditional, neighborhood
businesses may fit the profile, the details of the measure remained
to be hammered out, a Central Bank press secretary said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
