<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 19:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zions Shareholders Reject Deal  </HEADLINE>
By HANNAH WOLFSON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Zions Bancorp. shareholders voted down a
proposed merger with First Security Corp. on Friday, killing a $3.4
billion deal that had been fast losing support.
</P>
<P>
   After a tepid statement of support for the merger from Zions
president and CEO Harris Simmons, shareholders representing 45
percent of the outstanding shares voted against the plan. Just over
33 percent voted for it.
</P>
<P>
   ''If nothing else, this meeting today was a great demonstration
of corporate democracy,'' Simmons said. ''It's a meeting we'll sure
long remember.'' He had no further comment immediately after the
votes were tallied.
</P>
<P>
   The vote is a blow to First Security, whose shareholders
approved their half of the agreement last week. The plan called for
First Security shareholders to receive .442 shares in the combined
company for each of their shares; Zions shareholders would have
gotten one share in the combined company for each share they own.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not surprised at all,'' said Eric Reim, a market analyst
with U.S. Bancorp Piper Jaffray in Minneapolis. ''I think what the
vote reflected was the shareholders' belief that the way this deal
was structured and with what has transpired, it did not make
economic sense to Zions shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the word from the investment banking firm Goldman,
Sachs Group Inc., which announced in March it no longer considered
the deal fair to Zions' shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   Originally worth $5.9 billion when it was announced in June, the
deal's value had dropped to about $3.4 billion. Much of the drop
came in early March, when First Security panicked investors with an
announcement that first-quarter earnings were expected to drop by
as much as 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Based its closing stock price Friday, First Security has a
market value of about $2.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think that what probably turned the tide on the no vote was
the institutional investors, who were more swayed by the Goldman
Sachs letter,'' said George Paulson, a Zions shareholder who voted
against the merger.
</P>
<P>
   First Security spokeswoman Jackelin Slack said the company was
''disappointed'' that the Zions' shareholders voted against the
merger and was studying its options.
</P>
<P>
   One possibility is the threat of litigation, which was raised by
one First Security investor during Friday's meeting. Simmons said
they do not expect a lawsuit from First Security's management, but
could not rule out litigation altogether.
</P>
<P>
   The failure could leave either bank open to a takeover attempt
from an outside bank. Reim said First Security, with its declining
revenue base, is more vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Bank managers are expected to try to renegotiate the terms of
the merger with a stock ratio more favorable to Zions. In the
meantime, it is unclear what effect Friday's votes will have on
operations at Utah's two largest banks, which had already started
to consolidate some departments and sell off redundant branches as
ordered by regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Zions closed trading on the Nasdaq up $3.31\ at $41.62{. First
Security closed up 25 cents at $12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
