<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Third child comes forward to accuse dentist of breaking bones  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNION CITY, N.J. (AP) -- Prosecutors have decided not to charge a
dentist accused of breaking a 5-year-old's leg while performing a
root canal on the wrong tooth.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by the Hudson County Prosecutor's Office comes as a
third child came forward to accuse Kevin Ward of breaking one of
her bones. Heather Franks said her thumb was broken seven years ago
when the then-9-year-old girl came into Ward's Maywood office to
get a cavity filled.
</P>
<P>
   Ward faces two lawsuits, one filed this week, related to the
other alleged incidents but no disciplinary action from the state
board that regulates dentists.
</P>
<P>
   The state Board of Dentistry did suspend Ward's license for a
year in 1987 and ordered him to seek training in administering
anesthesia three years after a 4-year-old boy died in his care. The
board later stayed the suspension, however, letting Ward continue
to practice.
</P>
<P>
   Ward has lost two part-time jobs at Maywood and Vernon since the
latest charges against him but continues to work at the Children's
Dental Center in Union City.
</P>
<P>
   His office, surrounded by a purple stone fence and filled with
photographs of Easter bunnies, was full of children on Friday. A
technician said Ward would not comment. His lawyer, Vincent
Loughlin, has not returned repeated telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Hudson County Prosecutor Terrence Hull said the office
decided this week against charging Ward with aggravated assault for
breaking Mario Rivero's leg on Feb. 21.
</P>
<P>
   Ward gave an explanation of how the injury occurred and
prosecutors, after consulting with a doctor, concluded that Ward
didn't intentionally hurt the North Bergen boy, Hull said.
</P>
<P>
   The office did forward results of the investigation to the state
Attorney General's Office, which oversees the dentistry board, Hull
said. A spokesman from the office didn't return a telephone call on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Ward pressed down on Mario Rivero's leg so hard that he broke
the right femur after Mario kicked the dentist in the head in pain,
Rivero's parents said. The boy has spent three weeks in traction,
in a cast from his chest down, and has had nightmares, said the
family's lawyer, Leonard Altamura.
</P>
<P>
   Ward was also performing a root canal on the wrong tooth, said
Altamura, who filed a lawsuit against Ward on the family's behalf
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Altamura said he doesn't know whether Ward intended to break
Rivero's leg, but said, ''This is not the first time. This is not
the second time. This is the third time.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He is recklessly negligent, outrageously negligent. He should
not be practicing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ward also faces a lawsuit from Cathy Candelieri, the mother of
Amanda Schwab, who was 4 when her wrist was broken at Ward's Vernon
office in 1996. Police never pressed criminal charges, saying the
broken bone was an accident.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Franks, now 16, visited Ward on Nov. 1, 1993, for a
filling, Maywood police said in a report obtained by The Record of
Hackensack. She said she became upset when Ward put something in
her mouth and tried to get up, but was restrained by Ward and an
assistant, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Ward told police he restrained Heather out of concern for his
and her safety after he injected her with Novocain and ''she had an
anxiety attack,'' the police report said.
</P>
<P>
   Police also interviewed Ward's assistant, Marylim Rivera, who
said that she held Heather's legs while Ward held her hands down
and covered her mouth after she began kicking and throwing her arms
around. Rivera described the restraint as ''normal procedure when
you have a child who acts up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-03-31-00 1946 </TRAILER>
