<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kidnap Suspect Pleads Innocent  </HEADLINE>
By GLORIA PEREZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALMOLOYA DE JUAREZ, Mexico (AP) -- A suspect described as one of
Mexico's ''most sought kidnappers'' pleaded innocent to an array of
charges Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am simply a jewelry merchant and I am innocent on all
charges,'' Marcos Tinoco told a judge during arraignment at
Mexico's top security federal prison west of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   But prosecutors told a news conference Thursday that Tinoco used
a law school education and personal charm to gather information on
at least 11 wealthy victims -- most of them Jews -- whom he
kidnapped. In at least one case, he sliced off a victim's finger to
force ransom.
</P>
<P>
   Tinoco, 42, was arrested this week while driving in the upscale
Polanco neighborhood of Mexico City.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the attorney general's organized crime unit, Jose
Trinidad Larrieta, said Thursday that Tinoco was ''one of the
most-sought kidnappers'' and he led ''the most active and dangerous
criminal organization'' today.
</P>
<P>
   Formal charges lodged against him so far include organized crime
and possession of illegal firearms.
</P>
<P>
   ''The majority of his kidnappings last only a few hours,''
Larrieta said, calling Tinoco the king of rapid kidnappings.
</P>
<P>
   But on one occasion, he said, a victim was held for 18 days. A
finger was sliced off and sent to the victim's family.
</P>
<P>
   Ransoms ranged from $38,000 to $650,000, Larrieta said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Tinoco used his legal training to intimidate victims.
The suspect ''created false arrest orders which he showed to his
victims to make them believe there really was a judicial order
against them,'' Larrieta said.
</P>
<P>
   The capture of Tinoco is one in a series of triumphs over famed
kidnapping gangs by federal officials -- though daily newspapers
from around Mexico still often carry reports of new abductions.
</P>
<P>
   The most dramatic arrest was the August 1998 capture of Daniel
Arizmendi, who was notorious for sending victims' ears to their
families. He is now serving a 50-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Larrieta said police were investigating a possible link between
Tinoco and one of Mexico's most famous drug smugglers, the
now-imprisoned and convicted Hector Palma. He said one of the
victims was held at a house owned by a brother of Palma.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
