<HEADLINE> Bahamas Govt. Allows Kennedy Visit  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASSAU, Bahamas (AP) -- Despite the governing party's threat to
keep him out, U.S. environmental activist Robert F. Kennedy Jr.
arrived in the Bahamas on Friday to speak out against a
controversial development project.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy will address a town meeting Saturday on plans to build
the gated Clifton Cay housing development on New Providence Island.
He will leave Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy secretary general of the governing Free National
Movement party, Oswald Marshall, had warned Kennedy not to come,
hinting that the government would ''put Mr. Kennedy on the
(immigration) stop list for working illegally in the Bahamas.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Missouri Sherman-Peter, permanent secretary of the
Ministry of Foreign Affairs, said Friday her agency would not stop
Kennedy from entering the Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, a staff attorney for the Natural Resources Defense
Council, has campaigned against the project, which he says would
destroy historic sites, harm coral reefs and strip sand from
beaches in the area known as Clifton.
</P>
