<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, March 31, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japanese Volcano Erupts Again
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DATE, Japan (AP) -- A volcano in northern Japan erupted again on Saturday, a
day after it sent a spectacular blue-gray plume of molten rock and ash billowing
two miles above the crater and rolling down the snow-quilted slopes. There were
no immediate reports of damage or injuries from either eruption. Ash dusted
silent, evacuated villages near Mount Usu. Snow fell Friday evening and the
military was called in because of concerns over the possibility of landslides or
mudslides caused by melting runoff.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
N. Carolina Looks To Shield Tobacco
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- North Carolina, the nation's No. 1 tobacco producer,
will convene a special legislative session Wednesday to shield cigarette makers
from the crippling effects of a possible $300 billion verdict in Florida. The
special protection rankles anti-tobacco forces and troubles some constitutional
law scholars. But proponents, including the governor, say it is an economic
necessity in North Carolina, where tobacco generates nearly $1 billion for
farmers and where 114,000 people are employed in tobacco-related jobs.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Elian's Dad Infuriated by Process
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A senior Cuban official today said Elian Gonzalez's father is
infuriated by the pace of efforts to reclaim his son as U.S. authorities delay a
deadline to revoke the Miami relatives' custody of the boy. The U.S. Immigration
and Naturalization Service determined on Jan. 5 that Juan Miguel Gonzalez should
be reunited with his son and was the only one who had the right to speak for
him. In Miami, Elian's relatives today said they would let the boy's father
visit him at their Little Havana home, but that they are no longer willing to
give the 6-year-old refugee to Juan Miguel Gonzalez if he comes to the United
States to await the outcome of their court appeal.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ugandan Death Toll Passes Jonestown
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- The death toll in the doomsday sect massacre in
southwestern Uganda was raised Friday to 924, surpassing the 1978 Jonestown
tragedy in Guyana as the worst modern-day cult-related mass killing. Ugandan
authorities promised to apprehend the perpetrators of the stabbings, burnings
and stranglings. But investigators showed no signs of being able to track down
sect leaders or even of being able to confirm which -- if any -- survived. The
government called a day of prayer Sunday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Panel Probes Judge in Clinton Case
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A special panel is beginning an investigation of the chief
federal judge in the District of Columbia because she assigned six Whitewater
and campaign fund-raising prosecutions to Clinton appointees. Appeals Judge
Stephen Williams chose four judges -- three Republicans and a Clinton appointee
-- to help him delve into why Chief U.S. District Judge Norma Holloway Johnson
bypassed the computerized system of randomly assigning cases.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Medicare Caps Out-of-Pocket Costs
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Medicare announced new rules today that will limit older
Americans' out-of-pocket costs for hospital outpatient services. The change,
which starts July 1, will cap Medicare copayments for services received in
hospital-owned outpatient care centers -- such as one-day surgery, radiology and
rehabilitation therapy -- at a maximum equivalent to the program's inpatient
hospital deductible. That's $776 this year.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
drkoop.com in Poor Health
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Drkoop.com, the health information Web site started by
former Surgeon General C. Everett Koop, has been losing so much money that its
auditors doubt that it can stay in business. Release of the auditors' letter by
PricewaterhouseCoopers in drkoop.com's annual report late yesterday sent the
already beaten-down shares of the company crashing an additional 41 percent
today. Other consumer-oriented Internet sites that are in trouble include music
retailer CDNow Inc. and grocer Peapod, both of which are unprofitable.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 58.33, Nasdaq Up 114.70
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks edged back from the brink today, but the
Dow industrials closed down 58.33 at 10,921.92. Advancing issues on the New York
Stock Exchange led decliners 2,017-1,073. The Nasdaq was up 114.70 at 4,572.59.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Kuerten Beats Agassi at Ericsson
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KEY BISCAYNE, Fla. (AP) -- Hampered by a mild sprain in his right ankle,
Andre Agassi limped out the Ericsson Open with a 6-1, 6-4 loss to Brazil's
Gustavo Kuerten in the semifinals. Kuerten's upset spoiled a potential
Agassi-Pete Sampras showdown in Sunday's final. Sampras, seeded second, was to
play No. 14 Lleyton Hewitt in the other semifinal tonight.
</P>
