<HEADLINE> Texas Tax Break on Medicine To Begin  </HEADLINE>
By JIM VERTUNO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- A state sales tax break on some 100,000
over-the-counter medicines and medical products takes effect
Saturday and includes condoms, despite opposition from Gov. George
W. Bush and other conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   The tax break could save families about $17 per year, the
comptroller's office reported. It is projected to cost the state
about $160 million in sales tax revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Items exempted from the 6.25 percent state sales tax and local
taxes will include allergy treatments, bandages, cough and cold
remedies, vitamins and minerals and many others. Prescription drugs
have been tax-free in Texas since 1961.
</P>
<P>
   ''These are items we all need,'' said state Sen. Rodney Ellis,
who helped write the law.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to include condoms on the list of exempted
medicines was made by Republican Comptroller Carole Keeton
Rylander, who said the law dictates what items are tax-free.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature specified the tax break should cover any product
that has a National Drug Code number issued by the Food and Drug
Administration and is used to diagnose, treat or prevent disease
and suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not a matter of interpretation, it's a matter of the
law,'' said Rylander spokesman Mark Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who has said abstinence should be promoted to teen-agers,
proposed the tax break in his 1998 re-election campaign but never
wanted condoms included, said his spokesman, Mike Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a small factor in a very beneficial law,'' Jones said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 2006 </TRAILER>
