<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bennett Founders Claim Downfall Plot  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   UTICA, N.Y. (AP) -- The founders of the bankrupt Bennett Funding
Group, accused of swindling investors in one of the nation's
largest pyramid schemes, claim the company's court-appointed
trustee engineered their downfall to steal their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund T. and Kathleen Bennett filed a suit that seeks $5.8
billion in damages and Richard Breeden's removal as trustee.
</P>
<P>
   Breeden was chairman of the U.S. Securities Exchange Commission
until 1993, when the agency initiated a fraud investigation into
the Bennett empire of hotels, resort financing and investments in
race tracks and gambling enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC filed a civil complaint in 1996 alleging the group
cheated more than 21,000 creditors, including banks and elderly
investors, out of more than $1 billion by selling bogus leases.
</P>
<P>
   Edmund and Kathleen Bennett were never charged, but their sons,
Michael and Patrick, were accused of swindling investors out of
more than $700 million through their business that financed leases
for office equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Bennett pleaded guilty in 1998 to conspiracy,
obstruction of justice and perjury and faces a maximum of 15 years
in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Bennett, convicted last year on 49 charges, was told
Friday by a federal judge that he will serve 20 years in prison if
he gives all of his assets to investors who were cheated in the
scam. Otherwise, the judge warned, he will serve 30 years.
</P>
<P>
   In the lawsuit filed Wednesday, the elder Bennetts claim Breeden
manipulated and falsified their companies' books to make the
companies seem insolvent, then orchestrated the federal
investigation and used his influence to gain control.
</P>
<P>
   Breeden has not yet seen the Bennett's lawsuit and had no
immediate comment, said attorney Gary Mucci. The Bennetts have
leveled the same accusations previously and Breeden has denied
them.
</P>
<P>
   The suit was filed in response to four lawsuits filed by Breeden
seeking the return of $5.8 billion to the companies, the couple
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 2007 </TRAILER>
