<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Director Mendes Returns To Stage  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- After his first venture into movies garnered him
an Oscar for best director, Sam Mendes is headed back to the stage
-- and Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   ''I felt like it was time to do Shakespeare again,'' Mendes said
Friday, sitting in the tiny London theater he has run for nearly 10
years.
</P>
<P>
   The acclaimed theater director has been offered countless movies
following his success with ''American Beauty,'' his first-ever
film. But in July, he will start rehearsals for a new production of
the enduring Shakespeare comedy ''Twelfth Night.''
</P>
<P>
   The show will run Sept. 14-Nov. 25 in the 251-seat Donmar
Warehouse in London's Covent Garden district.
</P>
<P>
   Mendes, 34, said he now expects to switch back and forth between
theater and film. To that end, he started up Donmar Films several
months ago with funding from DreamWorks, the Hollywood studio that
made ''American Beauty.''
</P>
<P>
   Steven Spielberg's recently launched studio is to contribute
$160,000 a year to the theater and $400,000 a year to Mendes'
start-up film company for the next several years.
</P>
<P>
   Mendes said he's unlikely even to begin preparing another film
before the end of the year, pointing to fellow filmmakers Frank
Darabont (''The Green Mile'') and Anthony Minghella (''The Talented
Mr. Ripley'') as just two directors who take a long time between
projects.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, he made clear he had more immediate concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Upon returning from Los Angeles with his Oscar, he entered his
north London flat and, before he knew it, the boiler had blown up.
</P>
<P>
   ''Things like that,'' he said, ''really bring you down to
earth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
