<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Police: Man Slams Child to Ground  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A man muttering ''My savior, my
savior'' killed his 1{-year-old son by slamming him to the pavement
Friday, then swung the limp body at officers as they tried to
arrest him, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene Hulum, 25, was taken to the state hospital for a
psychiatric evaluation. He was later charged with capital murder.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses told police that Hulum left his apartment with the
child, Marquis, in his arms and twice smashed him to the ground in
the parking lot, police spokesman Terry Hastings said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm thinking he's playing with that child, but he's killing
him,'' said Anthony Farmer, 24. ''That baby didn't have a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   With the body slung over his shoulder, Hulum was confronted by
three police officers. Holding the child by one leg, Hulum swung
the body at the officers, hitting one in the head with it, before
being wrestled to the ground, police said. Police used pepper spray
to subdue him.
</P>
<P>
   Hulum had left his 4-year-old daughter behind in the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The children's mother was at work at the time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 2025 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000331.0247 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Denial of McVeigh Appeal Urged  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER (AP) -- Saying the legal system did not fail Timothy
McVeigh, federal prosecutors on Friday opposed his death row appeal
and request for new trial.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our legal system provided McVeigh a multimillion dollar
defense team to advocate his interests before an impartial judge
and jury selected far from the site of his deadly crime,'' Sean
Connelly, special attorney to the U.S. Attorney General wrote in a
brief filed in federal court Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In his second attempt to have his conviction and death sentence
overturned, McVeigh claimed his lawyer, Stephen Jones, failed to
provide adequate representation. McVeigh claims Jones leaked
inflammatory stories about him to the media, including a purported
confession, had a book deal in the works and had a conflict of
interest by becoming friends with Susan Ferrell's parents.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrell was one of 168 people killed in the April 19, 1995,
bombing of the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building.
</P>
<P>
   McVeigh also claimed some jurors were not honest in their
answers at jury selection and said the government suppressed
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Connelly dismissed those claims in his argument.
</P>
<P>
   ''McVeigh sits on death row not because our legal system failed
him but rather because his guilt was proven fairly beyond any
reasonable doubt and his crime cried out for the ultimate
punishment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McVeigh lost his first appeal last year when the U.S. Supreme
Court refused to hear arguments that his trial was tainted by jury
misconduct and news reports that he confessed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 2041 </TRAILER>
