<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000331.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> SUBDIVIDED </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, March 31, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japanese Volcano Erupts Again
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DATE, Japan (AP) -- A day after it sent a spectacular blue-gray plume of
molten rock and ash billowing two miles above villages near Mount Usu, a volcano
in northern Japan erupted again. While ash dusted silent, evacuated villages,
there were no immediate reports of damage or injuries from either Friday's or
Saturday's eruption. Snow fell Friday evening and the military was called in
because of concerns over the possibility of landslides or mudslides caused by
melting runoff.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Putin Urges START II Ratification
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- President Vladimir Putin called Friday for the quick
ratification by Russia of the START II nuclear arms reduction treaty, an accord
that has been stalled for years by hard-liners and communists in parliament. It
was his first major policy statement since being elected. Putin also called on
parliament to make even deeper cuts in atomic missiles, a signal that he wants
good relations with the West after recent tensions and unpredictability under
Boris Yeltsin. Putin stopped short, however, of addressing the most sensitive
nuclear arms issue between Moscow and Washington -- the U.S. desire to modify
the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Delays Anger Elian's Father
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A senior Cuban official today said Elian Gonzalez's father is
infuriated by the pace of efforts to reclaim his son as U.S. authorities delay a
deadline to revoke the Miami relatives' custody of the boy. The U.S. Immigration
and Naturalization Service determined on Jan. 5 that Juan Miguel Gonzalez should
be reunited with his son and was the only one who had the right to speak for
him. In Miami, Elian's relatives today said they would let the boy's father
visit him at their Little Havana home, but that they are no longer willing to
give the 6-year-old refugee to Juan Miguel Gonzalez if he comes to the United
States to await the outcome of their court appeal.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Men Said To Focus on White House Bid
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Polls released today found women are slightly less likely
than men to be interested in the presidential campaign and more likely to be
dissatisfied with politics. But women also are more likely than men to believe
the election will make a difference in their lives, according to the surveys for
Harvard University's Joan Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics and Public
Policy.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Medicare Caps Out-of-Pocket Costs
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Medicare announced new rules today that will limit older
Americans' out-of-pocket costs for hospital outpatient services. The change,
which starts July 1, will cap Medicare copayments for services received in
hospital-owned outpatient care centers -- such as one-day surgery, radiology and
rehabilitation therapy -- at a maximum equivalent to the program's inpatient
hospital deductible. That's $776 this year.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ugandan Death Toll Passes Jonestown
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- The death toll in the doomsday sect massacre in
southwestern Uganda was raised Friday to 924, surpassing the 1978 Jonestown
tragedy in Guyana as the worst modern-day cult-related mass killing. Ugandan
authorities promised to apprehend the perpetrators of the stabbings, burnings
and stranglings. But investigators showed no signs of being able to track down
sect leaders or even of being able to confirm which -- if any -- survived. The
government called a day of prayer Sunday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Xerox To Cut 5,200 Jobs
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Business machines giant Xerox Corp. said today it was
cutting 5,200 jobs, or 5 percent of its work force, saying it can ''no longer
operate business as usual and expect to win.'' Xerox said it was narrowing its
focus to two core markets: business machines such as copiers for home and
medium-sized offices, and larger documents systems for big corporations. In
1998, the company took a $1.1 billion charge and cut about 9,000 jobs in another
reorganization.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 58.33, Nasdaq Up 114.94
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks edged back from the brink today, but the
Dow industrials closed down 58.33 at 10,921.92. Advancing issues on the New York
Stock Exchange led decliners 2,017-1,073. The Nasdaq was up 114.94 at 4,572.83.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Atlanta Hawks' Coach Wants To Stay
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   ATLANTA (AP) -- Atlanta Hawks coach Lenny Wilkens told his players today to
ignore rumors that this might be his last season. ''I've got a lot of basketball
games left in me,'' Wilkens said. ''If they don't want me here, they'll have to
tell me that.'' Wilkens, 62, has two full seasons left on a five-year contract.
But the Hawks (26-45) have their worst record through 71 games since the
franchise moved to Atlanta in 1968.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
