<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 21:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Md. House Panel Approves Gun Bill  </HEADLINE>
By SETH HETTENA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) -- A measure that would make Maryland the
first state to require built-in locks on handguns breezed through a
House committee Friday, with members not changing so much as a
comma on the legislative session's most controversial bill.
</P>
<P>
   The vote was 14-7 in favor of the bill, which would require
internal locks on all new handguns sold in Maryland, beginning in
2003.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which has already passed the Senate, is up for a
vote before the full House as early as Monday. If it passes without
amendments, the bill goes to the desk of Democratic Gov. Parris
Glendening, who is eager to sign it.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are making history in the state of Maryland,'' Glendening
said after the vote. He said the vote sent a strong message:
''Maryland will stand up to the NRA, Maryland will do what is
necessary to protect our children, Maryland will make our
communities safer and Maryland will set a new, national standard
for gun safety.''
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the bill prohibits anyone convicted of a
violent crime as a juvenile from possessing a handgun until age 30
and requires gun manufacturers to provide a ballistic fingerprint
of shell casings of all new guns. It also imposes five-year
mandatory minimum sentences on some convicted felons caught with a
handgun.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans tried nine times Friday night to amend the bill,
which would have sent the measure back to the Senate, where
opponents might have been able to kill it with a filibuster. But
the six Republicans and lone Democrat who opposed the bill were
easily outnumbered by the rest of the committee.
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the bill was flawed, pointing out that the
definition of a built-in gun lock was so vague that the safety
levers already found on most firearms would qualify. Some
supporters agreed, but said there was not enough time to fix the
problems, with little more than a week remaining in the 2000
legislative session.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-03-31-00 2117 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
