<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
''Brother Asaiah'' Bates
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOMER, Alaska (AP) -- ''Brother Asaiah'' Bates, who founded a
commune on Kachemak Bay and later was elected to city council, died
Monday of heart problems. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   Bates said his World War II experience was the reason he devoted
himself to peace. He served in the South Pacific as a nose gunner
on a bomber.
</P>
<P>
   Bates found a messianic leader in California named Krishna Venta
who taught that mankind came to Earth in 12 rocket ships powered by
cosmic energy, that man has 110 interconnecting senses and that
one's negative thoughts are registered on the bodies of others.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1950s, Bates and other disciples established the Wisdom
Knowledge Faith Love commune at the head of Kachemak Bay. The
movement fizzled after Venta was killed by two excommunicated
followers in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Bates moved to Homer where he was elected to the Homer City
Council and joined the Chamber of Commerce. He became a janitor for
the phone company.
</P>
<P>
Jay Baumgardner
</P>
<P>
   BRISTOL, Tenn. (AP) -- Jay Baumgardner, a three-time Tennessee
senior amateur golf champion, died Thursday of an apparent heart
attack. He was 65.
</P>
<P>
   Baumgardner was state senior amateur champion in 1993, 1994 and
1996 and was Tennessee Senior Amateur Player of the Year in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He was ranked as one of the top 10 senior amateur golfers in the
country by Golf Digest in 1993.
</P>
<P>
Gisele Freund
</P>
<P>
   PARIS (AP) -- Gisele Freund, whose photographs captured the
attitudes of France's Left Bank literary elite, died Friday of a
heart attack. She was 91.
</P>
<P>
   Freund was one of Europe's most prominent photographers and
became a pillar among French feminist intellectuals after settling
in Paris in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   She met militant feminist writer Adrienne Monnier while browsing
at La Maison des Amis du Livre, Monnier's book shop on the Left
Bank. The shop was frequented by Jean-Paul Sartre, Simone de
Beauvoir, James Joyce and Ernest Hemingway.
</P>
<P>
   Monnier became her lifelong mentor and companion, introducing
her to the Parisian intellectual set and encouraging her to pursue
photography.
</P>
<P>
   In 1935, Freund executed an acclaimed series of photographs
documenting the misery of British coal miners, and met Andre
Malraux. Her portrait of the author of ''Man's Fate'' -- wrapped in
a trench coat with a cigarette dangling from his mouth -- is among
her most well-known photographs.
</P>
<P>
   Freund specialized in conveying attitudes focusing on hands,
body posture and clothing. Some of her most famous photographs were
published in Life and Time magazines.
</P>
<P>
Kenneth Charles Jones
</P>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Kenneth Charles Jones, a longtime Las Vegas Sun
photographer who covered famous Las Vegas visitors and everyday
residents, died Thursday. He was 86.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years he covered famous events and famous people,
including first lady Eleanor Roosevelt, President Kennedy and Elvis
Presley. Twenty years ago he shot aerial photographs of the tragic
MGM hotel fire that killed 87 and injured hundreds.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' first newspaper job was for the Evening Record and the
Courier-Tribune, which served Kent and Ravenna, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, seven children, nine grandchildren,
10 great grandchildren, and two great-great grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
Carol Ann Lewis
</P>
<P>
   GERING, Neb. (AP) -- Carol Ann Lewis, who owned and operated the
Gering Courier with her husband, Jack, for more than 40 years, died
Thursday. She was 65.
</P>
<P>
   Her grandfather, A.B. Wood, started the Courier in 1887. After
he became terminally ill in 1945, her father, Warren Wood, took
over the business.
</P>
<P>
   The Lewises sold the paper in April 1999 to Robert Van Vleet,
owner of the Sidney Daily Sun. The Omaha World-Herald Co. purchased
the Courier from Van Vleet last month.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis belonged to the Daughters of the American Revolution,
served on the Gering School Board, and was a former chairwoman of
the community's annual Oregon Trail Days.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
