<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 21:54 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wizards 104, Celtics 102  </HEADLINE>
By HOWARD ULMAN, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- Mitch Richmond's 16-foot jumper with two-tenths of
a second left gave the Washington Wizards a 104-102 win and sent
the Boston Celtics to their sixth straight loss Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   After a free throw by Don Reid put the Wizards ahead 102-100,
Vitaly Potapenko tied the game with a turnaround jumper with 14
seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Whitney then brought the ball upcourt for Washington as
Richmond, who had 30 points, sprinted around to get free. He got
the ball on the left side and lofted the winning shot over Tony
Battie's raised left arm.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics inbounded the ball, but the buzzer sounded before
Paul Pierce could attempt a shot.
</P>
<P>
   Boston rebounded somewhat from its worst loss of the season,
122-87 in Orlando on Tuesday night, a setback marred by on-court
bickering among some of its players. Coach Rick Pitino said he
would make ''major suspensions'' but took no punitive action.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics never trailed Friday until Aaron Williams converted
an offensive rebound for a 95-94 Wizards lead with 5:55 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hamilton added 20 points for Washington, which has been
eliminated from playoff contention. Antoine Walker had 21 points
and 14 rebounds and Pierce added 18 points for Boston.
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics fell to 30-42, assuring their third losing record in
Pitino's three seasons as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Boston suffered its third close loss in its current slide. In
the first two games, Anthony Peeler's 3-pointer at the buzzer gave
Minnesota a 109-106 win, and Aaron McKie's basket with no time left
in the first overtime sparked Philadelphia to a 117-115 victory.
</P>
<P>
   After trailing 97-96 with 4:34 left, the Celtics went ahead
100-97 on baskets by Walker and Battie. Then Juwan Howard hit a
foul-line jumper and a driving bank shot, putting the Wizards in
front 101-100 with 51 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Boston had taken an 83-82 lead into the fourth quarter and went
ahead 94-91 on Dana Barros' 3-pointer. Then Washington took its
first lead on consecutive baskets by Reid and Williams.
</P>
<P>
   After trailing 60-46, the Wizards finished the half with an 11-2
surge with Richmond scoring the last five points on a 3-pointer and
two free throws. That cut Boston's lead to 62-57 at halftime. It
was down to 83-82 with one quarter left.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Boston had won five of its previous six home games. ...
Washington is 6-2 in its last eight games. ... On the final play,
Boston's first inbounds pass hit the backboard and went out of
bounds without anyone touching it. The officials then conferred at
midcourt as the Wizards headed for their locker room, and referee
Bennett Salvatore waved them back for a do-over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
