<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, March 31, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Delays Anger Elian's Father
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- A senior Cuban official today said Elian Gonzalez's father is
infuriated by the pace of efforts to reclaim his son. The U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service determined on Jan. 5 that Juan Miguel Gonzalez should be
reunited with Elian and was the only one who had the right to speak for him. But
the INS has twice moved back deadlines to revoke temporary custody of the
6-year-old refugee by Miami relatives pending more negotiations. In Miami,
Elian's relatives today said they would let Gonzalez visit him at their Little
Havana home, but that they are no longer willing to give the 6-year-old refugee
to his father if he comes to the United States to await the outcome of their
court appeal.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mich. Boy Denies Shooting Classmate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. (AP) -- A 6-year-old boy denied today that he shot classmate
Kayla Rolland to death and blamed another first-grader. Little more than his
eyes and nose were visible over the witness stand. The boy testified at a
preliminary hearing for Jamelle James, 19, who is accused of carelessly storing
the semiautomatic handgun that the 6-year-old allegedly found and used to kill
Kayla on Feb. 29. James is charged with involuntary manslaughter; the 6-year-old
isn't charged.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japanese Volcano Erupts Again
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DATE, Japan (AP) -- A day after it sent a spectacular blue-gray plume of
molten rock and ash billowing two miles above villages near Mount Usu, a volcano
in northern Japan erupted again. While ash dusted silent, evacuated villages,
there were no immediate reports of damage or injuries from either Friday's or
Saturday's eruption. Snow fell Friday evening and the military was called in
because of concerns over the possibility of landslides or mudslides caused by
melting runoff.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Putin Urges START II Ratification
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- President Vladimir Putin called Friday for the quick
ratification by Russia of the START II nuclear arms reduction treaty, an accord
that has been stalled for years by hard-liners and communists in parliament. It
was his first major policy statement since being elected. Putin also called on
parliament to make even deeper cuts in atomic missiles, a signal that he wants
good relations with the West after recent tensions and unpredictability under
Boris Yeltsin. Putin stopped short, however, of addressing the most sensitive
nuclear arms issue between Moscow and Washington -- the U.S. desire to modify
the Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Ugandan Death Toll Passes Jonestown
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) -- The death toll in the doomsday sect massacre in
southwestern Uganda was raised Friday to 924, surpassing the 1978 Jonestown
tragedy in Guyana as the worst modern-day cult-related mass killing. Ugandan
authorities promised to apprehend the perpetrators of the stabbings, burnings
and stranglings. But investigators showed no signs of being able to track down
sect leaders or even of being able to confirm which -- if any -- survived. The
government called a day of prayer Sunday.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Upholds ATM Fee Ruling
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A federal appeals court today ruled the cities of Santa
Monica and San Francisco cannot enforce their bans on extra ATM fees while a
challenge to the laws is pending. The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld a
preliminary injunction issued in November by U.S. District Judge Vaughn Walker
against the fee-banning ordinances. Banks say they need the surcharges to pay
for expanding their ATM networks. Consumer organizations say the fees merely pad
the profits of banks that have been closing branches and laying off tellers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Xerox To Shred 5,200 Jobs
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Business machines giant Xerox Corp. said today it was
cutting 5,200 jobs, or 5 percent of its work force. Xerox said it was narrowing
its focus to two core markets: business machines such as copiers for home and
medium-sized offices, and larger documents systems for big corporations. In
1998, the company took a $1.1 billion charge and cut about 9,000 jobs in another
reorganization.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 58.33, Nasdaq Up 114.94
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks edged back from the brink today, and the
Nasdaq was up 114.94 at 4,572.83, even though it finished the week 9.4 percent
below its March 10 record high close. The Dow industrials closed down 58.33 at
10,921.92. Advancing issues on the New York Stock Exchange led decliners
2,017-1,073.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tennessee Beats Rutgers 64-54
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- After being frustrated most of the game, Tennessee went
ahead to stay with a key second-half surge and beat Rutgers 64-54 tonight during
an NCAA Final Four women's basketball matchup, giving the Lady Vols a chance to
win their seventh national championship. National player of the year Tamika
Catchings picked it up after scoring just two points in the first half and
freshman Kara Lawson hit two big shots to lead Tennessee (33-3) into Sunday
night's title game. The Lady Vols will play Connecticut or Penn State, who met
in tonight's second semifinal.
</P>
