<DOCNO> APW20000331.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 22:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricanes 3, Sabres 1  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Paul Coffey's power-play goal with 7:34
left lifted the Carolina Hurricanes to a 3-1 victory over the
Buffalo Sabres on Friday night and into a tie for eighth place in
the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Hill sealed the win, scoring into an open net with 4.9
seconds remaining. Paul Ranheim also scored for the Hurricanes, who
jumped ahead of the Sabres in the standings and caught the idle
Montreal Canadiens in the race for the conference's final playoff
berth.
</P>
<P>
   Vaclav Varada scored for the Sabres, who had a four-game winning
streak come to an end. After averaging more than four goals in
their last seven games, the Sabres managed only 20 shots -- six in
the final 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes have four games left, including a season-ending
home-and-home series against the expansion Atlanta Thrashers.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres have five games left, starting with Saturday's game
at Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Coffey carried the puck into the Sabres zone and, using Buffalo
defenseman Richard Smehlik as a screen, wristed a low shot that
deflected in off goalie Dominik Hasek's stick.
</P>
<P>
   The goal came with Varada in the penalty box for interference,
the Hurricanes' seventh power-play opportunity of the game, and
fourth straight called against the Sabres.
</P>
<P>
   Varada, with his season-high eighth goal, opened the scoring
deflecting in Rhett Warrener's point shot over goalie Arturs Irbe's
shoulder 32 seconds into the second period.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes replied at the 11:41 mark when Hasek misplayed
Bates Battaglia's shot from a poor angle. Hasek allowed the puck to
deflect off his stick and into the crease, allowing Ranheim to
stuff it in.
</P>
<P>
   For Ranheim, it was his ninth goal of the season and first in 27
games.
</P>
<P>
   Hasek made up for it three minutes later when, without his
stick, he blocked Paul Coffey's hard shot and then managed to knock
down Andrei Kovalenko's chip-in attempt from in close.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres, meanwhile, hit two goal posts, including Varada who
beat Irbe through the legs only to have the puck ring off then far
right post with 9:15 left in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Sabres' Doug Gilmour had a seven-game point streak snapped, the
first time he's failed to record at least a point since joining
Buffalo in a deal with Chicago. Despite battling a stomach virus,
which has caused him to lose seven pounds, Gilmour played a regular
shift.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes were missing All-Star Sami Kapanen, who missed
his second game because of concussion-like symptoms.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
