<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-03-31 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 17 injured as casino-bound minibus rear-ends truck on Garden StateParkway  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   GALLOWAY TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) -- Seventeen people were injured
Friday when a minibus taking gamblers to an Atlantic City casino
rear-ended a truck on the Garden State Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   Two were hospitalized in critical condition. The others suffered
minor injuries, state police said.
</P>
<P>
   The wreck shut down a four-mile section of the parkway for about
two hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Lucky Strike Travel Service Inc. minibus, with 17 people
aboard, left from New York's Chinatown section and was bound for
Bally's Park Place Casino Hotel when the accident occurred about 10
miles northwest of Atlantic City, Trooper Barry Saul said.
</P>
<P>
   The driver, Guang Zhi Chi, 29, of Brooklyn, N.Y., told police
that he was in the right lane on the southbound side of the parkway
when he pulled out to pass a slower-moving vehicle, Saul said.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling between 60 mph and 70 mph, the minibus rammed the rear
of a P.J. Gillespie Inc. concrete products truck in the left lane.
Truck driver Michael Colaneri, 61, of Millville and passenger
Robert Diaz, age unavailable, of Millville, suffered minor
injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The speed limit on that section of the parkway is 65 mph. Police
did not know how fast the truck was traveling.
</P>
<P>
   The gamblers were mostly in their 60s and 70s, but one was 17
years old.
</P>
<P>
   ''People were all over the floor, screaming, making all sorts of
noises,'' said the 17-year-old, who was treated for minor injuries
at Atlantic City Medical Center's Mainland Division. ''Smoke was
coming out of the front of the bus. It was crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Kwai Chan, 70, of New York, was listed in critical condition at
Atlantic City Medical Center. Another bus passenger, Cabiano Pineda
Jr., 60, of Long Island, also was in critical condition, a
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Chi, whose air bag deployed, was unhurt. One passenger declined
medical treatment. Chi will be cited either for careless driving,
following too closely or making an unsafe lane change, Saul said.
</P>
<P>
   The impact of the crash ripped the front section of the 24-seat
minibus off and shattered the windshield. Clothing, shoes, hunks of
metal and glass were strewn about the accident scene.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic backed up for more than two miles as State Police,
ambulance crews, firetrucks and a State Police helicopter tended to
the victims and cleaned up the highway.
</P>
<P>
   A Lucky Strike official defended his driver.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's very reliable,'' said Charlie Lee, assistant manager at
Lucky Strike Travel Service Inc., of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Chi had been driving for the company for about four years and
had had one previous accident recently, but no one was hurt in it,
Lee said. The status of his New York license wasn't clear Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Motor Vehicles had no record for Chi's name,
as spelled by New Jersey State Police and his Lucky Strike
supervisor. But a man named Zhi Juang Cai, also of Brooklyn, N.Y.,
and with the same June 28, 1970 birthday, has a valid commercial
driver's license despite a 1998 conviction for running a red light,
Motor Vehicles spokesman Joseph Picchi said.
</P>
<P>
   Lucky Strike operates up to a dozen round-trip excursions a day
between Chinatown and Bally's Park Place Casino Hotel in Atlantic
City, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   The truck's rear window was broken, but it suffered little
visible damage.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's not a lot of damage to it, but boy, that bus is
totaled,'' said Dennis Gillespie, whose father owns it, as he
surveyed the damage at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first serious accident involving a bus bound for an
Atlantic City casino this year, according to Sgt. Al Della Fave, a
spokesman for the State Police. The number of crashes this year was
not immediately available Friday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a rash of accidents involving casino buses in 1998
and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 24, 1998, eight people were killed when a Bruins
Transportation bus skidded off the parkway and plunged down an
embankment. Three days later, a bus returning to New York lost
control in Edison and struck a tree, injuring 31 people.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, a bus hit a bridge abutment on the Garden State
Parkway in Wall Township, injuring 11 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
