<HEADLINE> School Shooting Suspect Enters Plea  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONYERS, Ga. (AP) -- A teen-ager pleaded not guilty by reason of
insanity Friday to charges that he wounded six of his high school
classmates during a shooting spree in May.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, lawyers for T.J. Solomon acknowledged that he
opened fire with a .22-caliber rifle, wounding six Heritage High
classmates.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have never disputed that the shots were fired by Mr.
Solomon,'' defense attorney Jana Harris said earlier this month.
''The depths of his illness, the circumstances surrounding the case
-- these are the things that will be looked at the trial.''
</P>
<P>
   A trial is scheduled for June 15, but is likely to be postponed
for several months.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon, who has been in juvenile detention since his arrest,
could be sentenced to life in prison if convicted on all counts. If
a jury found Solomon not guilty by reason of insanity, he could be
institutionalized or freed.
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Solomon, 15 at the time of the shooting, opened
fire in a crowded hall area at Heritage, exactly one month after
the rampage in Littleton, Colo., that left 14 students and a
teacher dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
