<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Helms Likely To Get UN Invite Again  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- After swapping visits with members of the
U.N. Security Council, Sen. Jesse Helms is likely to get another
invitation to New York to continue the new dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the conservative North Carolina Republican is one of
the harshest critics of the United Nations, Security Council
members believe the two meetings have started the long process of
improving Washington's frayed relationship with the world body.
</P>
<P>
   Bangladesh's U.N. Ambassador Anwarul Chowdhury, the current
council president, told a news conference Friday that all 15
council members found the exchange of views at Thursday's meeting
in Washington to be important.
</P>
<P>
   ''We thought that this is a good beginning. The senators are
interested in continuing this dialogue. They're interested in
visiting us. They are interested also in receiving us again from
time to time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think there is ... a willingness to receive them here in the
near future,'' Chowdhury said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's visit to the Capitol didn't resolve the dispute over
U.S. arrears to the United Nations -- which the United Nations says
now total $1.7 billion. And at a 2{-hour roundtable, ambassador
after ambassador criticized a host of Helms-mandated conditions the
world body must meet before Washington pays up.
</P>
<P>
   But many U.N. envoys said the mood Thursday were better than
that during the first meeting in January when Helms addressed the
Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the mood shift is significant,'' British Ambassador
Jeremy Greenstock said. ''The substance shift is not yet there --
but one thing leads to another.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
