<HEADLINE> Friday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teen-ager Found Guilty of Second-Degree Murder
</P>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- The teenage girl charged with
killing 14-year-old Reena Virk was found guilty of second-degree
murder Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Ellard's mouth dropped open and she began crying quietly
after she heard the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother began sobbing as Ellard wiped tears away with her
sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   The British Columbia Supreme jury began deliberating Wednesday
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Virk's murder stunned the country and sparked numerous debates
about female teen violence.
</P>
<P>
   During two weeks of testimony the court heard from 10 teenagers
who said Ellard, 17, bragged about the killing in November 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ellard denied any part in the killing when she testified. She
had only met Virk that night and had no reason to kill her.
</P>
<P>
   Ellard is the last of eight teens to go to trial for Virk's
death.
Judge Grants Robert Baltovich Bail Pending Appeal
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- Robert Baltovich emerged from prison Friday on a
quest to officially join the growing ranks of Canada's wrongfully
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   Shrieks of joy echoed in the courthouse halls as appeal court
Justice Marc Rosenberg granted the 34-year-old's request for bail
pending the appeal of his 1992 conviction in the murder of his
girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, eight years to the day after he was first convicted
of killing Elizabeth Bain, Baltovich was greeted warmly by
applauding friends and family as he strolled out of custody.
</P>
<P>
   Baltovich then made his way down busy University Avenue to the
offices of lawyer James Lockyer, who will spend the next year
preparing his client's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   There have been at least six high-profile cases of wrongful
conviction in recent years, including Guy Paul Morin, David
Milgaard and Donald Marshall.
Ken Murray Trial Will Start
</P>
<P>
   ST. CATHARINES, Ontario (AP) -- The trial of Ken Murray, one-time
lawyer for sex killer Paul Bernardo, on obstruction of justice
charges will go ahead despite his lawyer's arguments that the
matter took too long to get to court.
</P>
<P>
   Murray closed his eyes and shook his head as Justice Patrick
Gravely ruled he did not face an unreasonable delay in the 38
months it took for the case, dealing with his handling of the
notorious Bernardo tapes, to get to trial. Murray held on to the
tapes for 17 months before handing them over to authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''Generally, everything that could be done was done in moving
this case expeditiously to trial,'' Gravely told Superior Court.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's lawyer, Austin Cooper, had argued to have the charges
dropped, saying Murray's constitutional rights were infringed
because of the delay.
Prime Minister Chretien Announces 900 Call Center Jobs
</P>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Nova Scotia (AP) -- Prime Minister Jean Chretien swooped
into hard-luck Cape Breton Friday, announcing up to 900 call center
jobs thanks in part to a $13-million contribution from the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is patronage at its best,'' said the prime minister,
brushing aside criticism that the package is an attempt to buy
votes in a region where the federal Liberals have no
representation.
</P>
<P>
   ''We take public money to make sure it is going in areas where
it is needed. And those who will benefit are the people of Cape
Breton.''
</P>
<P>
   But Chretien acknowledged that won't affect hundreds of coal
miners who are facing the loss of their jobs when Ottawa gets out
of the coal business later this year.
</P>
<P>
   The impending shutdown of the Cape Breton Development Corp., or
Devco, has provoked emotional demonstrations for more than a year.
Canadians Will Have Extra 24 Hours To File Tax Returns
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Canadians will have an extra 24 hours to file
their income tax returns on time.
</P>
<P>
   The deadline has been extended to midnight on May 1 instead of
April 30, which is a Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Many Revenue offices will be open until midnight that day, said
Revenue Minister Martin Cauchon, and some postal outlets.
</P>
</TEXT>
