<HEADLINE> Arizona's Williams To Have Surgery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- All-Star third baseman Matt Williams will undergo
surgery Saturday to have a metal plate placed in his broken right
foot.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Diamondbacks said the surgery would not alter the
timetable for Williams' recovery and will allow him to do
conditioning work, such as riding a stationary bicycle or other
activity that requires him to put weight on the foot, before the
break is healed.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery will be performed by team foot specialist Peter
Mitchell and team physician David Zeman.
</P>
<P>
   Williams broke the second metatarsal when he fouled a pitch off
the foot Tuesday in an exhibition game against Seattle in Tucson.
</P>
<P>
   He is expected to miss at least the first five weeks of the
season. Williams broke the same bone in 1995 and was sidelined for
68 games. However, that was a displaced break that required surgery
to insert pins in the bone. Williams has said that he tried to come
back too soon from that injury, and ended up fracturing the bone
again.
</P>
</TEXT>
