<HEADLINE> Boston's Pena Out With Hurt Elbow  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Promising young right-hander Juan Pena will be
lost for the season with a torn medial collateral ligament in his
elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Pena was sent to Boston from Florida on Thursday after
experiencing pain in the elbow during pre-game warmups. Team
physician William Morgan confirmed the torn MCL in an examination
Friday and said surgery would be required.
</P>
<P>
   The rehabilitation is expected to take 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old pitcher was told by manager Jimy Williams on
Wednesday that he would not be in the starting rotation but would
be a long-inning reliever. Brian Rose beat out Pena for the fifth
starting spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox believe that the injury occurred when Pena was
struck by Sean Casey's line drive on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Pena was 2-0 in two starts with an 0.69 ERA for Boston last
season after being called up from Triple-A Pawtucket. This spring,
Pena was 2-2 with a 1.64 ERA in 16 2-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Pena's spot in the bullpen is expected to be taken by
27-year-old right-hander Nerio Rodriguez, who was claimed on
waivers from the New York Mets. Rodriguez has a career 4-6 record
in the majors with a 6.49 ERA in stints with Baltimore and Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Rodriguez was 10-8 with a 4.54 ERA in 27 starts for
Triple-A Syracuse. He was 0-1 with a 13.50 ERA in two relief
appearances for Toronto.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
