<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EST  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Friday, March 31, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Delays Anger Elian's Father
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Elian Gonzalez's father is infuriated by the pace of efforts to
reclaim his son as U.S. authorities delay a deadline to revoke the Miami
relatives' custody of the boy, a senior Cuban official said today. The INS has
twice moved back deadlines to revoke the relative's temporary custody pending
more negotiations. In Miami, Elian's relatives today said they would let
Gonzalez visit him at their Little Havana home, but that they are no longer
willing to give the 6-year-old refugee to his father if he comes to the United
States to await the outcome of their court appeal.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Mich. Boy Denies Shooting Classmate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   FLINT, Mich. (AP) -- A 6-year-old boy denied today that he shot classmate
Kayla Rolland to death and blamed another first-grader. Little more than his
eyes and nose were visible over the witness stand. The boy testified at a
preliminary hearing for Jamelle James, 19, who is accused of carelessly storing
the semiautomatic handgun that the 6-year-old allegedly found and used to kill
Kayla on Feb. 29. James is charged with involuntary manslaughter; the 6-year-old
isn't charged.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tensions Rise Over Zimbabwe Farms
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- Civic groups and opposition parties were warned by
police Friday to call off a scheduled peace march as tensions worsened here over
black war veterans' occupation of white-owned farmland. The unrest began in
February, when veterans armed with spears, axes, clubs and guns smashed their
way into white farmers' homesteads and seized their spreads. President Robert
Mugabe has called the occupation a justifiable political protest against the
descendants of white settlers who ruled here during the colonial era. Police
have refused to evict the squatters.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japanese Volcano Erupts Again
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   DATE, Japan (AP) -- A day after it sent a spectacular blue-gray plume of
molten rock and ash billowing two miles above villages near Mount Usu, a volcano
in northern Japan erupted again. While ash dusted silent, evacuated villages,
there were no immediate reports of damage or injuries from either Friday's or
Saturday's eruption. Snow fell Friday evening and the military was called in
because of concerns over the possibility of landslides or mudslides caused by
melting runoff.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Farmers Shy Away From Biotech Crops
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Farmers are turning away from genetically engineered
crops, especially a biotech corn that's toxic to insects, amid consumer
resistance that started overseas and is now being felt in the United States.
Plantings of the gene-altered corn are projected to drop 24 percent this year,
according to findings of an Agriculture Department survey released Friday. The
biotech corn became especially controversial last year after a Cornell
University study suggested it could be killing Monarch butterflies.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Xerox To Shred 5,200 Jobs
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Business machines giant Xerox Corp. said today it was
cutting 5,200 jobs, or 5 percent of its work force. Xerox said it was narrowing
its focus to two core markets: business machines such as copiers for home and
medium-sized offices, and larger documents systems for big corporations. In
1998, the company took a $1.1 billion charge and cut about 9,000 jobs in another
reorganization.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Income, Spending Both Rose in Feb.
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- American consumers, the driving force behind the
supercharged economy, spent with abandon in February at a pace more than double
their income growth. It dragged the personal savings rate to a record low.
Economists said Friday's report shows that the Federal Reserve has not finished
raising interest rates to slow the economy and keep inflation from becoming a
problem.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Dow Ends Down 58.33, Nasdaq Up 114.94
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Technology stocks edged back from the brink today, and the
Nasdaq was up 114.94 at 4,572.83, even though it finished the week 9.4 percent
below its March 10 record high close. The Dow industrials closed down 58.33 at
10,921.92. Advancing issues on the New York Stock Exchange led decliners
2,017-1,073.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tennessee Beats Rutgers 64-54
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- After a rough start, Tennessee pulled ahead with a key
second-half surge and beat Rutgers 64-54 tonight during an NCAA Final Four
women's basketball matchup, giving the Lady Vols a chance to win their seventh
national championship. National player of the year Tamika Catchings picked it up
after scoring just two points in the first half and freshman Kara Lawson hit two
big shots to lead Tennessee (33-3) into Sunday night's title game. The Lady Vols
will play Connecticut or Penn State, who met in tonight's second semifinal.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by BRAD FOSS
</SUBHEAD>
</TEXT>
